column2: 75G Grilled Chicken With Stir Fry Veggies

column18: chicken
column24:
INGREDIENTS
For stir fry vegetables
1tsp Olive oil/ Sesame oil/ ghee
¼ cup roughly chopped Mushroom
1-2 sliced baby corns  (Optional)
¼ cup thin long sliced Carrot
¼ cup French Beans
¼ Steam cooked broccoli or cauliflower
½  cup Capsicum (red, yellow & green of your choice)
½ cup Zucchini (Optional)
1tbsp soy sauce
¼ tsp Vinegar
1 sliced red chill
2 to 3 basil leaves or Coriander leaves 
1 tbsp black and white sesame seeds mix  (Optional)
Salt (to taste)
1/2 tsp Pepper Powder
For Grilled Chicken
1 lemon’s juice
½  tsp Olive oil
4 tbsp Curd OR Greek Yogurt
1 tsp dried Oregano
2-3 cloves garlic
½ tsp Black Pepper
1 tsp Salt
1 green chilli
150g Skinless Chicken Breast
column25:
METHOD FOR STIR FRY VEGGIES
Take the oil in a non-stick pan. Heat up a little
 Add all of the vegetables.
Stir fry for a while
In a cup add Soy sauce, vinegar, with all the spices. Make a slurry
Evenly spread the slurry over the veggies
Cook for a while
Sprinkle the sesame seeds
Toss around the vegetables for a while and they are done!
 METHOD FOR GRILLED CHICKEN
Pound the chicken using a meat mallet or rolling pin
Mix all the ingredients in a mixing bowl except chicken and whisk them together.
Add pounded chicken and leave it to marinate for 20-25 minutes.
On a grilling pan, brush a little amount of oil and place the marinated chicken pieces.
Grill them completely
Sprinkle sesame seeds over them and serve with stir fry veggies

column24:
1 cup Parboiled rice
  1/4 cup Rice raw
 1/2 cup Split black gram flour (urad dal ka atta) skinless 
1/2 cup Fenugreek seeds (methi dana) 
 Salt to taste
column25:
1.Place the half boiled rice and raw rice in a deep bowl and wash them 2-3 times. Drain off water and then soak in 3 cups water for at least 5-6 hours.               
2.Wash and soak the gram with the fenugreek seeds in 1 cup water for at least 2-3 hours.
3.Drain the gram, raw rice and fenugreek seeds and place in a blender. Grind it with ½ cup water to a smooth and spongy batter. Transfer into a deep bowl.
4.Drain the parboiled rice and place in the same blender. Grind with 1 cup water, to make a slightly coarse batter. Transfer this into the same deep bowl.
5.Add salt and mix both the batters with hand. Mix thoroughly in brisk whipping motions so as to aerate the batter well. The batter should have a dropping consistency.
6.Keep the bowl covered with a tight lid in a warm place overnight to ferment.
7.Use as required.

column24:
INGREDIENTS
1/4 cups oats
1 tsp oil (For brushing the idli pan)
½  tsp mustard seeds
1 tsp chana dal
1 tsp urad dal
1/2 tsp turmeric powder
1 Green chilli
¼ cup carrot , finely chopped
1tbsp coriander leaves , chopped
A pinch of salt
¼ cup curd
A pinch of fruit salt
column25:
METHOD
Take  oats in a pan and dry roast them for about 5 minutes until golden brown.
Let it cool down and then grind to make it a powder.
In a broad pan heat oil over medium flame.
Add mustard seeds to it and let them crackle.
Now add chana and urad dal, turmeric powder and green chillis. Mix well and saute until light brown.
Add the chopped carrots and coriander leaves. Combine all the dry ingredients except oats powder thoroughly along with a pinch of salt and cook for a minute or two.
Let the mixture cool down for few minutes and then grind them all together before adding into idli batter.
Transfer the prepared oats powder to a large bowl.
In this add salt and the fried mixture. Combine well.
Now add the required quantity of curd and stir thoroughly in one direction adding a pinch of fruit salt to it.
Prepare a medium thick batter and leave it covered for few minutes.
Now grease the idli moulds with ghee using a brush.
Pour the prepared oats idli batter in each mould and put it in the steamer.
Cover with a lid and steam for about 15 minutes over medium flame.
After 15 minutes check whether the idlis are properly cooked.
The tasty and healthy oats idli is ready to serve with coconut chutney or sambhar

column25:
1. Heat 3 cups water in a non-stick pan. Add salt and rice, mix, cover and cook on medium heat till rice is half cooked. Strain the excess water and spread rice evenly onto a plate.
2. Heat ghee in a non-stick pan. Add cumin seeds and sauté till fragrant. Add cooked rice and sprinkle coriander leaves and toss to mix. Add salt and sprinkle some water, toss to mix, cover and cook for 4-5 minutes
. 3. Serve hot garnished with a coriander sprig.

column24:
Brown rice: 1/3 cup (60 gms)
Water: 4 cups
Pink Himalayan Salt as needed
column25:
Soak brown rice for 15 mins
boil water and add salt
add in brown rice, when water boils, put the flame on medium and cook for 15 mins.
Strain the water and keep the rice to a strainer
-----Note---- Cooking rice and straining the rice is the traditional method of cooking rice in Asia and some parts of South India. It also helps to cut down exposure to arsenic.

column24:
1 cup quinoa 
2 tablespoons oil 
½ teaspoon mustard seeds
 8-10 curry leaves
 2 medium  fresh onions, chopped 
¼ teaspoon turmeric powder 
2 green fresh chillies,
 Finely chopped 2 small potatoes, boiled, peeled and cut into cubes
 Salt to taste 
2 tablespoons roasted and crushed peanuts 
1 tablespoon finely chopped fresh coriander
 2 tablespoons scraped and cut fresh coconut
column25:
1. Rinse the quinoa well. Transfer the quinoa in to the deep nonstick pan. Add  some water. Boil the quinoa . Cover and and cook on low heat for eighteen to twenty minutes.
 2. Heat oil in a nonstick pan. Add the mustard seeds. Once they start to splutter, add curry leaves and sauté for a few seconds. 
3. Add the fresh onions and stir them  till golden brown. Add turmeric powder, green chillies and mix well.
 4. Add boiled potatoes and mix well. Add the cooked quinoa, salt and mix well. 
5. Take the pan off from the gas. Transfer in a serving bowl. 
6. Add roasted peanuts, coriander and coconut and serve hot.

column24:
Flattened rice(Poha)-100 gm (2 cup)
Peanuts (moongfali/shingdana)-50 gm (1/2 cup)
Chopped onion-2 (medium)
Green chilli (slit)-2 to 3
Lemon juice-2 tbsp
Curry leaves-15 to 17
Cumin seeds-1/2 tsp
Mustard seeds-1/2 tsp
Sugar-1/2 tsp (optional)
Turmeric powder-1/3 tsp
Cooking oil-3 to 4 tbsp
Chopped coriander leaves
Aloo bhujiya/ sev for garnish (optional)
Salt to taste
column25:
1. Wash the poha with running water and leave it for 10 minutes.
2. Roast the peanuts on low-medium flame for 2-3 minutes and keep it aside.
3. Heat a pan, add oil and let it heat properly.
4. Add cumin seeds, mustard seeds, green chilli and curry leaves and fry it for a few seconds.
5. Add sugar and mix it, add onions and fry it for 2-3 minutes on medium flame.
6. Add turmeric powder, mix it and cook it for a minute.
7. Add roasted peanuts, washed poha and salt, mix it properly.
8. Cover the pan and cook it for a minute on low flame.
9. Add lemon juice and coriander leaves, mix it and cover the pan, cook it for a minute on low flame.
10. Turn off the flame, garnish it with aloo bhujiya/sev and lemon slices.
11. Maharashtrian kanda poha is ready to serve.

column24:
FOR DOSA BATTER:
 2 cup idli rice
 ½ cup urad dal
 ½ tsp methi / fenugreek
 1 cup poha / aval / flattened rice, thin
 water, for soaking & grinding
 2 tsp salt
 oil, for roasting
FOR MIX VEG TOPPING:
 1 onion, finely chopped
 1 carrot, grated
 ½ capsicum, finely chopped
 1 to mato, finely chopped
 1 inch ginger, finely chopped
 1 chilli, finely chopped
 few curry leaves, chopped
 2 tbsp coriander, finely chopped
 ¼ tsp salt
column25:
firstly, in a large bowl take 2 cup idli rice, ½ cup urad dal and ½ tsp methi.
soak for 5 hours adding water as required.
drain off the water and transfer to the mixi or grinder.
blend to smooth paste in batches adding water as required.
in a bowl take 1 cup poha and rinse well.
blend to smooth paste adding water if required.
mix the rice-urad dal batter and poha paste well.
cover and ferment in a warm place for 8 hours.
after 8 hours, the batter has doubled in size. mix gently without disturbing the air bubbles.
further add 2 tsp salt and mix well.
prepare the vegetable topping by taking 1 onion, 1 carrot, ½ capsicum and 1 tomato.
also add 1 inch ginger, 1 chilli, few curry leaves, 2 tbsp coriander and ¼ tsp salt.
mix well making sure everything is well combined.
heat the griddle and pour a ladleful of batter.
spread out in a circular motion slightly thick than regular masala dosa.
top with mix vegetable mixture uniformly and pat slightly.
also pour 1 tsp oil around the edges.
cover and roast the dosa to a golden brown from the bottom.
flip over and roast both sides.
finally, enjoy mixed vegetable uttapam with chutney

column24:
Healthy Version of Dosa with no oil and with brown rice

1. Dosa Batter: 

Brown Rice - 2 Cups
Black Lentils-1/2 Cup
Chana Dal - 1/4 Cup
Beaten Brown Rice-1/4 Cup
Yoghurt - 1 Cup

2. Masala Preparation:

Grated Carrot - 1 Cup
Boiled & Mashed Kabuli Chana - 1 cup
Roasted Peanuts-1/4 Cup
Chopped Onions-1 Cup 
Finely Chopped Green Chilies - 4 Nos.
Curry Leaves-1/4 Cup
Mint Leaves- 10-12 
Cilantro-1/2 Cup
Lemon - 1 big size

3.Chutney:

Chopped Raw Coconut - 1 Cup
Roasted Peanuts-1/4 Cup
Putana or roasted chickpea lentil- 1 Cup
Green Chilies-3 Nos.



Preparation: (In four steps)
column25:
Step:1 Batter

1. Soak the brown rice, black grams, split chickpeas and beaten 
    rice in a bowl for over 10-12 hours

2. Grind the soaked grains into a fine batter 8-10 hours after    
    soaking.

3. Add a cup of Yogurt in the batter and let it ferment for 10-12    
    hours.

Step:2 Masala

1. Dry roast the Curry leaves, chopped onions and green chilies on 
    a    nonstick pan.

2. Add boiled & mashed Kabuli chana and roasted peanuts & saute.

3. Add Yogurt with little water and let it cook for 10 minutes.

4. Add chopped Cilantro just before removing it from the flame.

5. Once cooked take it in a bowl and lemon juice in it.

Step:3 Chutney

1. Grind the chopped Raw Cocnunt & 3 green chilies
2. Add roasted peanuts and putana (roasted split chickpeas) adding     

   yogurt with some water and grind 

Step:4 Dosa

1. Heat Non-stick Dosa Pan, sprinkle little water and pour batter on   

   pan and rotate the ladle in a circular motion in clockwise          

direction to make Dosa.
2. Sprinkle grated carrot on top of it.

3. Add Masala and let it cook till brown

Now serve this Arogya Masala Dosa with Coconut Chutney.

column25:
Recipe for sambar
1.  1 tbsp ghee / clarified butter1 tbsp ghee / clarified butter
2.firstly, pressure cook ½ cup toor dal, 1 tomato, ¼ tsp turmeric and 1½ cup water for 5 whistle.
3.in a kadai heat 3 tsp oil and saute 1 tsp mustard, pinch of hing, 1 dried red chilli and few curry leaves.
4.also saute 2 green chilli and ½ onion for a minute.
5. now add ½ cup tamarind extract, ½ tsp jaggery and 1 tsp salt. mix well.
6.boil for 10 minutes or till tamarind extract gets cooked well.
7.add in whisked dal and tomato. mix well.
8.also add 1½ cup water and adjust consistency. boil well.
9.furthermore add 1 tbsp of sambar powder and stir well.
10.add in 1 tbsp ghee and boil for 2 minutes.
11.finally sambar is ready to serve with vada or idli.

Recipe for vada

1. Firstly, in soak 1 cup urad dal in enough water for 3 hours. do not over soak, as the vadas will absorb oil.
2. Drain off the water and grind to fine fluffy paste adding water as required. I have added 4 tbsp of water to make smooth thick paste.
3. Transfer the urad dal paste into large mixing bowl. beat and mix the batter in circular motion till they turn light. this helps to incorporate air into batter and make medu vada soft and fluffy.
4. Further add 1 inch ginger, few curry leaves, 2 tbsp coriander, 1 tbsp dry coconut, pinch of hing, 2 tbsp rice flour and ½ tsp salt.
5. Mix the batter well with the help of spoon.
6. Heat the oil in large kadai. Wet your hands with enough water and take a small ball sized dough and make it round.
7. Now slowly shape the edges and make a hole at the centre like you prepared in bread vada.
8. Drop the vada in oil and deep fry it on medium flame.
9. Fry on both sides till they turn golden brown and crisp.
10. Drop the fried vada into warm water and add ¼ tsp salt.
11.Soak for 10 minutes or till vada absorbs water.
12. Squeeze of the water and place the vada in to the plate

column24:
1½ cups boiled split green gram (dhuli moong dal) 
1½ cups boiled basmati rice 
1 tbsp ghee + for drizzling 
1 tsp cumin seed 
½ tsp asafoetida (hing)
 1-2 fresh chillies chopped
 1½ tbsps chopped garlic
 1 large fresh onion, chopped 
1 medium red fresh tomato, chopped 
Salt to taste 
½ tsp  Turmeric Powder
 1 tsp red chilli powder
 2 tbsps finely chopped fresh coriander leaves
Papads to serve
 Pickle to serve
column25:
1. Heat some ghee in a non-stick pan. Add cumin seeds and let them changes colour to brown. Add hing and stir. 
 2. Add green chillies and fry a few seconds. Add garlic and mix and fry for 1 minute.
 3. Add onion and mix and cook till it turns. Add fresh tomato and stir and cook for 2-3 minutes. Add the salt, Turmeric Powder and red chilli powder and saute them and cook   for 2-3 minutes.
 4. Add boiled split skinless green gram and mix, add 1 cup of water and mix well. Cook them for 1-2 minutes.
 5. Add rice and mix, cook for 2-3 minutes on low heat. Add coriander leaves and mix, take the pan out from the heat and transfer the khichdi into serving bowls.
 6. Drizzle ghee and garnish with coriander. Serve hot with papads and pickle.

Grated cauliflower

Whole wheat flour dough ( 1 1/2 cups of flour will make 6 parathas)

Dry whole wheat flour for tossing and rolling

Ghee/oil

Ginger paste

Salt

Carom Seeds (Ajwain)

Red Chilli pwder

column25:
Toss a ball of dough in dry flour, and roll in to a disc of 4-5 inches in diameter.
Apply some oil in the center.
Transfer 2-3 tbsp spiced grated cauliflower to the center.
Pick up the dough from the edges and seal at the top.
Toss this stuffed ball in dry flour and roll to a diameter 6-7 inches.
Transfer to hot tawa. Cook and fry on both sides.

Tips for less calories :

You could avoid applying oil inside the paratha.

You could make paratha without frying with oil, and serve with a dash of oil/ghee smeared on the paratha after removing from the tawa.

column24:
1½ cups Chana Daal dough made using 2 cups whole wheat flour
 Salt to taste
 ½ tsp haldi powder 
1 green chilli
 ½ tbsp finely chopped ginger
 1 tsp cumin seeds
½ tsp red chilli powder
 1 tsp garam masala powder
 1 tbsp freshly chopped fresh coriander leaves
 Yogurt to serve
column25:
1. In a large bowl, add Chana Dal and some water, wash the dal and shift into another bowl. 
2. Soak the dal with some water for 3-4 hours. 
3. Heat a non-stick pan, add the soaked dal and 2 cups water. Add salt and turmeric powder and mix well. Cover and cook for 15-20 minutes.
 4. Shift the mixture into a blender, add green chilli, finely chopped ginger, cumin seeds and coarsely mince the mixture. 
5. Add turmeric powder, red chilli powder, garam masala powder, chopped coriander and stir well. 
6. Take a portion of the dough and shape it into a ball. Dust with flour and spread it to make cavity in the middle and stuff it with a portion of the prepared mixture. 
7. Roll the stuffed dough into a small disc. 
8. Heat a non-stick tawa, place the prepared disc on it and cook for 1-2 minutes. Flip and cook the other side for 1-2 minutes. 
9.  sprinkle  ghee and cook for 1-2 minutes on each side till golden and brown specks appear on both sides. Take it off the heat and transfer to a serving plate. Serve hot with yogurt.

column24:
1½ cups fine whole wheat flour (atta) + as required 
½ medium bunch fresh fenugreek leaves (methi),
 finely chopped 1 tablespoon ginger-green chilli paste
 ¼ teaspoon turmeric powder
 A pinch fresh red chilli powder 
Salt to taste 
2 tablespoons white fresh yogurt + for serving 1 tablespoon oil Ghee as required
½ cup besan
Jeera powder
column25:
1. Take 1½ cups of wheat flour in a bowl and ½ cup besan. Add methi leaves, ginger- garlic chili paste, turmeric powder, chilli powder, jeera powder, salt and stir well. Add proper water and knead them into a semi-soft dough. 
2. Heat a non-stick tawa on low flame and add some oil .
 3. Divide the kneaded dough into equal portions. Cover each portion with wheat flour and roll out some into thick discs type.
 4. sprinkle some oil on the disc, add  some wheat flour, fold into triangle and again roll out into semi-thick sheet.
 5. Place each sheet on hot pan and fry them from both sides till the colour changes to  golden brown, basting with some ghee.
 6. Serve hot with yogurt

column24:
Ingredients:
Onion 
2-3 Green Chillies 
Carrot 
Green Peas 
Tomato 
Capsicum 
1 tbsp Ghee 
Curry Leaves 
1/2 tsp Mustard Seeds 
Salt to taste 
Rava/Semolina 
2 Cups Water 
Coriander leaves to garnish
column25:
Recipe
1. Dry-roast semolina in a non-stick pan on medium heat till golden brown, sauté frequently. Transfer on a plate and cool.
 2. Finely chop onion.
 3. Heat oil in another non-stick pan. Mix  mustard seeds and cumin seeds and let the mustard seeds splutter. 
 4. Add split black gram, hing and curry leaves and let the curry leaves crackle. Add chopped onion and mix. Add green chilli and sauté till onion turns light golden brown 
 5. Chop tomato. 
 6. Boil 2½ cups water in a deep non-stick pan. 
 7. Add chopped fresh  tomato to sauté  the onion mixture and mix. Mix carrot and green peas and mix. Add ¼ cup water and salt, mix, cover and cook for 2 minutes or cook till      the water reduces.
 8. Add roasted semolina and mix. Mix salt and sugar and mix. Add boiling water, mix, reduce flame, cover and cook for 7-8 minutes. 
 9. Put the upma in a bowl, lightly press and level it out. Place the bowl inverted on a serving plate and demould. Spinkle with fried curry leave , coconut and lemon slice.
10. Serve hot with coconut chutney.

column24:
1 cup broken wheat (daliya) 
1 tsp coconut oil 
10-12 curry leaves 
½ cup soaked mix lentils 
1 small carrot, 
cut into ½ inch pieces
 10-12 French beans, cut into½ inch pieces
 ½ tsp cumin seeds 
Salt to taste 
Tempering 1 tbsp coconut oil
 1 tsp cumin seeds 
1 tsp mustard seeds 
1 large onion sliced
 Salt to taste 
6-7 garlic cloves chopped
 ½ inch ginger piece roughly chopped
 2-3 green chillies chopped
 8-10 curry leaves
column25:
1. Heat 2½ - 3cups water in a deep pan.
2. Dry roast daliya in a pressure cooker for 2 minutes or till fragrant. Add 1 tsp coconut oil, 10-12 curry leaves, ½ cup mix of soaked split skinless red lentil and soaked split skinless green gram, 1 small carrot cut into ½ inch pieces and 10-12 french beans cut into ½ inch pieces, ½ tsp cumin seeds, salt, and mix and fry  for 1-2 minutes. 
3. Add the hot water, mix, increase the flame to high and cook till 1 whistle is given out, reduce the flame to low and cook for 5-7 minutes further. 
4. To make the tempering, heat coconut oil in a non-stick pan, add 1 tsp cumin seeds and mustard seeds 1 tsp and fry for a few seconds. 
5. Add 1 large fresh onion sliced and a pinch of salt, mix and stir for 1 minute. Add 6-7 garlic cloves roughly chopped, ½ inch ginger finely chopped, 2-3 green fresh chillies chopped, 8-10 curry leaves and fry well.
 6. Add ½ tsp Turmeric Powder, ½ tsp red chilli powder, salt and 1 medium chopped fresh red tomato and mix well. Cook for 2-3 minutes. 
7. Mix 10-12 broccolli florets, ½ cup frozen green peas and fry for a minute. Cover and cook for 2 minutes. 
8. Open the cooker once the pressure has reduced completely, transfer the cooked daliya into the pan and mix well. Add ½ cup hot water and mix. 
9. Add a sprinkle of garam masala powder and mix, cover and cook for 1 minute. 
10. Add 2tbsps coriander leaves, mix well and transfer into a serving bowl. sprinkle a little ghee

column25: As per video

column24:
2 cups gram flour (besan) 
½ teaspoon turmeric powder
 Salt to taste
 1 tablespoon ginger-green chilli paste
 1 cup yogurt 
2 tablespoons oil 
1 teaspoon fruit salt
 1 teaspoon mustard seeds
 Fresh scraped coconut for garnishing
column25:
1. Mix together gram flour, turmeric powder, salt, ginger-green chilli paste and yogurt in a bowl.
2. Add sufficient water and mix well to make a slightly thick lump-free batter. 
3. Heat a steamer. Grease a thali. 
4. Add 1 tablespoon oil to the batter and mix well. Add fruit salt and mix again.
5. Pour the prepared batter in the thali and place it in the steamer. Cover and steam for 10-12 minutes. Remove from heat, cool slightly and cut into squares.
6. Heat remaining oil in a non-stick pan. Add mustard seeds and let them splutter.

column24:
1cup Kala Chana, soaked overnight and drained 
Salt to taste 
1 large fresh tomato, chopped
 1 medium fresh onion, chopped 
1 inch ginger, roughly chopped
 8-10 garlic cloves 
1-2 green chillies, chopped 
2 tbsps oil
 1 tsp cumin seeds
 ¼ tsp hing
2 bay leaves 
1-2 green cardamoms 
4-5 cloves ½ tsp turmeric powder
 ½ tsp red chilli powder 
½ tbsp coriander powder 
1 tsp dried fenugreek leaves (kasuri methi)
column25:
1. Take Chana in the bowl, add sufficient water and soak overnight. 
2. In a pressure cooker, add the soaked chana, salt and some water in to the cooker . Cook for 4 whistles. 
3. Meanwhile, in a blender jar, add tomato, onion, ginger, garlic, and green chillies. Add little water and blend to a paste. 
4. Heat oil in a non-stick pan, add cumin seeds, hing, bay leaves, green cardamoms, cloves and stir for a few seconds. 
5. Add the prepared paste, mix well and cook for 1-2 minutes. 
6. Add haldi powder, salt, laal mirch powder, coriander powder and mix well. Cook for 5-7 minutes or till the oil separates, mixing occasionally. 
7. Add the cooked chana and mix well. Cover and cook for 4-5 minutes. 
8. Crush dried fenugreek leaves and mix  to the pan. Cover and cook for 2 minutes.
 9. Garnish with coriander sprig. Serve hot with rotis, lemon wedges and onion rings.

column24:
1 cup kidney beans (rajma) 
3 tbsps ghee
 1½ tsps cumin seeds
 2 bay leaves 
1 inch cinnamon stick 
2 large onions, finely chopped
 3-4 green chillies, chopped
 1½ tbsps ginger-garlic paste 
2 cups fresh tomato puree
 2½ tsps red chilli powder
 2 tsps coriander powder 
Salt to taste 
1 tsp Punjabi garam masala powder 
3 tbsps chopped fresh coriander leaves 
2 tsps lemon juice
 Fresh cream for drizzling
 Fresh coriander sprig for garnish
column25:
1. Wash kidney beans for 2-3 times with sufficient water and soak for 7-8 hours.
2. Heat ghee in a pressure cooker, add cumin seeds and let them change colour. Add bay leaves and cinnamon stick and sauté till fragrant. 
3. Add onions, mix and sauté till they turn golden brown. Add green chillies, ginger-garlic paste and sauté for 1-2 minutes.
4. Add tomato puree, mix and cook for 3-4 minutes or till the fat separates. Add red chilli powder, coriander powder and salt and mix well. Cook for 2-3 minutes. 
5. Add soaked kidney beans and mix, adjust salt and pour 4-5 cups water, mix, cover and cook under pressure till 3-4 whistles are given out on high heat, reduce the heat and cook further till 3-4 whistles are given out.
6. Open the cooker once the pressure has reduced completely; add Punjabi garam masala powder and coriander leaves and mix.
7. Switch the heat off, add lemon juice, mix and transfer into a serving bowl, garnish with fresh cream and coriander sprig.

METHOD FOR STIR FRY VEGGIES
Take curd in a cup and add salt & pepper
Add Paneer Cubes to it and let it marinate for 15-20 minutes
Take the oil in a non stick pan. Heat up a little
Then add all the vegetables one by one and keep saueting (Not Paneer).
Stir fry for a while
In a cup add Soy sauce, vinegar, with all the spices. Make a slurry
Evenly spread the slurry over the veggies
Cook for a while
Grill the Paneer cubes in a separate pan or griller
Add the grilled paneer to the stir fried veggies
Sprinkle the sesame seeds
Toss it all around  for a while and they are done!

¼ teaspoon turmeric powder   
4 tablespoons oil

½ teaspoon mustard seeds     
4 whole dry red chillies, broken    
½ teaspoon fenugreek seeds (methi dana)(optional)  
¼ teaspoon asafoetida

column25:
1. Pressure-cook the dal in two and half cups of water with turmeric powder and one teaspoon oil for three whistles. Open lid once the pressure has reduced. Mash the cooked dal lightly with a wooden spoon. 
2. Soak tamarind in one-cup warm water, extract pulp and set aside.
3. Heat the remaining oil in a thick-bottomed pan. Add mustard seeds. When they splutter add dry red chillies, fenugreek seeds and asafoetida.
4. Stir and add green chillies, curry leaves and drumsticks and cook for one minute on medium heat stirring briefly.
5. Add sambhar powder, salt and one cup water. 
6. Reduce heat and simmer for six to eight minutes or till drumsticks are cooked. Add tamarind pulp, boiled dal and simmer for two to three minutes.
7. Serve hot with steamed rice.

Green chillies – 1 no
Curry leaves – few sprigs
Grated coconut – ½cup
Salt – a small pinch
Sprinkle Green coriander
column25: Mix together besan, curd, water, turmeric, ginger paste, green chilly paste, salt and whisk them well. Place them in a saucepan and bring to a boil. Keep stirring till it thickens. Make it quite thick. Now remove it and spread the contents on to a thali or a marble/stone top and spread it very thin. Use the back of a knife or a pallet knife to spread evenly while it is still hot. Heat oil in a pan, add mustard seeds, green chillies, and curry leaves, once it splutters add grated coconut and remove from heat. Add fresh coriander and mix and sprinkle this tempering on the khandvi. Reserve a little tempering for the garnish. Let it cool completely. Run a knife on the spread khandvi in long strips 2” wide. Push the edges inwards and roll them up. Stack them and sprinkle with the remaining tempering and serve cold.

 Coconut chutney for serving
column25:
1. Blend split skinless black gram along with some water into smooth and thick batter. Transfer in a bowl. 
2. Add curry leaves, coconut, green chillies, crushed peppercorns and salt and mix well. 
3. Heat sufficient oil in a kadai. 
4. Dampen your palms with some water, take a portion on the batter, make a cavity in the center to shape into medu vada and drop in hot oil directly and deep-fry till golden brown and crisp. Drain on absorbent paper. 
5. Serve hot with coconut chutney.

Place the ground chillies in a bowl or a bottle.

In a tadka pan heat the oil over medium heat. Add the mustard seeds and once they splutter add the asafoetida and turn off the heat. 

Pour this tempering over the green chilli thecha and mix well.

Serve the Maharashtrian Green Chilli Thecha Recipe along with Methi Thalipeeth or Bhakri along with nice cup of Gulkand chai.

column25:
1. Heat oil in a small pan and switch off the heat. 
2. Take khapli atta in a large bowl, add whole wheat flour, salt, and hot oil and mix well. Add ¼ cup water and knead to a stiff dough. Cover with a damp muslin cloth and set aside for 10-15 minutes.
 3. Divide the dough into small equal portions and shape each portion into a small thick disc, cut out a shape with a katori. 
4. Heat a non-stick tawa, place the discs on it and cook on low heat for 2-3 minutes on each side while pressing the discs gently with a roti press on both sides.
 5. Once golden brown, drizzle ghee on both sides and transfer the discs on a serving plate and serve hot.

1. Pressure cook pigeon peas in sufficient water with fenugreek seeds, peanuts, turmeric powder, salt and ½ teaspoon ghee till the pressure is released for 2-3 times. Reduce heat and simmer for 5 minutes. 
2. Heat 1 tablespoon ghee in a non-stick pan. Add mustard seeds and let them splutter. 
3. Add cumin seeds and sauté for a few seconds. Add asafoetida and sauté for 30 seconds. 
4. Add curry leaves, green chillies and red chillies and sauté for a minute. Add cooked pigeon peas and little water, stir to mix and simmer for 1-2 minutes. 
5. Add kokum petals and jaggery, mix well and bring to a boil. Add some more water, stir and boil for 5-10 minutes.
 6. Add lemon juice and mix well. 
7. Garnish with coriander leaves, drizzle ½ teaspoon ghee on top and serve hot with steamed rice.

column24:
INGREDIENTS
¼ cup Ragi Flour
⅛  cup Urad dal
¼  tsp fenugreek seeds
Salt (to taste)
Oil (for brushing)
column25:
METHOD
Combine the urad dal, fenugreek seeds and enough water in a deep bowl, cover with a lid and keep aside to soak for 2 hours.
Drain well and blend in a mixer to a smooth paste using enough of water
Transfer the mixture into a deep bowl, add the ragi flour, salt and water (enough to make a running consistency of dosa batter), mix very well using a whisk. Cover with a lid and keep aside to ferment in a warm place for 12 hours.
Once fermented, mix very well again
Heat a non stick tawa (griddle), sprinkle a little water on the tawa and wipe it off gently using a muslin cloth. 
Pour a ladleful of batter on it and spread it in a circular motion to make a thin circle. 
Smear a very little oil over it and along the edges and cook on a high flame till the dosa turns brown in color and crisp from both the sides
Fold over to make semi circle or a roll
Serve the Ragi Dosa/ Nachni Dosa immediately with sambhar and coconut chutney.

. Clean chicken thoroughly and add 1/2 tsp salt, red chili powder, turmeric and yogurt keep it covered in the refrigerator for 30 minutes

1. Heat ⅛ cup ghee in a non-stick pan, add semolina and roast till golden brown and fragrant. Transfer into a large bowl and allow to cool to room temperature. 
2. Heat remaining ghee in the same pan, add mustard seeds, asafoetida, split skinless black gram, green chillies and curry leaves and sauté for a few seconds or till everything crisps up. Transfer on a plate and allow to cool to room temperature. 
3. Crush the fried curry leaves and add them into the semolina and add the remaining fried mixture. Mix well.
 4. Add powdered sugar, salt and fruit salt and mix till well combined. Transfer into an air tight container and store up to 20 days in a dry place. 
5. For making the idlis, take 1 cup of the prepared premix in a large bowl. Add yogurt and ⅓ cup water and whisk well. Set aside for 10 minutes.
 6. Heat sufficient water in a steamer and add the prepared batter into each greased idli mould and steam for 8-10 minutes. 7. Take them off the heat and serve hot with tomato chutney and coconut chutney.

column25:
To begin making the Menthe/Fenugreek Seeds Tambli Recipe, heat ghee in a kadai or a heavy bottomed pan. Add methi seeds and dry red chillies to it. Roast them until methi seeds and red chilies turn brownish and aromatic. Once done transfer to a plate .

In a mixer grinder, blend the methi seeds along with grated coconut, salt and little yogurt to make a smooth paste. You can add a little water to the mixture.

Transfer the methe and coconut mixture to a serving bowl . Add the remaining yogurt and stir well. Add salt and check the taste. 

The final step is to make the seasoning. Heat ghee in the small tadka pan over medium heat.

Once hot add mustard seeds and allow it to crackle. When they splutter add curry leaves and turn off the heat. Pour this seasoning on the Menthe Tambli and give a gentle stir. The Menthe Tambli is ready to be served.

Serve the Menthe / Fenugreek Seeds Tambli as a side dish along with your main course meal for lunch or dinner

For the masala
2 Onions , roughly chopped

column25:
To begin making the Karnataka Style Chicken Saaru Recipe, we will first make the masala for the saaru. 

Heat a small skillet on medium-low flame, add the poppy seeds and dry roast them. 

Once the poppy seeds are roasted, add in the cloves, cinnamon and dry red chilli and roast them well. Turn off the flame and keep it aside.

Heat another pan on medium flame, add a tablespoon of oil, add ginger, garlic, onions and saute until the onions turn translucent.

Add grated coconut and saute well till they turn light brown. Turn off the flame.

In a mixer-jar, combine the dry roasted spices along with ginger-garlic-onion mixture, grind to a smooth paste along with some water. Transfer to a bowl and set aside. 

Heat oil in the pressure cooker over medium heat, add the chicken, turmeric powder,salt and red chilli powder. Roast the chicken in the pan for about 5 minutes until the chicken begins to get a roasted texture and is getting partially cooked. 

After 5 minutes of roasting the chicken, add the ground saaru masala (onion coconut & spices paste) and give it a stir. Check for salt and add 1 cup of water and pressure cook for about 3 to 4 whistles until the chicken is cooked and turn off the heat.

Allow the pressure to release naturally. Open the cooker and check for spices and salt and adjust accordingly.

Serve the Karnataka Style Chicken Saaru Recipe along with Ragi Mudde, Akki Roti or Jolada Rotti to enjoy it for your lunch.

Dry roast the coriander seeds until they turn dark brown.

Add dry red chillies, piece of cinnamon, cardamom, cloves, fenugreek seeds, cumin seeds, pepper and raw rice.

Keep roasting it for few minutes.

Once the roasted ingredients are cooled down add it into a blender, grind them into a dry powder.

To make the fresh masala, add coriander leaves, garlic cloves, ginger, green chillies and half a sliced onion in a blender and grind everything together, add some water to it to make a smooth paste.

Wash the pork with vinegar and salt.

Add the pork into pressure cooker add the fresh masala, other half of the sliced onion, 3 tbsp of the dry masala and water. Mix it well.

Cook the curry for one whistle. Switch off the flame and wait for the cooker to cool down. Open the lid of the cooker and place it on the flame again. Add salt to taste.

Add the water in which the kombucha has been soaking, into the curry,

Pandi Curry is ready to be served.

1. Take muslin cloth, add tea leaves dried Indian gooseberries and tie into a knot. 
 2. Heat a pressure cooker, add some water, chickpeas, knotted muslin cloth, salt,bay leaf and black cardamoms and mix well. Cook on high flame for 7-8 whistles, reduce the flame and cook further for 15 minutes. 
 3. Heat ghee and oil in a non-stick pan, add cumin seeds, carom seeds, black peppercorns, cloves and green cardamom and fry till fragrant. 
 4. Mix onion, a pinch of salt and fry till golden brown. Mix ginger-garlic paste and stir till the raw smell goes away.

 7. Add cinnamon and sauté for 30 seconds and add fresh tomato puree and mix well. 
 8. Add dried fenugreek leaves and mix well, cook till the fat separates.
 9. Mash potato and add into the pan, add Punjabi Chole Masala and mix well. Reduce the heat.
10. Discard the knotted muslin cloth and black cardamom, add cooked chole in the pan and mix well , cover and cook for 10-15 minutes

column24:
Soya chaap - 3-4 (250 grams)
 Tomato - 3 (250 grams)
 Ginger - 1 inch
 Green chilly - 1 piece
 Cream - 100 grams
 Oil - 3-4 tbsp
 Green coriander - 2-3 tbsp (finely chopped)
 Asafoetida - 1 pinch
 Cumin seeds - ¼ tsp
 Turmeric powder - ¼ tsp
 Red chilly powder - ¼ tsp
 Garam masala - less than ¼ tsp
 Coriander powder - 1 tsp
 Dry fenugreek leaves - 1 tsp
 Whole spices - brown cardamom -1, cinnamon stick - 1, clove - 2, Black pepper - 6-7
 Salt - 1 tsp (as per taste)
column25:
1. Chop off the soya chunks in 1-1.5 inch chunks.
2. Finely chop tomato-ginger-green chilly and grind finely to make a fine paste.
3. Heat some oil in a pan and fry the chunks until they get brow in color and cooked through. Drain out the chunks on kitchen paper towels to remove excess oil.
4. Splutter cumin seeds in the remaining oil. Then add asafoetida, turmeric powder, coriander powder, dry fenugreek seeds, along with whole spices i.e. black pepper, cinnamon stick, clove and cardamom (peeled). Saute the spices until fragrant.
5. Then add tomato-ginger-green chilly paste, followed by red chilly powder and saute until you see oil leaving the sides of the masala.
6. Now to the masala add garam masala and cream. Keep stirring constantly until you see gentle boil in the masala.
7. Add ½ cup water to the masala and stir constantly until the gravy starts simmering again.
8. Mix some green coriander to the gravy along with salt and soya chaap chunks.
9. Cover and let the curry simmer for 4-5 minutes on low flame so that the soya chunks absorb all the spices well. Spicy soya chaap curry is now ready. Transfer to another bowl.
10. Serve this awesome soya chaap curry garnished with coriander sprigs with steaming hot with any Indian bread like butter naan, parantha or chapatti. It also goes well with plain rice or jeera rice as well.

column25:
Combine the marinade ingredients. Place the chicken in a bowl with the lemon juice. Add the marinade ingredients and sprinkle the ginger pieces over the chicken.


Marinate the chicken for about 20 minutes.


Steam the chicken. If using the wok to steam the chicken, place the chicken on a steam proof dish and pour the marinade ingredients over it. Steam the chicken until it turns white and is cooked through.

If using a commercial steamer, prepare according to the steamer directions. Depending on the type of steamer, you may not be able to pour the marinade over the chicken before steaming. If that is the case, reserve the marinade and steam the chicken according to the manufacturer's instructions. Bring the reserved marinade to a boil and pour over the chicken just before serving.

Serve hot with rice and stir-fried dried mushrooms. Garnish with green onion and lemon wedges.

 5-6 4 inch lemon grass

column25:
1. To prepare Thai green curry paste, dry-roast cumin seeds and coriander seeds in a non-stick pan till fragrant.
 2. Roughly chop lemongrass, garlic cloves and galangal. Discard the stem of kaffir lime leaves. 
3. Grind together chopped lemongrass, garlic cloves, galangal, kaffir lime leaves, coriander leaves, coriander stems, broken green chillies, basil leaves, sugar, salt and roasted seeds into smooth and thick paste. Add 2-3 tablespoons water and grind again. Transfer in a bowl.
 4. To prepare curry, heat oil in a deep non-stick pan. Add garlic and sauté for 30 seconds. 
5. Add pea aubergine, galangal and 3-4 kaffir lime leaves and sauté for 30 seconds. 
6. Lightly beat the lemon grass with the back of the knife, add to pan and sauté for 10 seconds.
 7. Add 2-3 tablespoons Thai green curry paste and sauté for 2 minutes. Add 2-3 tablespoons water and sauté for 1-2 minutes.
 8. Add coconut milk, mix and cook for 2-3 minutes. Add pumpkin, brinjal, French beans, carrot and babycorn and mix well. 
9. Add sugar and salt, mix and simmer for 7-8 minutes. Add 3-4 tablespoons water, Chinese cabbage, bok choy stems, bok choy leaves and snow peas, mix and cook for 3-4 minutes. Add basil leaves, switch off heat and mix well. 
10. Pour the curry in a serving bowl, garnish with some red chilli and spring onion green and serve hot with steamed rice.

column25:
To begin making the Paneer Matar Pulao Recipe, firstly wash the rice and soak for 15-20 minutes and drain. 

Heat the ghee in a pressure cooker on medium heat; add the fennel seeds, cardamom, cinnamon, clove and bay leaf and saute until you get a lovely aroma.

Add the ginger, garlic and green chilies, and saute for a few seconds. At this stage, add onions and saute until the onion turns pink. 

Once done, add in the rice, two cups of water, and salt. Close the pressure cooker. 

Pressure cook for 2- 3 whistles and turn off the flame.  Allow the pressure to release naturally.

Open the pressure cooker and fluff the rice with a fork. 

Heat a skillet, with ghee on medium flame, to this add the paneer cubes and saute for about a minute. 

To this, add the steamed green peas and salt. 

Toss the paneer on high heat for about a minute or two and turn off the flame. 

Now add the paneer-green peas into the pulao and mix well. 

Add in the fresh chopped mint leaves and transfer the Paneer Matar Pulao to a serving platter. 

Serve Paneer Matar Pulao Recipe along with Shabnam Curry and Boondi Raita for a delicious weekday lunch.

Making mixed kathol recipe:
▢1-2 tablespoons Ghee (clarified butter) or Oil
▢½ teaspoon Mustard seeds
▢1 teaspoon Cumin seeds

▢2 medium or 1 ¼ cups Tomato finely chopped

column25:
Soaking and pressure cooking beans:
Take all the beans and wash them under running cold water till water runs clear.
Soak them in enough water for 8 hours or overnight.
After the soaking time they have got bigger in size. Drain and discard the soaking water.
Take the beans into pressure cooker add fresh 2 cups of water.
Cover the cooker with lid, put the weight on.
Cook it for 2 whistles on high, then lower the heat and cook for 20 minutes. Then turn off the stove.
Let the pressure go down by itself and open the lid. They should be soft and cooked perfectly.
Making jain mixed kathol recipe:
Heat the oil or ghee in a pan on medium heat.
Once hot add mustard seeds and let them pop.
Then add cumin seeds and let them sizzle.
Now add chopped green chilies and cook for 30 seconds.
Add chopped tomatoes. Sprinkle the salt and mix.
Cook till tomatoes are soft and mushy. Mash them using back of the spoon/spatula slightly.
Now add turmeric powder, red chili powder and cumin-coriander powder.
Mix well and cook for 1 minute.
Now add cooked beans with its water.
Mix well. If needed, you can add extra water to make liking consistency.
Let it simmer for 4-5 minutes on low.
Now add lemon juice and mix.
Lastly add chopped coriander leaves. Mix well.
Turn off the stove.

 For the dal

 Salt to taste

 ½ tbsp lemon juice 
5 tbsp chopped jaggery (gur) 
1 tsp ginger-green chilli (adrak-mirchi) paste
 1 tsp chilli powder
 3 tbsp broken cashews (kaju)
 10 curry leaves (kadi patta)
 ¼ tsp turmeric powder (haldi) 
2 tbsp ghee
 1 tbsp oil
 ¼ tsp cumin seeds (jeera)

column25:
For the dhoklis 
1. Combine all the ingredients in a deep bowl and knead into a semi-stiff dough using enough water. 
2. Cover the dough with a lid and keep aside for atleast 15 minutes.
 3. Divide the dough into 5 equal portions and roll out each portion into a 200 mm. (8”) diameter thin circle using a little whole wheat flour for rolling. 
4. Heat a non-stick tava (griddle) and cook each chapati lightly from both the sides.
 5. Cool and cut each chapati into diamond or square shapes and keep aside. 
For the dal
 1. Clean, wash and drain the dal. 
2. Combine the dal and 2 cups of hot water in a pressure cooker and pressure cook for 3 whistles. 
3. Allow the steam to escape before opening the lid.
 4. Combine the cooked dal and 1 cup of hot water in a deep non-stick pan and blend it well using a hand blender till smooth. 
5. Add more 2½ cups of hot water and mix very well.
 6. Place the deep non-stick pan on the flame , add the salt, kokum, lemon juice, jaggery, ginger-green chilli paste, chilli powder, cashewnuts, curry leaves and turmeric powder, mix well and cook on a medium flame for 10 to 15 minutes, while stirirng occasionally.
 7. Meanwhile, for the tempering, heat the ghee and oil in a small non-stick pan, add the cumin seeds and mustard seeds and allow them to crackle.
 8. When the seeds crackle, add the asafoetida, red chillies, cinnamon, cloves and sauté on a medium flame for 30 seconds. 
9. Add this tempering to the dal, mix well and cook on a medium flame for 2 to 3 minutes, while stirirng occasionally. Keep aside. How to proceed Just before serving, boil the dal, once it starts boiling, add the dhoklis, coriander and ghee, mix well and cook on a medium flame for 1 to 2 minutes, while stirring occasionally. Serve immediately with ghee.
 Handy tips: 1. Add the dhoklis one by one into the dal, otherwise they could coagulate to form one big lump. 2. Add more water if the dal thickens while simmering.

Heat a pan and add split yellow moong dal. Dry roast the moong dal for 2 to 3 mins.
Turn off the heat and wash the roasted moong dal and keep it aside.
Meanwhile heat a cooker pan and add washed moong dal, little millet. Mix it well.
Now add 3 cups of water and cover the lid. Pressure cook this for 3 whistles.
Once the steam settled down on its own, carefully open the lid and mix again. keep this aside.
Now heat another pan on medium flame and add a tbsp of ghee. Once the ghee is melted up, add cumin,turmeric powder and black pepper.
Similarly add green chilli, grated ginger, cashews. Saute well until it splutters and cashews are golden.
Likewise add curry leaves and hing. saute it for a min.
Then add cooked moong dal & millet mixture. Add required amount of water.
Mix everything well. Now add salt and give a quick mix.
Turn off the heat and add grated dry coconut and ghee. Gently mix once.
Now the tasty, healthy little millet pongal is ready to serve.

column24:
1 cup Foxtail Millet
1-1/2 cups White Urad Dal (Split)
1 teaspoon Methi Seeds (Fenugreek Seeds)
Salt , to taste
column25:
To begin making the Foxtail Millet Idli Recipe, we will wash and soak the millets in water in a separately bowl and urad dal along with methi seeds with enough water in another bowl overnight or keep soaked for at least 8 hours. Soak each of them separately.

To make the batter, drain the excess water soaked millets and urad dal.

Blend the urad dal along with just enough water to make a thick and very smooth batter.

Transfer the batter to a large bowl in which we will set it aside for fermentation along with ground millet.

Next blend the foxtail millet with just enough water to make a smooth batter.

Add this to the urad dal batter, add 2 teaspoons of salt and stir well to combine.

Ferment the batter for 5 to 6 hours or overnight.

Once the batter is fermented, gently stir and be careful to not release the air pockets.

You can make regular sized idlis or also use the mini idli stand. Grease the idli molds with a little oil and spoon the foxtail millet idli batter into the molds.

Prepare the idli steamer with a little water in the bottom.

Place the filled idli racks in the steamer. Place the steamer on high heat and steam the idli’s for 10 minutes.

After 10 minutes of steaming, turn off the heat. Open the steamer and insert a knife or a pick to test whether the idli's are cooked. If nothing sticks then the idlis are perfectly steamed.

Now you can remove the Foxtail millet idli from the steamer. Have a small bowl filled with water.

Dip a spoon in the water and then scoop the ragi idli out starting from the edges. Dipping the spoon in water helps in the easy removal of idli from the plates.

The wholesome homemade pillow-soft foxtail millet idli is now ready to be served. 

Serve the Foxtail Millet Mini Idli Recipe along with Thakkali Vengayam Sambar, chutney to enjoy your morning breakfast.

For an Indian Diabetic Meal serve this Foxtail Millet Idli Recipe along with Murungakkai Vendhaya Keerai Sambar Recipe and Horsegram Sesame Chutney Recipe for a healthy

column25:

column24:
1/2 cup broken wheat (dalia)
 2 tsp oil
 1/4 tsp mustard seeds ( rai / sarson)
 2 tsp finely chopped green chillies
 1/2 cup chopped onions
 1/2 tsp grated ginger (adrak)
 1/4 cup green peas
 1/4 cup chopped carrots
 salt to taste For The Garnish 
2 tbsp finely chopped coriander (dhania)
column25:
1. Clean and wash the broken wheat thoroughly. Par- boil the broken wheat in 2 cups of hot water for 3 to 4 minutes. Drain and keep aside.
 2. Heat the oil in a pressure cooker, and add the mustard seeds. 
3. When the seeds crackle, add the green chillies and sauté on a medium flame for a few seconds. 
4. Add the onions and ginger, mix well and sauté on a medium flame for 1 to 2 minutes. 
5. Add the green peas and carrots, mix well and sauté on a medium flame for 1 to 2 minutes.
 6. Add the broken wheat, salt and 1¼ cups of water, mix well and pressure cook for 2 whistles.
 7. Allow the steam to escape before opening the lid. 8. Serve immediately garnished with coriander.

column24:
1. Finger Millets Powder - 2-3 Tablespoons
2. Salt
3. Pepper Powder
4. Chopped Vegetables
column25: Heat 2 teaspoons clarified butter (ghee) in a pan. Clarified butter (ghee) or oil could be used. Add 1/2 teaspoon cumin seeds, 2 dried chillies and fry. Add chopped onions and fry. Add 1/4 cup carrot pieces and mix. Add vegetables of your choice and mix. Close the lid and cook on low flame for 5 minutes. Add 3 cups water. Add 1/2 teaspoon pepper powder (optional), 1 teaspoon salt and mix. Close the lid and let the water boil. Add finger millets powder liquid and mix. More water could be added. Boil the soup. Keep mixing. Add more pepper powder or salt if necessary. It will take 12-15 minutes for the soup to cook completely. Boil till required consistency is obtained. Add coriander leaves and mix.

column24:
2 Cups Chopped Spinach leaves or 1 large bunch Spinach
1 Cup Dil Leaves chopped or1 small bunch
1 Cup Fenugreek leaves or 1 small bunch
1/4 cup Coriander leaves optional
1/2 Cup Toor Dal
1 1/2 No's Onion medium size
2 No's Tomatoes
3 No's Green Chilly
6 Garlic Cloves
1 1/2 Tsp Salt or as required
For Masala Paste
1/2 cup Fresh Grated Coconut
1 Tsp Tamarind ,firmly pressed
2 Tbsp Sambar Powder
For Tempering
2-3 Tsp Cooking Oil
1/2 Tsp Mustard Seeds
2 sprigs Curry Leaves
2 Dry Red Chilli ,Broken
1/4 Tsp Asafoetida
1/2 small Onion , Quartered and crushed
3 Garlic cloves ,crushed
column25:
Clean all the green and thoroughly wash . Roughly chop greens .Rinse and wash Toor dal.
In pressure cooker,add toor dal,onion, 6 cloves of garlic,tomatoes,green chilly and all greens.Add 1 cup of water and pressure cook for a whistle
When pressure is released on its own,drain the water and keep it aside. Allow it to cool .
Once cooled , place all the above cooked greens and dal into a mixer/processor and blend/ process for 3-5 seconds such that everything is blended well.
In a small mixer jar,add fresh coconut,tamarind and sambar powder to a very smooth paste by adding little water.
Take a pan,heat oil,add mustard seeds once it sputters add all the seasoning ingredients listed above in order.
Fry Onion and garlic for a 2 minutes,add the above grounded coconut paste fry well till oil leaves the corners.
For this add cooked and mashed greens,mix well. Add drained water and also about 2.5 - 3 cups of water, add salt to taste. Cover and bring to boil . Once it starts to boil,turn off the heat. Alternatively you can also close pressure cooker and when its about to whistle, turn off the stove. Refer notes
Masida soppu saaru will be ready to serve .Serve this curry along with Ragi Mudde / Ragi Balls or plain Rice .

column24:
4 tablespoons split pigeon peas (toor dal), soaked
 ¾ teaspoon turmeric powder 
1½ teaspoons rasam masala powder
 ¼ teaspoon asafoetida 
¼ teaspoon black pepper powder 
2½ tablespoons tamarind pulp
 2 medium tomatoes, chopped
 Salt to taste
 4 tablespoons chopped fresh coriander leaves Tempering 
2 tablespoons ghee
 ½ teaspoon mustard seeds 
A pinch asafoetida 5-6 curry leaves
column25:
1. Pressure cook the pigeon peas in 4 cups water with half the turmeric powder till 4-5 whistles.
 2. Heat some water in a non-stick pan. Add remaining turmeric powder, rasam masala powder, asafetida, pepper powder, tamarind pulp and tomatoes, mix well and bring to a boil. Reduce heat and cook till the liquid becomes half the volume. 
3. Mash the cooked dal and strain the water.
 4. Add the strained dal water to the tamarind mixture alongwith salt and chopped coriander and mix well. 
5. For tempering, heat ghee in a non-stick tempering pan. Add mustard seeds and let them splutter. Add asafetida and curry leaves and switch off heat. 
6. Add the tempering to the rasam, mix well and cook on medium heat for 4-5 minutes. 7. Serve hot with steamed rice.

column24:
3 tbsps Tata Sampann Organic Toor Dal
 ¾ tsp asafoetida
 ½ tsp turmeric powder 
2 large tomatoes, finely chopped 
2 tbsps freshly chopped coriander leaves
 1½ tbsps rasam powder 
Salt to taste
 1 tbsp tamarind pulp
 7-8 black peppercorns 
2 tsps cumin seeds 
1 tbsp ghee 
¼ tsp mustard seeds
 8-10 curry leaves
 Steamed rice to serve 
Fried papad to serve
column25:
1. In a bowl, add Tata Sampann Organic Toor Dal and add sufficient water. Soak it for 20-25 minutes. Boil it with ½ tsp asafoetida and turmeric powder.
 2. Meanwhile, in a pan, add tomatoes, chopped coriander, rasam powder, salt and sufficient water. Mix well, cover and cook till the mixture comes to a boil.
 3. Add the cooked dal and mix well. Cover and cook till the tomatoes are pulpy and the mixture comes to a boil. 
4. Add tamarind pulp and mix well. Lower the heat and allow to reduce slightly. 
5. Meanwhile, dry roast black peppercorns in another non-stick. Add cumin seeds and roast till fragrant. Transfer them into a jar and blend to a coarse powder. 
6. Add the prepared powder into the rasam, mix well and cook for 2-3 minutes. 
7. For the tempering, heat ghee in the same pan, add mustard seeds, remaining asafoetida and curry leaves. Let the seeds splutter and add it to the rasam. 
8. Cover and cook for 1 minute. Take it off the heat.
 9. Serve hot with rice and fried papad.

column24:
6 eggs, hard boiled and halved 
2 medium onions, finely chopped
 ½ cup scraped fresh coconut 
½ inch cinnamon 
4-5 black peppercorns
 3-4 cloves
 1 green chilli, roughly chopped
 4-5 garlic cloves ½ inch ginger, roughly chopped
 2 tablespoons coriander seeds
 ½ teaspoon fennel seeds
 5-6 fresh coriander sprigs + for garnishing
 2 tablespoons oil
 Salt to taste
 ¼ teaspoon turmeric powder 
2 teaspoons red chilli powder
 2-3 kokum petals
column25:
. Grind together coconut, half of onion, cinnamon, peppercorns, cloves, green chilli, garlic, ginger, coriander seeds, fennel seeds and 5-6 coriander sprigs alongwith water into a smooth paste. 
2. Heat oil in a deep non-stick pan. Add remaining onion and sauté on high heat for 1 minute. Add salt and sauté for 2-3 minutes or till onion turns golden brown.
 3. Add ground coconut paste, mix and cook on high heat for 4-5 minutes or till the oil separates.
 4. Add turmeric powder, chilli powder and salt and mix. Add 2½ cups water, mix, cover and cook for 2 minutes.
 5. Reduce heat, add kokum petals and halved eggs, mix, cover and cook for 2 minutes. 
6. Serve hot garnished with coriander sprigs.

column24:
1 medium carrot, peeled and cut into ½ inch cubes
 1 medium green capsicum, seeded and cut into ½ inch pieces
 1 medium red capsicum, seeded and cut into ½ inch pieces
 2 medium potatoes, peeled and cut into ½ inch cubes 
2-3 tablespoons oil
 6-8 garlic cloves, finely chopped
 1 inch ginger piece, finely chopped
 1 medium onion, peeled, diced, layers separated
 2 fresh jalapenos, finely chopped
 2 teaspoons cumin powder 
1 teaspoon curry powder 
1 teaspoon garam masala powder 
1 cup tomato puree
 Salt to taste
 ¼ cup cashew nut powder 
¼ cup fresh cream 
1 tablespoon chopped fresh coriander A few fresh mint sprigs for garnish
column25:
1. Heat oil in a deep nonstick pan. Add the garlic, ginger and cook on medium heat till the raw flavor of the garlic and ginger is gone.
 2. Add the onions and sauté till the onions are translucent. Add the carrots, green capsicum, red bell pepper and jalapenos and sauté well. 
3. Add half a cup water, mix well and. Add cumin powder, curry powder, garam masala powder and mix well. Cook for two to three minutes. 
4. Add the potatoes, mix well. Add half cup water, tomato puree and mix well.
 5. Add the salt, cover and cook till the vegetables are almost cooked.
 6. Add cashew nut power, cover and cook till the vegetables are done. Add fresh cream and mix well.
 7. Transfer in a serving bowl. Sprinkle coriander on top.
 8. Serve hot garnished with mint sprigs.

column24:
Cooking soda (optional) - pinch.
• Peppercorns - 1/4 tea spoon.
• Curry leaves - 2 springs.
• Ginger ( finely chopped) - 1 tea spoon.
• Onions ( finely chopped) - 1/4 cup.
• Channa dal - 1+1/2 cup.
• Ghee - 1 tablespoon.
• Lemon juice - 1 tablespoon.
• Salt - to taste.
• Mustard seeds - 1 tablespoon.
• Turmeric powder - 1 tea spoon.
• Hing / asafoetida - pinch.
• Coconut (freshly grated) - 3 tablespoon.
• Red chilies - 5 number.
column25:
Wash and soak the channa dal in water for 3 to 4 hours. Drain the water and keep aside.
In the mixie jar, add red chilies, onions, ginger, curry leaves, pepper corns, salt, channa dal, a pinch of cooking soda and grind to a coarse paste.
Remove the mixture into a bowl and add little ghee and lime juice and mix well.
Then make them to small dumplings and steam cook for about 10 minutes. Keep aside.
For tempering:

Heat ghee in a pan, add mustard seeds, dry red chilies, turmeric powder, hing, curry leaves, grated coconut, salt, lemon juice, chopped coriander leaves, sugar, saute it.
At last, add steamed dumplings in it and toss it well.
Delicious Steamed Masala Vada is now ready to serve.

column24:
1 tsp - Cumin seeds
1 medium - Chopped onion
1 tbsp - Ginger garlic paste
1/8 cup - Dry coconut grated
1/4 cup - tomato puree
1 tsp - Red chilli powder
1/4 tsp - Turmeric
1 tsp - Garam masala
1.5 tsp - Salt
2 tsp- Water
200 gms - Fresh mushrooms
column25:
1. In a pan, roast 1 tsp of cumin seeds on low flame.
Then add chopped onion and saute. Add little water if onion starts sticking to the pan & again saute well.
2. Then add ginger garlic paste to it and saute till sweet aromatic smell comes up.
3. Add red chilli powder, turmeric, Garam masala & salt & mix well. Then add tomato puree and mix everything well with each other.
4. Add grated dry coconut to this mixture and saute well.
5. Saute this mixture till it becomes dry & starts leaving sides of the pan. Once this is done, masala is ready.
6. Add chopped mushrooms to this and cover it with lid cook for 5-6 minutes till mushrooms becomes mushy.
Stir in between.
7. Once mushrooms are cooked garnish with coriander leaves. Serve hot with roti or naan.

column24:
For The Misal Masala
1 tbsp oil
1/4 cup thinly sliced onions
1/4 cup grated dry coconut (kopra)
2 tsp coriander (dhania) seeds
1 tsp cumin seeds (jeera)
3 cloves (laung / lavang)
3 peppercorns (kalimirch)
25 mm stick cinnamon (dalchini)
2 whole dry kashmiri red chillies
3 garlic (lehsun) cloves

For The Misal
3 tbsp oil
1 tsp cumin seeds (jeera)
1/4 cup finely chopped onions
1 cup finely chopped tomatoes
1/4 tsp turmeric powder (haldi)
1/2 cup matki (moath beans) sprouts
1/2 cup safed vatana (dried white peas) sprouts
1/2 cup moong (whole green gram) sprouts
2 tbsp chawli (cow pea / lobhia) sprouts
1 1/2 tsp chilli powder
2 tbsp finely chopped coriander (dhania)
salt to taste
For Serving
1/2 cup mixed farsaan (chivda)
1/2 cup potatoes
1/2 cup finely chopped onions
4 tbsp finely chopped coriander (dhania)
8 laddi pavs
4 lemon wedges
column25:
For the misal masala

1. Heat the oil in a broad non-stick pan, add the onions and coconut and dry roast on 
    a medium flame for 2 to 3 minutes.
2. Add all the remaining ingredients and sauté on a medium flame for 3 to 4 minutes.
3. Remove from the flame and allow it to cool completely.
4. Once cooled, blend in a mixer to a smooth powder without using
5. Any water. Keep aside.

For the misal

1. Heat the oil in a pressure cooker and add the cumin seeds.
2. When the seeds crackle, add the onions and sauté on a medium flame for 1 to 
    2 minutes.
3. Add the prepared misal masala and sauté on a medium flame for 1 more minute.
4. Add the tomatoes, turmeric powder and a little water (approx. 1 tbsp), mix well 
    and cook on a medium flame for 2 to 3 minutes, while stirring occasionally.
5. Add the matki, safed vatana, moong and chawli sprouts and mix well.
6. Add 2 cups of hot water and salt, mix well and pressure cook for 3 whistles.
7. Allow the steam to escape before opening the lid.
8. Add the chilli powder, 1/2 cup of water and coriander, mix well and simmer for 3 to 
   4 minutes, while stirring occasionally.

column24:
Ingredients 
1 cup jowar flour
 ½ cup rice flour
 ¼ cup wheat flour
 ¼ cup chickpea flour (besan) 
Salt to taste 
¼ tsp turmeric powder
 1 tbsp finely chopped garlic
 1 medium onion, finely chopped
 1½ tbsps green paste (2 green chillies 1 tsp jeera and a handful of coriander leaves paste)4
 ½ cup yogurt + for serving 
¼ cup chopped fresh coriander 
2 tsps oil + for drizzling
 4-5 zip lock bags 
Banana leaf for plating
column25:
1. Add jowar flour, rice flour, wheat flour, chickpea flour, salt, turmeric powder, garlic, onion, green paste, yogurt and chopped coriander in a bowl. Mix well. Add little water, combine well and knead to soft dough. 
2. Divide the dough into equal portions. On a worktop, place a zip lock bag, drizzle oil over it to grease, take ball size dough, grease hand with water and flatten the dough by tapping it with little pressure from hands. Keep it thick.
 3. Heat a non-stick tawa, add flattened dough placing moistened face down, flip on another side drizzle oil on both sides and cook for 5-6 minutes over medium heat till golden brown specs appear. Drain on an absorbent paper.
 4. Transfer prepared dhapates on a banana leaf kept over serving plate.
 5. Serve hot with yogurt.

column24:
1 cup gram flour
 3 tablespoons oil + for greasing and deep-frying
 1 teaspoon mustard seeds
 ½ teaspoon asafoetida
 1 tablespoons ginger-garlic paste 
1½ cups finely chopped fresh coriander leaves 
1 teaspoon red chilli powder
 ½ teaspoon turmeric powder
 ½ cup roasted and crushed peanuts 
Salt to taste
column25:
1. Take gram flour in a bowl. Add some water and whisk well. 
2. Heat 3 tablespoons oil in a non-stick pan. Add mustard seeds and let it splutter. Add asafoetida and ginger-garlic paste and sauté for a minute.
 3. Add chopped coriander, chilli powder, turmeric powder, peanuts and salt, mix and cook for a minute.
 4. Add gram flour mixture, mix and cook till thick. Transfer in a round steel plate. 
5. Grease palms with some oil and spread the prepared mixture. Set aside to cool.
 6. Cut into cubes.
 7. Heat sufficient oil in a kadai. Deep-fry the cubes till golden and crisp. Drain on absorbent paper. 
8. Serve hot.

column2: Bharli Vangi/ Stuffed Brinjal/ Eggplant/ Baingan
column3: भर्ली वांगी/ भरवां ब्रिंजल/ बैंगन/ बिंगन
column24:
6-8 purple brinjals (vaangi/baingan)
 1 cup scraped fresh coconut 
¼ cup roasted peanuts, coarsely powdered 
1½ tsps red chilli powder 
3 tsps goda masala 
Salt to taste
 ¼ cup chopped fresh coriander leaves
 2 tsps chopped jiggery
 ¼ cup tamarind pulp 
4 tbsps oil 
1 tsp mustard seeds
 ¼ tsp asafoetida (hing)
 ¼ tsp turmeric powder
 2 tbsps chopped fresh coriander leaves
 Fresh coriander sprig for garnis
column25:
1. Trim the heads of the brinjals and make four slits from the top without separating the segments and make a small slit on the bottom. Transfer them in a bowl with water.
 2. To make the masala, take coconut in a large parat¸ add peanuts, red chilli powder, goda masala, salt, coriander leaves, jaggery, tamarind pulp and mix well. 
3. Generously stuff each brinjal with the masala. 
4. Heat oil in a kadai, add mustard seeds and let them change colour. Add asafoetida and turmeric powder and sauté for a few seconds. 
5. Add the stuffed brinjals along with the masala and sauté on high heat for 3-4 minutes or till the brinjals turn slightly golden brown. 
6. Reduce the heat to low, cover and cook for 2 minutes. Add ¼ cup water, mix, cover and cook for 15-20 minutes, sautéing in between. 
7. Sprinkle coriander leaves, switch the heat off and transfer into a serving bowl. Garnish with coriander sprig. Serve hot.

column2: Aluchi Patal Bhaji/ Colocassia Leaves Gravy
column3: अलुची पाटल भजी/ अरबी के पत्तों की ग्रेवी
column24:
2 bunch tender colocasia leaves (alu) with stems
½ medium white radish (mooli)
¼ cup soaked Bengal gram (chana dal)
¼ cup soaked raw peanuts
2-3 green chillies, broken
2 tbsps gram flour (besan)
2 tsps chopped jaggery
2 tsps tamarind pulp
Salt to taste
Tempering
1½ tbsps ghee
¼ tsp fenugreek seeds (methi dana)
1 tsp mustard seeds
¼ tsp asafoetida (hing)
¼ tsp turmeric powder
column25:
1. Peel the colocasia stems, make a cut in the centre to separate the leaves and the stems. Shred the leaves and finely chop the stems. Peel and slice the white radish.
2. Transfer the colocasia leaves and white radish into a pressure cooker, add Bengal gram, peanuts, green chillies and ½ cup water. Cover and cook under pressure till 3 whistles are given out. 
3. Open the cooker once the pressure has reduced completely, transfer into a deep pan.
4. Add gram flour, mix and cook for 1-2 minutes. Add 1½ cups water, mix and cook till the mixture comes to a boil. 
5. Add jaggery, tamarind pulp and salt and mix well. Cook for 1-2 minutes and take the pan off the heat.
6. For the tempering, heat ghee in a small tempering pan, add fenugreek seeds, mustard seeds and let them splutter. Add asafoetida, ¼ tsp turmeric powder and mix. Pour the tempering into the cooked mixture. Mix and transfer into a serving bowl. Serve hot.

column2: Bharli Bhendi/ Stuffed Ladies Finger/ Okra
column3: भरली भंती/ भरवां लेडीज फिंगर/ ओकरा
column24:
500 grams lady’s fingers (bhindi)
1 teaspoon red chilli powder
1½ tablespoons coriander powder
1 teaspoon cumin powder
2 teaspoons dried mango powder (amchur)
1 teaspoon turmeric powder
1 teaspoon garam masala powder
Salt to taste 
1 teaspoon + 2 tablespoons oil
6-8 shallots
Chapattis for serving
column25:
1. Trim the ends of the lady’s fingers and slit them with one side intact. 
2. To prepare masala, mix together chilli powder, coriander powder, cumin powder, dried mango powder, turmeric powder, garam masala powder and salt in a bowl. Add 1 teaspoon oil and mix well.  
3. Stuff the slits of lady’s fingers with some masala and place on a plate. Reserve the remaining masala. 
4. Heat remaining oil in a non-stick pan. Add stuffed ladyfingers, shallots and reserved masala, mix and cook on medium heat till lady’s fingers are fully done. 
5. Serve hot with chapattis.

column24:
1½ cups tukda basmati rice, soaked and drained
2 tablespoons ghee
1 tablespoon oil
1 teaspoon mustard seeds
2 green chillies, slit
8-10 ivy gourds (tendli), quartered
¼ teaspoon asafoetida
10-12 cashewnuts, soaked
1 teaspoon turmeric powder
2½ tablespoons goda masala
½ cup green peas, blanched
2 tablespoons grated jaggery
Salt to taste
1 tablespoon lemon juice
½ cup scraped fresh coconut
½ cup chopped fresh coriander leaves
column25:
1. Heat ghee and oil together in a deep non-stick pan, add 
        mustard seeds and let them splutter.
2. Add green chillies, ivy gourd, asafetida and cashewnuts and 
        mix well.
3. Add turmeric powder and goda masala and mix again. Add 
        green peas, mix, cover and cook for two to three minutes on 
        medium heat.
4. Add rice and mix well. Sauté for two to three minutes or till all 
        the moisture has evaporated.
5. Add about four cups of water and mix well. Increase heat, 
        cover and let the mixture boil.
6. Add jaggery and salt and mix well. Reduce heat, cover and 
        cook for four to five minutes.
7. Open the lid, add lemon juice and mix well. Cover again and 
        cook till rice is completely cooked.
8. Mix together coriander leaves and coconut in a bowl for 
        garnishing. 
9. Transfer the rice into a serving dish, garnish with coriander 
        leaves and coconut and serve hot.

  chilli)
• 1 small boiled peeled and mashed Potato
• 2 cups chopped Shepu leaves
• 1/2 tsp Salt
column25:
Heat up oil in a pan. Add cumin seeds and let them sizzle up. 
• Add chilli garlic paste and fry for a minute. 
• Add potato. You can add turmeric powder if you want. 
• Pluck shepu leaves, wash it really good and chop it. Add shepu 
  leaves. Mix well. 
• Cover and cook for about 5-7 minutes. 
• Open the lid and mix again. 
• Add salt. Cook uncovered for about 5-7 minutes. 
• Shepuchi bhaji is already. 
• Shepuchi bhaji goes well with chapatti phulka. 
• It goes well with rice as side dish too.

½ cup sugar
2 tbsp butter
½ cup maize kernels (dry corn kernels)
Salt to taste
column25:
1. Heat the butter and salt in a pressure cooker, add the dry corn kernels and sauté on a medium flame for 30 seconds.
2. Cover the pressure cooker with a lid, but do not close it completely, cook on a medium flame for 5 minutes without a whistle. Keep aside.
3. Put the sugar in a deep non-stick pan, cook on a slow flame for 4 to 5 minutes, while tilting the pan occasionally.
4. Switch off the flame, add the prepared popcorn and mix well.
5. Place them on a big plate or thali and cool completely.
6. Separate them lightly with your fingers.
    Serve or store in an air-tight container. Use as required.

column24:
2 tbsp oil
▢¼ cup peanut / groundnut
▢2 tbsp roasted split gram dal / putani / daria / roasted chana dal / pottu kadalai
▢1 tsp mustard / rai
▢1 dried red chilli, broken
▢pinch of hing / asafoetida
▢few curry leaves
▢¼ tsp turmeric / haldi
▢½ tsp kashmiri red chilli powder / lal mirch powder
▢3 cup murmura / puffed rice / churumuri / mandakki
▢1 tsp powdered sugar
▢¼ tsp salt
▢¾ cup hot sev, optional
column25:
firstly, in a large kadai heat 2 tbsp oil and add ¼ cup peanut.
saute on medium flame till the peanuts turn golden and crunchy.
now add 2 tbsp putani and roast on low flame. set aside.
further add 1 tsp mustard, 1 dried red chilli, a pinch of hing and few curry leaves.
saute and splutter well.
additionally, add ¼ tsp turmeric and ½ tsp chilli powder. saute on low flame.
now add 3 cup murmura and mix gently coating spices well.
turn off the flame and add 1 tsp powdered sugar, ¼ tsp salt and ¾ cup hot sev. mix well.
finally, cool the spicy murmura completely and store in airtight container for 2 months.

column24:
• 1 tbsp Oil
• Raw peanuts
• Mustard seeds
• Cumin seeds,
• A pinch Asafoetida
• Finely chopped Green chillies
• Curry leaves
• Finely chopped Onion
• 2 cups leftover Rice
• Salt to taste
• Sugar
• Finely chopped Coriander
column25:
Heat up oil in a pan. 
• Add some raw peanuts in it and fry them until they turn reddish. 
• Remove them from oil and keep aside. 
• Add mustard seeds and let them pop up. Add cumin seeds and 
  let them sizzle up. 
• Add asafoetida, green chillies, curry leaves and finely chopped 
  onion. 
• Fry the onion on medium heat for about 4-5 minutes until it turns 
  soft. No need to change its colour. 
• Add rice, salt, sugar to taste and mix well. You can use any rice 
  you want. 
• If you have added salt while cooking add just a little now. 
• Cover and steam the rice for about 5 minutes. 
• Add lots of finely chopped coriander and mix well. 
• While serving, take out rice into a dish and garnish with fried 
  peanuts. 
• You can also add fine shev, fresh or dried coconut and again 
  coriander.
