column24:
1½ cups gram flour (besan)
1½ tablespoons oil
Salt to taste
½ teaspoon red chilli powder
1 teaspoon mustard seeds 
½ teaspoon asafoetida (hing)
6-8 curry leaves
3 green chillies, slit
1 tablespoon chopped garlic
2 large onions, finely chopped
½ teaspoon turmeric powder
Chopped fresh coriander leaves for garnishing
column25:
1. Heat oil in a non-stick pan.
2. Combine gram flour, salt, chilli powder and 5 cups water and whisk well to make a smooth batter.
3. Add mustard seeds to hot oil and let it splutter. Add asafoetida and curry leaves and let the curry leaves crackle. Add green chillies and garlic and sauté for 30 seconds. 
4. Add onions and sauté till golden brown. Add salt and turmeric powder and mix well. 
5. Add the batter, mix, reduce heat, cover and cook for 10-12 minutes.
6. Garnish with some coriander leaves and serve hot with ukadichya bhakrya.

column3: ग्रिल्ड काली मिर्च, सब्जियां और पनीर (40 ग्राम)
column24:
1 1/2 cup paneer (cubed in 1” square and 1/2” thick)
1/2 cup bell pepper (cubed, yellow and green to give the color)
1/2 cup cherry tomatoes
2 tsp oil
1 Tbsp green chili (finely chopped, optional)
2 Tbsp cilantro (finely chopped, hara dhania)
1 tsp fresh lemon juice
1/2 tsp salt
1/2 tsp black salt
1/2 tsp roasted cumin seed powder
1/8 tsp black pepper
1/8 tsp red chili powder
column25:
Mix the spice mix and keep aside. you can make this spice mix in a large quantity and keep it ready to go whenever you need it.

Heat heavy flat frying pan on low medium heat, add the oil in to warm frying pan. Spread the paneer cubes don’t over lap them. Grill the paneer from both sides, this should take about 2 minutes. Take them out from frying pan.
Use the same pan and grill the bell pepper, for about 2 minutes stirring occasionally, bell pepper will have some brown spots. Take them out from frying pan.
Use the same pan and grill the tomatoes for about 1-2 minutes, tomatoes will have some blisters. Take them out from frying pan.
In a bowl toss the paneer with spice mix, use the spice mix about in half the quantity, adjust for you taste, cilantro, green chili and lemon juice.
Serve the grilled paneer with side of bell pepper and tomatoes and sprinkle little spice mix over bell pepper and tomatoes.
A healthy and delicious appetizer is ready to serve.
Recipe Notes
Note: This spice mix known as chaat masala can also be used to spice up any food. It especially tastes good when it is sprinkled over sliced cucumber and tomato or over pakoras. You can make the chaat masala in a larger quantity and keep it ready to go whenever you need it.

column24:
3 medium potatoes (aloo), peeled 
1 small cauliflower (gobhi), separated into medium florets
 1½ tablespoons oil
 1 teaspoon cumin seeds (jeera) 
1 inch ginger, cut into thin strips
 2 green chillies, slit
 ¼ teaspoon turmeric powder
 1 medium onion, finely chopped
 1 teaspoon red chilli powder
 1½ teaspoons coriander powder
 Salt to taste
 1 medium tomato, finely chopped 
1 tablespoon chopped fresh coriander leaves + for garnishing
column25:
. Heat oil in a non-stick pan. Add cumin seeds and when it changes colour, add half of ginger strips and green chillies and sauté. 
2. Add turmeric powder and onion sauté till onion turns translucent. 
3. Cut potatoes into ½ inch pieces. 
4. Add chilli powder and coriander powder to sautéed onion and sauté for 1 minute. Add potato pieces and toss. Add salt, cover and cook on medium heat for 1-2 minutes.
 5. Add cauliflower florets, tomato and coriander leaves, toss, cover, reduce heat and cook for 20-25 minutes, sprinkling some water 1-2 times in between.
 6. Serve hot garnished with remaining ginger strips and some coriander leaves.

column24:
2 tbsps oil
2 green chillies
1 large onion, finely chopped
2½ tsps ginger-garlic paste 
2 medium tomatoes, finely chopped
4 medium potatoes, peeled
½ tsp turmeric powder
2 tsps red chilli powder
2 tsps coriander powder
1 tsp cumin powder
2 medium capsicum, cut into 1 inch dices
1 tsp Tata Sampann Kitchen King Masala
¼ cup roasted peanuts
1½ tbsps chopped fresh coriander leaves 
¼ lemon wedge 
Fresh coriander sprigs for garnish
column25:
1. Heat oil in a wok, add cumin seeds and let them change colour. Chop green chillies and add them into the pan.
2. Add the onion and mix well. Cook till translucent. Add ginger-garlic paste and sauté for 1-2 minutes.
3. Add tomatoes and mix well. Add salt, mix and cook till the tomatoes turn pulpy.
4. Cut potatoes in 1 inch cubes and set aside.
5. In the tomatoes mixture, add turmeric powder, red chilli powder, coriander powder, cumin powder and sauté for 1-2 minutes or till the oil separates.
6. Add the cubed potatoes and mix well. Adjust salt and toss. 
7. Add ¾ cup water and mix well. Let the mixture come to a boil. Reduce the heat, cover and cook till the potatoes are ¾ cooked. 
8. Add capsicums and mix well. Cook for 4-5 minutes. Add Tata Sampann Kitchen King Masala and mix well.
9. Meanwhile, coarsely crush peanuts in a mortar pestle and add ¾ into the pan.
10. Add chopped coriander and squeeze lemon and mix well.  Take the pan off the heat.
11. Transfer the prepared Sabzi into a serving bowl, garnish with remaining peanuts and coriander sprigs. Serve hot.

column24:
2-3 kurmura laddoo
 20 strawberries 
3 tbsps blueberry jam
 ½ cup whisked yogurt + a little to drizzle 
A little mixed fruit jam
column25:
1. Roughly chop strawberries. 
2. Put blueberry jam in a bowl, add ½ cup whisked yogurt and mix well. 
3. Rub a little mixed fruit jam on the insides of serving glass cups.
4. Crush kurmura laddoos coarsely in a bowl. 
5. Divide most of it between the serving cups. Put blueberry yogurt over it. 
6. Top it with strawberries, drizzle a little plain yogurt on top. Sprinkle a little crushed kurmura laddoo and serve immediately.

column24:
200 grams cottage cheese (paneer)
2 medium green capsicums, cut into 1 inch pieces    
1½ tablespoons oil      
½ teaspoon mustard seeds     
A pinch asafoetida    
2-3 tablespoons peanuts      
¼ teaspoon turmeric powder   
Salt to taste
1½ tablespoons grated jaggery     
Masala  
½ cup scraped coconut     
3 tablespoons sesame seeds    
2 tablespoons split Bengal gram  
2 tablespoons coriander seeds   
¼ teaspoon fenugreek seeds     
4-5 dried red chillies (bedgi)      
2 tablespoons tamarind pulp 
Toasted sesame seeds for garnishing
column25:
. For masala, dry roast the coconut and sesame seeds separately in a pan till fragrant and lightly coloured.  Transfer into a plate and set aside to cool.
2. Add split Bengal gram, coriander seeds, fenugreek seeds and red chillies and sauté till fragrant.  Grind this along with the coconut, sesame seeds and tamarind pulp to a fine paste with three-fourth cup of water.
3. Cut cottage cheese into small cubes. 
4. For tempering, heat oil in a non-stick pan, add mustard seeds, asafoetida, tumeric powder and ground paste and mix well. Add 2-3 tablespoons water and mix well. Add jaggery, tamarind pulp and mix well. Add cottage cheese cubes and mix well. Add salt, peanuts and capsicum and mix well. Cook for 2-3 minutes.
5.  Serve hot garnished with sesame seeds.

column24:
Gatte
1¼ cups gram flour (besan)  
A pinch of carom seeds (ajwain)
¼ tsp turmeric powder
¼ tsp red chilli powder
Salt to taste
1 tsp garam masala powder
½ tsp cumin powder
A pinch of baking soda
2 tbsps yogurt
1 tsp ginger-garlic-green chilli paste
2 tbsps + ½ tsp oil
Sabzi
1 cup yogurt
¼ tsp turmeric powder
½ tsp red chilli powder
½ tsp cumin powder
Salt to taste
½ tsp ginger-garlic-green chilli paste
2 tbsps ghee
1 tsp cumin seeds
¼ tsp asafoetida (hing)
2 dried red chillies
1 large onion, finely chopped
1 cup fresh tomato puree
¼ tsp dry fenugreek leaves (kasuri methi)
½ tsp garam masala powder
2 tbsps chopped fresh coriander leaves
Fresh coriander sprig for garnish
column25:
1. For making the gatte, take gram flour in a bowl, add carom seeds, turmeric powder, red chilli powder, salt, garam masala powder, cumin powder, baking soda, yogurt, ginger-garlic-green chilli paste, 2 tbsps oil, and ¼ cup water and knead to a semi-soft dough. Cover with a  damp muslin cloth and set aside for 10-15 minutes.
2. Divide the dough into equal portions and shape each into an oblong shape. 
3. Boil sufficient water in a non-stick deep pan, add salt and remaining oil along with the shaped dough portions and boil for 8-10 minutes. Drain on to a plate, pour 2 cups cooking liquor over it and cut the cooked dough portions into ½ inch discs, these are called gatte. Set aside until in use.
4. For the sabzi, heat ghee in a kadai, add cumin seeds and let them change colour. Add asafoetida, dried red chillies and sauté for a few seconds.
5.  Add onion, mix and sauté till it turns golden brown. Add tomato puree, mix and cook for 4-5 minutes.
6. Add yogurt mixture, mix and cook till the fat separates. Add dry fenugreek leaves, mix and cook for a minute.
7. Add the cooked gatte, mix and cook further for 6-8 minutes. Add garam masala powder and coriander leaves and mix well. Take the kadai off the heat and transfer into a serving bowl.
8. Garnish with coriander sprig and serve hot.

column24:
250 gms tinned jackfruit pieces
3 tbsps oil + to deep fry
¼ cup chopped onions
1 black cardamom, seeds separated
4-5 dried red chillies, broken
¾ tsp roasted cumin powder
½ tsp garam masala powder
2 tsps coriander powder
½ tsp Mexican chilli powder
½ tsp red chilli powder
¼ tsp turmeric powder
1 cup tomato puree
Salt to taste
column25:
. Drain the jackfruit pieces and deep fry till golden. Drain on absorbent paper.
2. Heat 3 tbsps oil in another pan, add onions and saute till well browned.
3. Add black cardamom seeds and red chillies and continue to saute for 2 minutes.
4. Add roasted cumin powder and garam masala powder and saute for 1 minute
5. Add coriander powder, Mexican chilli powder, red chilli powder and turmeric powder and mix well.
6. Add tomato paste or tomato puree and mix well. Saute till oil begins to separate. Add salt and mix. 
7. Add fried jackfruit pieces and mix well. Ideally keep the curry for 1 day so that the jack fruit pieces soak in the masala well.   
8. Next day heat the curry and serve hot with roti.

column24:
750 grams bottle gourd   
5 tablespoons gram flour  
½ teaspoon red chilli powder
Salt to taste
12 pieces of tamarind with seeds 
Oil for deep-frying
½ teaspoon garam masala powder
2 tablespoons chopped fresh coriander
Gravy
3 tablespoons oil
2 medium onions, chopped  
5 medium tomatoes, puréed  
¾ teaspoon turmeric powder
¾ teaspoon red chilli powder
1½ tablespoons coriander powder
Salt to taste
column25:
1. For the kofte, peel and grate the bottle gourd. Squeeze to remove excess water. Add the gram flour, chilli powder and salt, and mix well. Divide the mixture into twelve equal portions. 
2. Stuff one piece of tamarind into each portion and shape into a round kofta. Remove the tamarind seeds if desired.
3. Heat sufficient oil in a non-stick kadai and deep-fry the kofte, in small batches, for two to three minutes, or until golden brown and crisp on the outside. Drain on absorbent paper and set aside.  
4. For the gravy, heat the oil in a non-stick pan; add the onions and sauté until light golden brown. Add the tomato purée and cook till the oil rise to the surface.
5. Add the turmeric powder, chilli powder and coriander powder. Continue to sauté on medium heat for one minute. Add two tablespoons of water and sauté till the oil rises to the surface again.
6. Add two cups of water and bring to a boil. Add the salt, lower the heat and simmer for five minutes.  Keep the gravy hot.
7. To serve, arrange the kofte on a serving platter and pour the gravy over them. Sprinkle garam masala powder and garnish with the chopped coriander.

column24:
2 medium potatoes (aloo), peeled and cut into cubes
½ cup green peas (matar)
1 tablespoon oil
1 teaspoon cumin seeds
1 medium onion, chopped
Salt to taste
½ cup tomato puree
1 tablespoon ginger-garlic paste
1 teaspoon cumin powder
1 teaspoon coriander powder
½ teaspoonturmeric powder 
1 teaspoon red chilli powder
1 tablespoon chopped fresh coriander leaves 
1 teaspoon garam masala powder
column25:
1. Heat oil in a non-stick pan. Add cumin seeds and sauté till fragrant. Add onion and salt, mix and sauté till onion turns golden. 
2. Add tomato puree and mix well. Add ginger-garlic paste, mix, cover and cook for 2-3 minutes.
3. Add cumin powder, coriander powder, turmeric powder, chilli powder and chopped coriander and mix well. Add potatoes, green peas, mix and cook for a minute. 
4. Add garam masala powder and ½ cup water, mix, cover and cook on medium heat till potatoes are done.
5. Serve hot garnished with a coriander sprig.

column24:
400 gms button mushrooms
½ tsp fennel seeds (saunf)
½ star anise (badiyan)
1 tbsp coriander seeds
1 tsp cumin seeds
1 green cardamom
1 inch cinnamon stick
10 black peppercorns
6-8 cloves
4-5 dried red chillies
3 tbsps oil
½ cup scraped coconut
15-20 curry leaves
1 medium onion, chopped
1 tbsp ginger paste
1 tbsp garlic paste
1½ cups chopped tomatoes
Salt to taste
1 tsp poppy seeds (khuskhus), soaked
column25:
1. In a small non-stick pan, dry roast fennel seeds, star anise, coriander seeds, cumin seeds, green cardamom, cinnamon, black peppercorns, cloves and red chillies till fragrant.
2. Heat oil in another non-stick pan.
3. Add coconut to the pan with spices and saute for 2-3 minutes.
4. Add curry leaves and onions to the oil and saute till golden.  Add tomatoes, mushrooms and salt and mix.
5. Grind the sautéed ingredients with poppy seeds to a fine paste with a little water.
6. Add it to the mushrooms and mix well.  Cover and cook on low heat for 5 minutes.
7. Serve hot with chapattis.

▢ ½ tsp fennel / saunf
▢ few curry leaves

in a large kadai heat 4 tsp oil and splutter ½ tsp jeera, ½ tsp fennel, and few curry leaves.
add ½ onion, ½ tsp ginger garlic paste and 1 chilli. saute well making sure onions are cooked well.
squeeze of the bitter gourd and add to the kadai.
saute for a minute making sure the bitter gourd is roasted.
now add ¼ tsp turmeric, ½ tsp chilli powder, ½ tsp coriander powder, ¼ tsp garam masala and ½ tsp salt.

further, add ¾ cup tamarind extract and 1 tbsp jaggery.
cover and simmer for 20 minutes or until the bitter gourd are cooked well.
finally, add coriander leaves and enjoy bitter gourd curry with hot steamed rice or chapati.

Sugar - 1 1/2 tablespoons or 2 gm Stevia Powder
Grated apple - 150 grams 
Cardamom powder - 1/4 teaspoon 
Pistachios - for garnishing
column25:
PREPARATION 
1. In a pan, add 50 grams oats and dry roast for 3-4 minutes or until turns light brown in colour. 
2. Remove it from heat. 
3. Now, transfer it in a blender and blend it into fine powder. 
4. Set aside. 
5. In a small bowl, add 30 ml of warm milk, 1/4 teaspoon saffron and mix it well. 
6. Soak for 30 minutes. 
7. In a pan, add 1 tablespoon pistachios, 1 tablespoon almonds and dry roast for 2-3 minutes. 
8. Remove it from heat. 
9. In a pan, add 750 ml milk and stir well. 
10. Cook for 4-5 minutes on medium heat. 
11. Add blended mixture and mix it well. 
12. Now, add soaked saffron milk, 1 1/2 tablespoons sugar and mix again. 
13. Cook for 5-7 minutes on medium heat. 
14. Add roasted nuts and give it a nice stir. 
15. Add 150 grams of grated apple and mix it well. 
16. Add 1/4 teaspoon cardamom powder and mix again. 
17. Cook for another 3-5 minutes on medium heat. 
18. Remove it from heat and cool for 30 minutes. 
19. Add the oats phirni into a serving dish. 
20. Garnish it with pistachios. 
21. Serve warm or chilled.

column24:
INGREDIENTS
2tbsp Bajra flour
2tbsp Ragi flour
2tbsp Jowar flour 
2tbsp Maize flour
Luke warm water (required to knead)
Ghee ½  tsp
column25:
METHOD
Heat water in a bowl. 
Mix all the flours together. Keep adding water enough to make soft pliable dough. 
Knead for few minutes untill it turns sticky. Add ghee and knead again. 
Brush ghee over the kneaded dough and keep it aside covered in moist muslin cloth for 15-30 minutes. 
Make small balls of the dough
Dust the rolling base with little amount of flour and roll using the rolling pin.
If the chapati is not rolling properly,  take two parchment papers or rice papers and keep the rolling dough in between them and then roll on to the plastic sheet.
Heat a griddle
When the griddle becomes hot, transfer the roti on it. Squeeze off excess water from the muslin cloth and smear water over the roti including the edges with the cloth. Do not pour water on roti. The roti must become moist all over.  By now the roti firms up from the centre. 
Flip the roti to the other side. Repeat dampening and then cover it. 
When the roti is cooked, remove from griddle and rub ½ tsp ghee over it. 
Serve hot with curries or vegetables.

column24:
INGREDIENTS
•Onion ¼ cup 
•Tomato ¼ cup
•Cauliflower ¼ cup 
•Peas ¼ cup
•Carrot ¼ cup
•Black Rice ¼ cup
•Oil 1 tsp
•Salt ¼ tsp
•Black pepper powder a pinch 
•Turmeric a pinch
•Coriander leaves a few
•Cumin
column25:
METHOD
1. Wash and soak black rice in water for 5-6 hours or overnight. Next day add the soaked rice to cooker along with 1 cup of water and pressure cook for 2 whistles.
2. Once pressure releases, drain excess water if any and gently fluff the rice and keep aside. The cooked rice will be sticky.
3. Heat a pan with oil. Once hot add bay leaf, cloves, star anise, cardamom and cumin seeds. Once it splutters, add ginger garlic paste and saute until raw smell goes.
4. Add slitted green chilli and chopped onion. Saute until onion turns translucent. Add chopped tomato and saute until it turns mushy.
5. Now add turmeric powder, garam masala and chilli powder. Saute for a minute and add chopped carrots.
6. Pour little water and add required salt. Mix and cook covered for few minutes until carrots gets cooked soft and becomes thick.
7. Add cooked black rice, mix with spoon without mashing the rice until it is coated well with masala. Cook for 2-3 minutes
8. Switch off and garnish with coriander leaves. Black rice pulao is ready. Serve hot with any raita.

column24:
INGREDIENTS:
1 grated fresh coconut
1-2 cups of water
column25:
METHOD:
For coconut milk
Take all the grated coconut in a blender jar.
Add the 1 cup water and blend on high till the coconut is ground well.
Strain in a cheesecloth/muslin or a fine sieve and collect the first extract in a bowl or pan.
This is the thick coconut milk or the first extract which is to be used for Icecream.
Then collect and put back the coconut residue into the blender.
Add 1 to 1.5 cups water and blend again.
Strain and collect this coconut milk in another bowl keep doing this for 2-3 times until all the milk is extracted out of the coconut. 
You can use this thin extracted milk for other recipes.

column24:
Servings: 4 
INGREDIENTS 
16 ounces tofu 
1 bell pepper 
½ onion 
2 teaspoons oil 
½ teaspoon salt 
½ teaspoon black pepper 
½ teaspoon onion powder 
½ teaspoon garlic powder 
¼ teaspoon turmeric powder 
1 tablespoon lemon juice
column25:
PREPARATION 
1. Drain tofu from a container, wrap it in a paper towel, and place it on a plate. Rest another plate on top of the tofu and microwave for 3-5 minutes. 
2. Unwrap the tofu and cut into cubes. 
3. Place the tofu in a bowl, and mash with a fork. 
4. Cut the top off a bell pepper and remove all the seeds and thinly slice. 
5. Chop the onion. 
6. Heat oil in a pan over medium heat. Add the onions and peppers, and cook until softened. 
7. Add in the tofu and cook on medium heat until most of the water has evaporated. 
8. Add the salt, pepper, onion powder, garlic powder, and cumin, and mix well, until all the seasonings are evenly distributed. 
9. Add the lemon juice to the tofu and mix until evenly combined. 
10. Remove the tofu from the heat. Serve and enjoy!

column24:
INGREDIENTS

½  cup cauliflower florets ( gobi )
½  tbsp chopped raw cashew nuts
½  onion medium-sized
¼  tsp finely chopped ginger
1 cloves garlic
¼  tsp cumin powder ( jeera powder )
A pinch turmeric powder (optional)
Black pepper (ground) to taste
¾  cup water or vegetable stock
½  tsp olive oil
Salt to taste
column25:
METHOD
Separate the cauliflower into small florets and rinse the florets.
Finely chop the onions and ginger.
Heat oil in a pan. Add cloves and saute for a couple of seconds.
Then add the finely chopped onions and ginger. Saute till the onions turn light brown in color
Now add the cauliflower florets along with salt, turmeric powder and cumin powder and stir fry for 2 minutes.
Then add the chopped cashew nuts along with water or vegetable stock. Bring the mixture to a boil. Then reduce heat and simmer on low flame for 10-12 minutes or till the cauliflower turns soft and is cooked.
Remove from heat and once it cools down slightly, discard the cloves. Blend the cauliflower mixture using a blender or mixer.
Now transfer the blended cauliflower mixture to the pan. Add freshly ground black pepper powder to taste. Check for salt and add some if needed. Once the soup turns warm, remove from heat.
Pour the gobi soup into serving bowls. Garnish with a few roasted cashew nuts and serve warm.

Ingredients 
Makes 4 servings 
1 pound (500g) salmon 
1 inch (2cm) piece of ginger, grated 
2 garlic cloves, minced 
1 tbsp (15g) sweet chili sauce 
1 tbsp (15ml) rice vinegar 
1 1/2 tbsp (30g) honey 
3 tbsp (45 ml) soy sauce 
1 tbsp (15g) sesame oil 
Sesame seeds for serving 
Green onion, chopped
column25:
1. In a small bowl combine ginger with garlic, soy sauce, sweet chili sauce, rice vinegar, honey and sesame oil. 
2. Cut the salmon in 4 pieces and season with salt and freshly ground black pepper. 
3. Place the salmon pieces in a bowl, pour the soy sauce marinade over it, cover and marinate for at least 30 minutes overnight. 
4. Preheat the oven to 400F (200C). Line a baking pan with parchment paper. 
5. Place the salmon pieces into the prepared pan and bake for 15-20 minutes. From 5 to 5 minutes brush the top with the marinade used. 
6. Sprinkle sesame seeds and chopped green onion on top and serve immediately over rice and vegetables. Enjoy!

column24:
Broccoli 
Butter/Oil - 1 Tsp
Onion - 1 No. Chopped
Garlic - 12 Cloves
Potato - 1 No. Chopped
Water
Salt
Pepper
column25:
1. Wash and clean the broccoli. Cut it roughly into small pieces and keep them aside.
2. Heat a pressure cooker and add butter/oil to it.
3. Once the butter is melted, add in the roughly chopped onions and garlic cloves.
4. Saute until the onions turn slightly transparent.
5. Add in the chopped potatoes, broccoli pieces, salt and crushed pepper. Mix it all well.
6. Add 2 cups of water into the pressure cooker, cover it with the lid and pressure cook the ingredients for at least 2 whistles on medium flame.
7. Transfer the cooked ingredients along with water to a large bowl and let it completely cool down.
8. Transfer the cooled down ingredients to a mixer jar and grind everything into smooth puree.
9. Now, transfer this puree to a sauce and dilute it with water if it is too thick. 
10. Check for seasoning and add salt, pepper powder if required.
11. Let the soup come to a boil and turn off the stove.
12. Wholesome Broccoli Soup is ready to be served hot and nice with any toasted bread of your choice.

column25:
Oil pulling is easy to do and involves just a few simple steps.

Here are the 4 simple steps to do oil pulling:

Measure one tablespoon of oil, such as coconut, sesame or olive oil.
Swish it around in your mouth for 15–20 minutes, being careful not to swallow any.
Spit the oil into a trash can once you’re done. Avoid spitting it into the sink or toilet, as this can cause a buildup of oil, which may lead to clogging.
Rinse your mouth well using water before eating or drinking anything.
Repeat these steps a few times per week or up to three times daily. You may also want to work your way up, starting with swishing for just 5 minutes and increasing the duration until you’re able to do it for a full 15–20 minutes.

column24:
3 cups pressed rice (poha)
2 tablespoons oil
1 teaspoon mustard seeds
1 teaspoon cumin seeds
¼ teaspoon asafoetida
3-4 curry leaves
2 green chillies, slit
1 medium onion, finely chopped
Salt to taste 
½ teaspoon turmeric powder
¾ cup bean sprouts
2 tablespoons chopped fresh coriander 
½ cup fresh pomegranate pearls
column25:
. Put the pressed rice in a sieve and place it over a bowl.  Pour sufficient water over it so that the pressed rice is well dampened.  
2. Heat oil in a non-stick pan, add mustard seeds, cumin seeds, asafoetida, curry leaves and green chillies and sauté for a minute.
3. Add onion and a little salt and mix well, cover and cook till the onion turns golden brown.
4. Add turmeric powder and a little water and mix well. Add the pressed rice and a little salt and mix well.
5. Add bean sprouts and quarter cup water and mix well. Cover and cook for five to seven minutes.
6. Add one tablespoon coriander leaves and mix well.
7. Serve hot, garnished with pomegranate pearls and remaining coriander leaves.

column24:
FOR DOSA BATTER:
 2 cup idli rice
 ½ cup urad dal
 ½ tsp methi / fenugreek
 1 cup poha / aval / flattened rice, thin
 water, for soaking & grinding
 2 tsp salt
 oil, for roasting
FOR MIX VEG TOPPING:
 1 onion, finely chopped
 1 carrot, grated
 ½ capsicum, finely chopped
 1 to mato, finely chopped
 1 inch ginger, finely chopped
 1 chilli, finely chopped
 few curry leaves, chopped
 2 tbsp coriander, finely chopped
 ¼ tsp salt
column25:
firstly, in a large bowl take 2 cup idli rice, ½ cup urad dal and ½ tsp methi.
soak for 5 hours adding water as required.
drain off the water and transfer to the mixi or grinder.
blend to smooth paste in batches adding water as required.
in a bowl take 1 cup poha and rinse well.
blend to smooth paste adding water if required.
mix the rice-urad dal batter and poha paste well.
cover and ferment in a warm place for 8 hours.
after 8 hours, the batter has doubled in size. mix gently without disturbing the air bubbles.
further add 2 tsp salt and mix well.
prepare the vegetable topping by taking 1 onion, 1 carrot, ½ capsicum and 1 tomato.
also add 1 inch ginger, 1 chilli, few curry leaves, 2 tbsp coriander and ¼ tsp salt.
mix well making sure everything is well combined.
heat the griddle and pour a ladleful of batter.
spread out in a circular motion slightly thick than regular masala dosa.
top with mix vegetable mixture uniformly and pat slightly.
also pour 1 tsp oil around the edges.
cover and roast the dosa to a golden brown from the bottom.
flip over and roast both sides.
finally, enjoy mixed vegetable uttapam with chutney

2 cups vermicelli

column25:
1. Roast vermicelli in a non-stick pan till brown. Remove from heat and set aside. 
2. Heat ghee in the same pan. Add mustard seeds and let it splutter. Add split black gram, green chillies, curry leaves and asafoetida. Mix well and add onion. Mix and sauté till onion is golden.

 4. Add roasted vermicelli, four cups hot water and salt. Mix, cover and cook till the vermicelli is done. 
5. Add green peas and cook for two minutes. 
6. Transfer into a serving bowl, garnish with coriander leaves and serve hot.

1. Heat ⅛ cup ghee in a non-stick pan, add semolina and roast till golden brown and fragrant. Transfer into a large bowl and allow to cool to room temperature. 
2. Heat remaining ghee in the same pan, add mustard seeds, asafoetida, split skinless black gram, green chillies and curry leaves and sauté for a few seconds or till everything crisps up. Transfer on a plate and allow to cool to room temperature. 
3. Crush the fried curry leaves and add them into the semolina and add the remaining fried mixture. Mix well.
 4. Add powdered sugar, salt and fruit salt and mix till well combined. Transfer into an air tight container and store up to 20 days in a dry place. 
5. For making the idlis, take 1 cup of the prepared premix in a large bowl. Add yogurt and ⅓ cup water and whisk well. Set aside for 10 minutes.
 6. Heat sufficient water in a steamer and add the prepared batter into each greased idli mould and steam for 8-10 minutes. 7. Take them off the heat and serve hot with tomato chutney and coconut chutney.

1. Coarsely grind together rice and coconut. Add 2 cups and grind into a smooth batter. Transfer in a bowl.

column2: Vegetable Besan Chilla Medium + Green Chutney
column24:
INGREDIENTS
1 cup Besan (gram flour)
¼ teaspoon Ajwain (Carom seeds)
1 teaspoon Red chili powder
1 teaspoon Coriander powder
¼ teaspoon Turmeric powder
¼ teaspoon Garam masala
Salt to taste
1 small Green chili chopped
¼ cup Tomato finely chopped
⅓ cup Red onion finely chopped
¼ cup Spinach (Palak) finely chopped
¼ cup Capsicum (Green bell pepper) finely chopped
¼ cup Carrot grated
2 tablespoons Cilantro or coriander leaves finely chopped
¼ cup Plain yogurt
1 ½ cups Water
Oil to shallow fry cheela
column25:
METHOD
Take besan, carom seeds, turmeric powder, red chili powder, coriander powder, garam masala and salt in a bowl and mix well.
Add all the vegetables and Mix well, so all the flour is coated to veggies.
Then mix in yogurt.
Add little water at a time and make lump free batter.
Batter should be runny , adjust the water to get right consistency of batter, Also do a taste test to check salt.
Heat a non stick pan or tawa on medium heat. Once hot brush the tawa with oil
Once oil is hot, pour the ladleful of batter and spread it to make round shape pancake.
Let the cheela gets cook on one side about 2 minutes or till gets golden brown.
Drizzle some oil on top and then flip it using spatula. Cook other side for 1-2 minutes.
Once both sides are cooked, remove it to plate and serve.
Repeat the same with rest of the batter.

column2: Ragi Roti With 1/2 Tsp Ghee (Finger Millet Chapati)
column3: 1/2 छोटा चम्मच घी के साथ रागी रोटी
column24:
INGREDIENTS
½ Cup Ragi flour
½ cup water (required to knead)
½  tsp A2 Ghee 
A pinch- Pink Himalayan salt
column25:
METHOD
Heat water in a bowl. Add a pinch of salt. When the water comes to the boil, reduce the flame to half. 
Add the flour in the water pan on reduced flame and let it stay for 10 seconds. Turn off the flame. 
Then mix it altogether using a wooden spatula. 
After mixing, cover it with a lid and let it stay for 2-3 minutes. 
Then transfer it into a plate and knead the dough by sprinkling required amount of water.    
After the dough is made, add ghee and mix well in the dough. 
Make small balls of the dough
Before rolling the dough ball, knead the ball 2-3 times again. 
Dust the rolling base with little amount of flour and roll using the rolling pin.
If the chapati is not rolling properly,  take two parchment papers or rice papers and keep the rolling dough in between them and then roll on to the plastic sheet.
Heat a griddle
When the griddle becomes hot, transfer the roti on it. 
When small bubble starts popping, Flip the roti to the other side. Cook the roti by slightly pressing it on all sides. 
Keep flipping and cooking untill completely cooked. 
When the roti is cooked, remove from griddle and rub ½ tsp ghee over it. 
Dust off the tawa from excess flour by using a cotton cloth. 
Serve chapati hot with curries or vegetables. 


*NOTE: Do not discard the husk after sieving. Add the sieved husk if it is free from any kind of contamination.

column25:
METHOD
Add water and rinsed black rice to a saucepan.
Over medium-high heat, bring the water to a boil. Add the salt, reduce heat, cover and cook for about 30-35 minutes. (Don't open the lid too often because this will let a lot of steam out.) Continue cooking until the rice is tender and chewy and all water is absorbed.
Take off the heat and let it stand covered for about 5 to 10 minutes then fluff with a fork and serve.

column24:
INGREDIENTS
1 medium head of cauliflower
1 teaspoon olive oil
juice of 1/2 lime
sea salt and freshly ground black pepper
1 tsp cumin seeds
1 green chilli sliced
1/2 tsp turmeric powder
salt to taste
2 tbsp coriander leaves (optional for garnishing)
column25:
METHOD
First, turn the cauliflower into cauliflower rice. Place the cauliflower florets into the food processor and pulse a few times until you have rice like texture. Alternatively you can use a box grater with medium sized holes.
Next heat oil in the pan or a skillet. Add the seasoning – cumin and green chilli. Stir for about 5 seconds.
Add cauliflower rice, spice powders, salt, and saute to mix well. Cook for 5-7 minutes, stirring occasionally over medium heat.
Add coriander leaves, just before serving and mix well.
Serve this  spiced cauliflower rice with your favorite curries.

column24:
What You Need To Make a Cauliflower Crust Pizza:
2 cups of grated CAULIFLOWER
1 cup of freshly grated PARMESAN CHEESE
1 EGG beaten
PARCHMENT PAPER to line your baking sheet
and whatever PIZZA SAUCE and
PIZZA TOPPINGS you desire
column25:
How to Cook the A Cauliflower Crust Pizza Recipe:
Grate fresh cauliflower florets into granules resembling "poprocks"
Heat the grated cauliflower in a skillet--don't add oil or water--use medium heat, not too hot. Stir until the cauliflower has dried out somewhat, it won't dry completely, but the dryer the better. Heat at least 10 minutes, just enough to evaporate the moisture, not enough to color or cook down.
Remove skillet from burner and set aside to allow cauliflower to slightly cool.
In a bowl, beat 1 egg.
Add grated Parmesan cheese to the egg. You can substitute, asiago or romano cheeses, just be sure you use a hard cheese for best results.
Add the cauliflower to the bowl and mix well with the egg and cheese and form into a ball.
Spread parchment paper onto a baking sheet. DEFINITELY USE PARCHMENT PAPER, otherwise your crust may tear when you try to pick it up (and also be sure not to mix up parchment paper with wax paper!)
Place the balled cauliflower and cheese onto the parchment paper and spread out into a pizza shape about ¼ inch thick.  The crust will be about 10" across.
Do not make the edges of the crust too thin; keep the size of the crust uniform for even cooking. The cauliflower will darken quite rapidly around the edges if too thin.
Place crust into an oven preheated to 400 degrees Fahrenheit and cook approx. 15-20 minutes until the crust has colored and firmed up.
Remove cauliflower pizza crust from the oven and top with your favorite pizza sauce. Use a marinara sauce, pesto, white sauce, or whatever. Top with your favorite pizza toppings.
Return pizza to the oven and continue to cook at 400 F for about 10 minutes until the toppings are done, watch the edges of the cauliflower crust; the edges will darken too much if overcooked.
Remove the pizza from the oven and set on a cooling rack -or don't- this step isn't make or break.
And that's it.
eat and enjoy.

METHOD

Drain water and grind moong Dal with ginger, green chillies, hing, cumin, methi seeds, fennel seeds to smooth paste.
Mix together the moong dal paste, spinach, chopped onions, chopped tomatoes, salt, corriander leaves.
On a heated non stick tawa, brush a little amount of oil and spread a laddle full of this mixture. Cover and cook for a minute. Repeat the same on the other side.

column24:
INGREDIENTS
½  cup cauliflower rice
½  medium onion finely chopped
½  cup mix vegetables (carrot, green beans ,green peas)
1 tsp coconut oil or ghee
½ tsp mustard seeds
5-6 curry leaves
½  green chilies
½ tsp ginger minced
a pinch of asafetida (hing)
salt to taste
1 tsp lemon juice
1 tsp cilantro (coriander leaves) for garnish
1 tsp grated coconut
column25:
METHOD
Firstly separate cauliflower into florets and stalks. Wash thoroughly. Mince or grate florets with the help of grater or food processor to resemble fine rice or semolina.
Heat  coconut oil or ghee in a kadai. Add mustard seeds, let the mustard splutter.
Add curry leaves, ginger, green chilli and hing. Saute for another 30-40 seconds.
Next add the onions and cook till the onions become soft.
Then add the mix vegetables and cook for 2-3 minutes.
Now add cauliflower rice, salt, mix well and Cover with a lid and cook on medium low heat for 4 to 5 minutes. Stir in between and turn off the flame.
Once the cauliflower is cooked, remove from heat and garnish with coriander, lime juice, and grated coconut, mix well and serve hot.
Cauliflower Upma is Ready & serve hot with greek yogurt or coconut chutney.

column24:
INGREDIENTS

1 tsp ghee or coconut oil
½ medium chopped onions
1 tsp grated ginger
2 cloves garlic, minced
½ small beetroot (peeled and cubed)
1 cup diced carrots
2 cups water 
salt and pepper to taste
lemon juice optional
column25:
METHOD
In a pressure cooker, add the oil and heat it for about a minute. Fry the onions, ginger and garlic. Add a pinch or two of salt to quicken the cooking of onions.
Once the onions become translucent, add the beets, carrots, and water. Use water just enough to cover the vegetables. Add some more salt and pepper. Close the lid and cook it for 2 whistles. This should take about 15 minutes.
Once the pressure is released, open the lid of the cooker and blend the cooked vegetables using an immersion blender. If you choose to puree it in a regular blender you will have to wait for the vegetables to cool down completely.
Add some more water if you need a thinner consistency soup. Taste and season with some more salt and pepper accordingly.
Some lemon juice can be added  before serving and garnish it with some fresh coriander leaves.

column24:
for soup:
▢3 tsp oil
▢3 clove garlic, finely chopped
▢1 inch ginger, finely chopped
▢2 tbsp spring onion, chopped (optional)
▢1 carrot, finely chopped
▢5 beans, finely chopped
▢½ capsicum, finely chopped
▢2 tbsp cabbage, finely chopped (Optional)
▢2 tbsp peas / matar
▢2 tbsp sweet corn
▢4 cup water
▢¾ tsp salt
▢1 tbsp vinegar
▢½ tsp mixed herbs
▢½ tsp chilli flakes
▢½ tsp pepper powder
▢2 tbsp spring onion, chopped
for slurry:
▢1 tsp corn flour
▢¼ cup water
column25:
1. Firstly, in a large kadai heat 3 tsp oil and saute 3 clove garlic, 1 inch ginger and 2 tbsp spring onion.
2. Add 1 carrot, 5 beans, ½ capsicum and stir fry for a minute.
3. Also add 2 tbsp cabbage, 2 tbsp peas, 2 tbsp sweet corn and saute slightly.
4. Now add 4 cup water and ¾ tsp salt. mix well.
5. Cover and boil for 5 minutes or until vegetables are cooked well.
6. Further in a small bowl take 1 tsp corn flour and ¼ cup water.
7. Mix well making sure there are no lumps.
8. Pour the corn flour slurry and boil for 3-4 minutes or until soup thickens.
9. Add 1 tbsp vinegar, ½ tsp mixed herbs, ½ tsp chilli flakes and ½ tsp pepper powder.
10. Mix well making sure the spices are well combined.
11. Finally, top with 2 tbsp spring onion and enjoy vegetable soup.

column24:
Prep Time: 15 mins
Cook Time: 50 mins
Servings: 4  

To Cook The Rice

Basmati Rice - 1 Cup
Salt - 1/2 Tsp
Juice Of 1/2 Lemon

To Marinate The Vegetables

Curd - 1 Cup
Ginger Garlic Paste - 2 Tsp
Salt - 2 Tsp
Turmeric Powder - 1 Tsp
Chilli Powder - 4 Tsp
Cumin Powder - 2 Tsp
Coriander Powder - 2 Tsp
Garam Masala - 2 Tsp
Kasuri Methi - 1 Tbsp
Onion - 1 No.
Green Chilli - 3 Nos
Tomato - 2 Nos
Cauliflower - 1 No.
Green Peas - 1 Cup
Fried Onions
Mint Leaves
Coriander Leaves

To Dum Cook

Vegetable Mixture
Cooked Rice
Ghee
Saffron Milk
Fried Onions
Mint Leaves
Coriander Leaves
column25:
Method:

1. Wash and soak rice for 30 mins in water.
2. Take water in a pot and boil it.
3. Add salt to it and then add in the soaked rice.
4. Cook the rice until nicely done. Squeeze some lemon juice to keep the rice fluffy.
5. Take curd in a large bowl. Add ginger garlic paste, salt, turmeric powder, red chilli powder, cumin powder, coriander powder, garam masala powder, kasuri methi and mix it all well.
6. To this, add onions, green chillies, tomatoes, green peas, cauliflower, mint leaves, coriander and fried onions.
7. Mix it well and marinate for 10 mins.
8. In another bowl, mix warm milk and saffron strands together, keep it aside.
9. Take oil and ghee in a pot. 
10. Add in the marinated vegetables, mix and cook for 15 mins by covering the pot with a lid.
11. Add the required amount of salt and mix well. Take half cauliflower masala aside into a bowl.
12. Spread the cauliflower masala in the pot evenly and put a layer of cooked rice over.
13. Spread the rice too evenly and sprinkle some ghee, saffron milk, fried onions, mint leaves, coriander leaves.
14. Repeat the same with remaining masala and rice.
15. Cover the pot with a lid and dum cook the biryani for 15 mins.
16. Yummiest Cauliflower Biryani is ready to be served hot with some Raitha and Brinjal Curry by the side.

column24:
INGREDIENTS
2 Eggs
¼  cup Spinach
2tbsp Coriander leaves
¼ tsp Himalayan salt
1 green chilli
⅛ tsp turmeric
1 tsp Butter or ghee
¼ tsp oregano
⅛ tsp black pepper
½ inch Ginger
50g Paneer
column25:
METHOD
Chop the green leafy veggies. 
Rinse spinach and coriander leaves in lot of running water and drain completely
Fine chop green chillies. Mince or grate the ginger.
Break the eggs into a bowl. Add chopped spinach, coriander leaves, onions, salt, ginger, turmeric and green chilli. 
Beat all of them together until the mixture turns frothy.
Heat a pan and brush the pan with ghee or butter on a medium heat. When the pan is hot enough, pour the mixture evenly. 
If required, spread the spinach evenly over the egg. Cook on medium heat until the base is set and firm. 
Flip it and add scrambled paneer over half the omelette. Add spices over the scrambled paneer.  
Cook until the eggs are cooked completely. 
Sprinkle italian herbs and black pepper powder. Fold half.
Serve hot with mint, coriander or imli chutney.

column24:
INGREDIENTS
2tbsp Bajra flour
2tbsp Ragi flour
2tbsp Whole wheat flour
2tbsp Rolled Oats flour
Luke warm water (required to knead)
Ghee ½  tsp
column25:
METHOD
Take oats in a mixer and make powder. 
Heat water in a bowl, add to the ground oats and set them  aside for 5 minutes. 
To this add all the other flours. Mix and keep adding water enough to make soft pliable dough. 
Knead for few minutes untill it turns sticky. Add ghee and knead again. 
Brush ghee over the kneaded dough and keep it aside covered in moist muslin cloth for 15-30 minutes. 
Make small balls of the dough
Dust the rolling base with little amount of flour and roll using the rolling pin.
If the chapati is not rolling properly, take two parchment papers or rice papers and keep the rolling dough in between them and then roll on to the plastic sheet.
Heat a griddle
When the griddle becomes hot, transfer the roti on it. Squeeze off excess water from the muslin cloth and smear water over the roti including the edges with the cloth. Do not pour water on roti. The roti must become moist all over.  By now the roti firms up from the centre. 
Flip the roti to the other side. Repeat dampening and then cover it. 
When the roti is cooked, remove from griddle and rub ½ tsp ghee over it. 
Serve hot with curries or vegetables. 


*NOTE: Do not discard the husk after sieving. Add the sieved husk if it is free from any kind of contamination.

Take the oil in a non-stick pan. Heat up a little
 Add all of the vegetables.
Stir fry for a while
In a cup add Soy sauce, vinegar, with all the spices. Make a slurry
Evenly spread the slurry over the veggies
Cook for a while
Sprinkle the sesame seeds
Toss around the vegetables for a while and they are done!

Pound the chicken using a meat mallet or rolling pin
Mix all the ingredients in a mixing bowl except chicken and whisk them together.
Add pounded chicken and leave it to marinate for 20-25 minutes.
On a grilling pan, brush a little amount of oil and place the marinated chicken pieces.
Grill them completely
Sprinkle sesame seeds over them and serve with stir fry veggies

column2: Roasted Gnocchi & Brussel Sprouts With Meyer Lemon Vinaigrette
column3: भुना हुआ ग्नोची और ब्रुसेल स्प्राउट्स मेयर लेमन विनैग्रेट के साथ
column24:
•        Brussel sprouts 100g
•        Onion 50g
•        Gnocchi 50g
•        Lemon juice 10g
•        Extra virgin olive oil 5g
•        Sun-dried tomato 20g
•        Lemon
•        Salt & pepper
column25:
1.         In a large bowl, add lemon, Brussel sprouts, onion, gnocchi, extra virgin olive oil, salt & pepper. 
2.        Mix all the ingredients nicely. 
3.        Roast at 450-degree for 18-20 mins. 
4.        Add the roasted vegetable to another bowl, add lemon juice, sun-dried tomatoes, salt, and pepper, mix it well and Enjoy!

column24:
•        Cauliflower-150g
•        Lemon-20g
•        Olive oil- 10g
•        Parmesan cheese- 5g
•        Salt & pepper
column25:
1.        Cut cauliflower into pieces.
2.        Remove the skin of lemon, cut the lemon into wedges.
3.        Take a baking tray, spray some cooking spray, spread the cauliflower on the tray.
4.        Drop the lemon fragments on the tray as well.
5.        Add olive oil, salt & pepper. Mix well. 
6.        Roast at 450-degree for 25-30 mins.
7.        Spread parmesan cheese over it. You can also add capers(optional). Enjoy!

column24:
•        Portobello mushroom-50g
•        Breadcrumbs- 10
•        Parmesan cheese-3
•        Extra-virgin olive oil-3
•        Salt & pepper
•        Parsley.
column25:
1.        Take portobello mushroom, add salt. 
2.        Roast at 450-degree for 20 mins. 
3.        In a bowl, add breadcrumbs, parmesan cheese, parsley, extra-virgin olive oil, salt & pepper. 
4.        Mix all the ingredients. 
5.        Stuff this filling inside the mushroom. 
6.        Continue roasting for 5 mins.

column2: Shrimp & Rice Packets With Olives & Oranges
column3: जैतून और संतरे के साथ झींगा और चावल के पैकेट
column24:
•        Rice-30g
•        Broth-20g
•        Green olives-10g
•        Orange zest-5g
•        Orange juice-20g
•        Shrimp-30g
•        Olive oil-5g
•        Orange slice-20g
•        Almonds-5g
•        Salt to taste
column25:
1.	Preheat oven at 400-degree F. 
2.	In a bowl, take rice, add broth, green olives, orange zest, orange juice, salt. 
3.	Mix them well, take a parchment paper, fold in half, keep the mixture prepared earlier in between. 
4.	Add shrimp, olive oil, orange slice. 
5.	Fold the parchment paper & crimp edges. 
6.	Place this pocket on a baking sheet. Roast for 15-17 mins. 
7.	Open the pocket, add almonds and enjoy!

column24:
•	Peanut oil-10g
•	Egg-50g
•	Lime juice-30g
•	Fish sauce-10g
•	Ketchup-5g
•	Brown sugar-5g
•	Cabbage-40g
•	Shrimp-30g
•	Carrot-10g
•	Peanut-5g
column25:
1.        In a pan, add peanut oil, add egg, cook for 3 mins. 
2.        Cut the omelet into pieces. 
3.        In a bowl, add lime juice, fish sauce, ketchup, brown sugar, red crushed chili, peanut oil and mix well.
4.        Add this mixture in chopped cabbage & mix. 
5.        Place this mixture in a plate, over this place the egg, shrimp, grated carrot and crushed peanut. 
6.        Pour the rest of the sauce over this and enjoy!

column2: Slow Cooker Buffalo Chicken Lettuce Wraps
column3: धीमी कुकर बफ़ेलो चिकन लेट्यूस रैप्स
column24:
•	Skinless
•	Boneless chicken breasts-50g
•	Cayenne pepper sauce-10g
•	Ranch dressing mix 15g
•	Lettuce leaves-30g
column25:
1.	Place chicken breast in slow cooker. 
2.	Whisk Cayenne pepper sauce & Ranch dressing mix. 
3.	Pour this sauce over chicken. 
4.	Cook on low for 6-7 hours. 
5.	Shred chicken into strands with the help of a fork. 
6.	Strain liquid to be served on the side. 
7.	Place the shredded chicken on lettuce leave, garnish it with the sauce and enjoy!

3.        Add the egg and cook while mixing it with spinach. 
4.        Add cheddar cheese once the egg is done.

2.	Slice the cherries.

column24:
•        Chicken breast – 60g
•        Almond flour-10g
•        Parmesan cheese-5g 
•        Pork rinds-5g, egg-20g 
•        Coconut oil-5g
•        Olive oil-5g
•        Ketchup-10g
•        Rice vinegar-10ml
•        Erythritol-10g
•        Soy sauce-10g
•        Garlic powder-5g
column25:
1.        Cube the chicken breast into chunks. 
2.        Take almond flour, parmesan cheese, pork rinds and grind in a food processor. 
3.        Set up the binding station with a beaten egg. 
4.        Dip the chicken chunks in egg, then coat in the pork rind mixture. 
5.        In a pan, heat coconut oil, olive oil and add the chicken chunks. 
6.        Cook until golden and crispy. 
7.        In another pan, take ketchup, add rice vinegar, erythritol, garlic powder, soy sauce to it and whisk while it boils down. 
8.        Pour this sauce over the chicken and mix together to coat. 
9.        Your chicken is ready, enjoy!

column25:

4.	Now, blend 25ml milk, 20g yogurt, 20g banana, 20g frozen raspberries and again pour in the same glass. 
5.	Top the smoothie with chia seeds. Serve it with starfruit, kiwi, strawberry on a stick and Enjoy!

•        1 tsp olive oil
•        ½ cup paneer
•        1 onion (finely chopped) 
•        1 tsp ginger garlic paste
•        ¼ tsp turmeric
•        ½ tsp kashmiri red chilli powder
•        ½ tsp coriander powder
•        1/2 cup tomato pulp
•        2 tbsp water
•        ½ tsp salt
•        ½ capsicum (sliced)
•        2 tbsp coriander (finely chopped)
•        1 Jowar tortilla/ roti
•        2 tsp chilli sauce
•        2 tbsp cabbage (shredded)
•        2 tbsp carrot (grated)
•        few onion (sliced)
•        1 tsp lemon juice
•        4 tbsp cheddar cheese (grated)
column25:
Roll stuffing preparation: 
1. firstly, in a kadai heat 1 tbsp oil and saute 1 onion, 1 tsp ginger garlic paste. 
2. saute until onions turn olden brown. 
3. further, add ¼ tsp turmeric, ½ tsp chilli powder, ½ tsp coriander powder, ¼ tsp cumin powder and ½ tsp garam masala. 
4. saute on low flame until spices turn aromatic. 
5. now add 1/2 cup tomato pulp and saute well. to prepare tomato pulp, blend 2 ripened tomato to a smooth paste. 
6. saute until the oil separates from tomato paste. 
7. further, add 2 tbsp water, ½ tsp salt and mix well 
8. add in roasted paneer, ½ capsicum and mix well. 
9. cover and simmer for 4 minutes. 
10. now add 2 tbsp coriander and mix well. paneer stuffing ready. 
Paneer kathi roll prepartrion: 
1. firstly, take jowar roti. 
2. 1 tsp chilli sauce, spread uniformly. 
3. now add in 2 tbsp prepared paneer stuffing and spread slightly. 
4. top with 1 tbsp cabbage, 1 tbsp carrot and few onions. 
5. Squeez lemon, also, grate 2 tbsp cheddar cheese uniformly. 
6. now roll tight without allowing the stuffing to come out. 
7. tuck the ends make it well secured. 
8. finally, cut into halves and enjoy paneer frankie.

•        Chicken pieces boneless 150 grams
•        Whole wheat flour 1/2 cup
•        Salt to taste
•        Oil 2 tbsps + to shallow fry
•        Onion chopped 1 medium
•        Tomato chopped 1 medium
•        Ginger paste 1 teaspoons
•        Garlic paste 1 teaspoons
•        Kashmiri red chilli powder 2 teaspoons
•        Turmeric powder 1/2 teaspoon
•        Coriander powder 1 teaspoons
•        Lemon juice 1 tablespoons
•        Egg 1 
•        Green chutney 2 teaspoon
column25:
1.        Mix together the flour and salt; add water and knead into a firm dough. Cover with a damp cloth and set aside for about fifteen minutes. roll into rotis.
2.        Cook the rotis lightly on a tawa and set aside. Heat two tablespoons of oil in a pan; add the chicken, chopped onions, tomatoes, ginger paste, garlic paste, salt, chilli powder, turmeric powder and coriander powder; stir over high heat till the chicken is cooked.

3.        Add the lemon juice and mix. Beat the eggs with salt in a bowl. Heat a tawa and place a roti on it. Spread a little beaten egg over the roti. Turn it over and dribble a little oil all a round.

4.        Spread a little egg over the other side as well; turn over and cook a while longer. Be careful not to overcook the rotis.

5.        Place a little chicken mixture on one side of the roti. Sprinkle some sliced onions over the chicken. Top with a little green chutney and sprinkle with a little vinegar. Roll up the roti into a tight roll.

column24:
INGREDIENTS
½ Cup Jowar flour
½ cup water (required to knead)
½  tsp A2 Ghee 
A pinch- Pink Himalayan salt
column25:
METHOD
Heat water in a bowl. Add a pinch of salt. When the water comes to the boil, reduce the flame to half. 
Add the flour in the water pan on reduced flame and let it stay for 10 seconds. Turn off the flame. 
Then mix it altogether using a wooden spatula. 
After mixing, cover it with a lid and let it stay for 2-3 minutes. 
Then transfer it into a plate and knead the dough by sprinkling required amount of water.    
After the dough is made, add ghee and mix well in the dough. 
Make small balls of the dough
Before rolling the dough ball, knead the ball 2-3 times again. 
Dust the rolling base with little amount of flour and roll using the rolling pin.
If the chapati is not rolling properly, take two parchment papers or rice papers and keep the rolling dough in between them and then roll on to the plastic sheet.
Heat a griddle
When the griddle becomes hot, transfer the roti on it. 
Squeeze off excess water from the muslin cloth and smear water over the roti including the edges with the cloth. Do not pour water on roti. The roti must become moist all over.  By now the roti firms up from the centre. 
Flip the roti to the other side. Repeat dampening and then press it with spatula
 Cook the roti by slightly pressing it on all sides. 
Keep flipping and pressing and cooking untill completely cooked. 
When the roti is cooked, remove from griddle and rub ½ tsp ghee over it. 
Dust off the tawa from excess flour by using a cotton cloth. 
Serve chapati hot with curries or vegetables.

•        Bulgur Wheat / Daliya / Ghav Na Fada/ Broken wheat
•        Cauliflower florets
•        Chopped Bell pepper / Capsicum 
•        Chopped carrots
•        Green Peas
•        Onion, Chopped
•        Garlic grated
•        Ginger grated
•        Cumin seeds
•        Light or extra virgin Olive oil or coconut oil (You can use any)
•        Mint
•        Cilantro
•        Salt to taste
•        Red Chili powder (use according to your spice level, Spice level for this recipe is ⅗)
•        Garam masala
•        Turmeric powder
•        Lemon juice
•        Water
column25:
1.        Wash Bulgur wheat / Daliya 2-3 times and drain the water.
2.        Turn on Saute Button, heat oil, add cumin seeds, ginger and garlic. Saute for few seconds.
3.        Now add all the chopped vegetables, washed daliya/Bulgur wheat, salt, chili powder, turmeric powder and water. Stir well.
4.        Turn off the saute mode, close the lid, Press the manual button. Set the time for 6 minutes under high pressure with pressure valve set to sealing.
5.        When cooking time is complete, do a quick release of the pressure.
6.        When the pressure is fully released, the float valve will drop and the lid will unlock to open. Now it is safe to open the lid.
7.        Open and give a gentle stir with fork.
8.        Now add chopped cilantro, mint and lemon juice. Give it a gentle mix.
9.        Daliya is ready. Serve it with Cucumber Raita, Boondi Raita or Plain curd/yogurt.

for batter:
•        moong dal / hesaru kaal
•        chana dal
•        water as required (to soak)
•        rice flour
•        salt to taste
other ingredients:
•        oil (for roasting dosa)
•        onion (finely chopped)
•        ginger (finely chopped)
•        green chili (finely chopped)
column25:
1.        firstly, in a large mixing bowl soak moong dal and chana dal for atleast 4 - 8 hours.
2.        further, drain off the water and blend to smooth batter. add water if required.
3.        transfer to a large bowl.
4.        add rice flour to get the extra crispiness.
5.        also add salt to taste.
6.        mix the batter well and get to dosa batter consistency. add water if required.
7.        further pour a ladleful of the batter on a hot griddle.
8.        spread it in a circular motion thin circle.
9.        also smear a little finely chopped onions, jeera, ginger - chili and oil over the pessarattu.
10.       press gently, so that the onions stick to dosa.
11.       if the dosa is not cooked from top, flip and cook both sides of dosa.
12.       now mark triangle over dosa to fold in triangle shape.
13.       slowly remove the dosa from ends.
14.       and fold to triangle or shape of your choice.
15.       finally, serve pessarattu with hot uppitu, allam chutney or coconut chutney.

•        Whole Urad Dal 
•        Fenugreek Seeds / Vendayam / Methi 
•        Salt to taste
•        Water as needed
column25:
1.        Take all the ingredients except salt in a bowl and rinse well.
2.        Now cover with water and let it soak for 10 hours. Now drain it and rinse it well.
3.        Now take this in blender and puree till smooth.
4.        Pour it into bowl, cover and leave it to ferment for 8 hours.
5.        Now add salt and mix well.Add water as needed.
6.        Heat a tawa, make dosa, drizzle oil around the sides. Cook till golden, flip over and cook.
7.        Serve with chutney or sambar.

column2: Upma Persarattu/Green Gram Lentil (Moong Dal) Dosa Stuffed With Upma.
column3: उपमा पर्सरट्टू/ग्रीन ग्राम दाल (मूंग दाल) डोसा को उपमा के साथ भरा।
column24:
•        Moong dal
•        Rice
•        Green chilies
•        Ginger piece, chopped
•        teaspoon Cumin seeds
•        Salt to taste 
•        As needed Oil, for cooking
•        For Serving/ Garnish:
•        Onion, finely chopped
•        Salt
column25:
1.        To begin making the Pesarattu Upma Recipe will first soak the green moong dal and rice together in water for at least 3 hours.  After 3 hours drain the water.
2.        Blend the dal, green chillies and ginger by adding little water at a time to make a smooth thick batter. Transfer the batter into a large bowl, add onions, salt and coriander leaves. Stir well to combine the Pesarattu batter well. Check the salt levels and adjust to suit your taste.
3.        In a saucepan, bring the 3 cups of water, salt and sugar to a brisk boil. After it comes to a brisk boil, turn the heat to low to keep the water warm.  
4.        Our next step is to make the upma, roast the sooji in a cast iron pan and roast them till it slightly changes its colour. Keep it aside.
5.        Heat oil/ghee in a heavy bottomed pan. Add the mustard seeds, urad dal and allow it to crackle and the urad dal to turn golden brown. Stir in the asafoetida and curry leaves.
6.        Next, add the onions, green chillies and ginger and cook till the onion becomes soft and translucent.
7.        Next, add the tomatoes and allow it cook till the tomatoes becomes mushy and soft. 
8.        Finally, add sooji  and gradually add the sugar and salt warm water. Keep stirring until the Upma comes together. 
9.        Cook for about 5 to 8 minutes until the upma, comes away from the sides of a pan. Once the upma is cooked well, turn off the heat and keep aside.
10.        Now to make the Pesarattu. You will need a well-seasoned skillet.
11.        Preheat the skillet on medium heat; sprinkle some water to check on the pan; if it sizzles then you know the pan has the right amount of heat to spread the Pesarattu batter. Pour a ladle full of the Pesarattu batter onto the pan and spread evenly inside out to make a circle.
12.        Drizzle some oil on the top and the sides of the Pesarattu and allow it to cook on low to medium heat. Once you notice the top of the Pesarattu getting steamed, flip it over to cook on the other side.
13.        Once you notice brown spots and the Pesarattu is cooked, flip it back and place a big scoop of the upma to the side and fold it into half and remove from the pan and serve hot. Proceed the same way with the remaining Pesarattu batter.
14.        Serve the Pesarattu Upma Recipe along with tomato chutney and coconut chutney to make it a rich breakfast meal.

column24:
• 75g coconut flour
• 2 tbsp psyllium husk powder
• 1 tsp xanthan gum
• 1 tsp baking powder
• 1 pinch Himalayan salt
• 1 tbsp nigella and/or sesame seeds
• 1 cup / 240ml hot water
• ¼ cup / 60g full-fat natural yogurt
• 2 tbsp coconut oil/olive oil melted handful chopped parsley or coriander/cilantro
column25:
1. Preheat the oven to 180 Celsius / 356 Fahrenheit.
2. Mix all dry ingredients in another bowl - coconut flour, psyllium husk powder, xanthan gum and salt. Make sure there are no lumps.
3. Add the wet ingredients - hot water, yogurt, melted coconut oil or olive oil - and stir together until a dough forms.
4. Form a dough ball and let it sit for a few minutes until the coconut flour and the psyllium have absorbed all the moisture and the dough is not sticky.
5. Cut the dough into 6 pieces and roll them out between two sheets of parchment paper into long flatbreads, about ½ cm thick. Place on an upturned  baking sheet and remove the top parchment. Optional: sprinkle with sesame seeds and/or nigella seeds.
Bake for 12-15 minutes or until browned (baking time will depend on how thick your flatbreads are). If large air bubbles form, pierce with a fork during baking.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            6. If necessary, rotate the baking sheet so the flatbreads brown equally and/or turn on the grill/broiler at the end to ensure they crisp and brown on top.             7. Top with melted butter, olive oil or coconut oil, sprinkle with more salt and chopped parsley or coriander/cilantro leaves before serving.

column24:
• 50  gms  Desiccated Coconut
• tbsp  Psyllium Husk Telephone Brand
• tbsp  Melted Coconut oil Patanjali
• ½ tsp  Ajwain or Carrom Seeds
• ¼ tsp  Pink Salt
• ½ cup Hot water                                      • 1 tsp  Ghee
column25:
1. In a bowl measure the desiccated Coconut and Psyllium husk.
Add the salt put it in a grinder.
2. Now grind the mixture till it is a fine powder.
3. Take out the mixture in a bowl, add the melted oil and carom seeds to it. Mix well.
4. Slowly add half the water to it. The ingredients will start binding with each other; add more only if you think the batter is very dry and not coming together. 5. The water needs to be hot, not boiling.
6. I will not be able to tell you the exact amount of water, as different brands of Psyllium husk will react differently.
7. Now let the dough rest for five to seven minutes. Heat the griddle or non-stick pan on which you intent to cook the chapati.
8. I smeared the hot plate or tawa with half the ghee and got it ready.
9. Cut two pieces of parchment or baking paper. Divide the batter into four parts and form small balls in your hands.
10. Place one ball between the sheets of paper and lightly press with a rolling pin or belan. Do not apply too much pressure or the batter will stick to the paper.
11.Now you can either lift the bread with a flat spoon or with your hands and place it on the hot plate.
12. Keep the heat high and let it get lightly golden on one side before you turn it.
13. Turn a few times more, with a flat spoon, the bread should be cooked from all sides and should be crisp. Don’t worry it does not stick to the plate, because of the oil in it.
14. Serve them hot with vegetable or curry of your choice.

column24:
• 2 cups cauliflower rice
• 1 medium onion finely chopped
• 1.5 cups mix vegetables (carrot, green beans ,green peas)
• 1 tablespoon coconut oil
• 1 teaspoon mustard seeds
• 1 stalk curry leaves
• 2 green chilies
• 1 teaspoon ginger minced
• a pinch of asafetida (hing)
• salt to taste
• 1 tablespoon lemon juice
• 1 tablespoon cilantro (coriander leaves) for garnish
• 1 tablespoon grated coconut
column25:
1. Firstly separate cauliflower into florets and stalks. Wash thoroughly. Mince or grate florets with the help of grater or food processor to resemble fine rice or semolina.
2. Heat 1 tbsp of coconut oil in a kadai. Add mustard seeds, let the mustard splutter.
3. Add curry leaves, ginger, green chilli and hing. Saute for another 30-40 seconds.
4. Next add the onions and cook till the onions become soft.
5. Then add the mix vegetables and cook for 2-3 minutes.
6. Now add cauliflower rice, salt, mix well and Cover with a lid and cook on medium low heat for 4 to 5 minutes. Stir in between and turn off the flame.
8. Once the cauliflower is cooked, remove from heat and garnish with coriander, lime juice, and grated coconut, mix well and serve hot.
9. Cauliflower Upma is Ready & serve hot with greek yogurt or coconut chutney.

column24:
• Cabbage grated 200g
• Cottage cheese/paneer 150g
• Ginger finely grated 1/2 tsp
• Green chilies finely chopped 1 tsp
• Turmeric powder 1/2 tsp
• Red chili powder 1/2  tsp
• Hung curd 1 tbsp
• Lemon juice 1 tsp
• Psyllium husk 1 tsp
• Oil 2 tbsp
• Almond flour 2tbsp
column25:
1. In a mixing bowl add the cabbage and salt.
2. Mix thoroughly and keep it aside for 2 -3 mins.
3. Now with the help of muslin cloth squeeze out the excess water as much as possible.
4. Now transfer the squeezed cabbage in a big mixing bowl.
5. Now add all the ingredients one by one and mix it thoroughly, forming a medium consistency dough.
6. Now roll out small portions into a ball shape and keep it aside.
7. Roll out all the dough into small balls
8. Heat an Appam pan and put some oil on all the cavities.
9. Drop the appam balls into it.
10. Brush the top with oil and cover and cook for about 4-5 minutes until it becomes crispy.
11. Now, with the help of 2 spoons, toss and turn each appam and cover and cook to get crispy from the other sides.
12. Take it out and serve hot with green chutney or mayo dip.

column24:
• 3 tbsp water
• 1tsp ghee
• Green Chilli
• 2 tbsp Onion
• 2 tbsp Coriander Leaves
• ¼ tsp Cumin Seeds
• Few pinches of Hing or asafoetida
• 3tbsp Coconut flour
• 1 tbsp Golden Flaxseed Meal
• 1 tbsp Nutritional Yeast
• 3 tbsp Mozarella Cheese
• Salt- to taste
column25:
1.Take all the ingredients except ghee & water in a bowl. Mix them well.
2. Now add water slowly, 1 tbsp at a time. Make it into thick paste. 
3. Now you can make one big uttapam or 2 small ones.
4. Spread the mix gently on to a greased non stick pan. There should be no breaks in the uttapam.
5. Cook it for 4-5 mins on low medium heat till it forms a nice crust.
6. Slightly lift the Uttapam to see if its cooked and formed crust on the bottom. If its cooked well, then gently slide the spatula under the Uttapam and flip it gently. 
7. Cook well on the other side for a couple of minutes.
8. Once cooked on both sides, remove & serve hot.

column24:
• 8 cups red or green cabbage (finely grated or chopped)
• 1 ½  - 2 tsp Himalayan pink salt (plus more to taste)
• 1 small beet (finely shredded)
• 3 whole carrots (finely shredded) (optional)
• 3 Tbsp fresh ginger (shredded / grated)
• 3 Tbsp fresh turmeric (shredded / grated)
• 4 cloves garlic (finely minced)
column25:
1. Sterilize glass jars. Do so easily by pouring boiling water over clean jars and lids and drying completely. Let come back to room temperature before adding ingredients.
2. Add finely grated cabbage to a large mixing bowl and top with 1 ½ teaspoons sea salt. Wash hands thoroughly and massage cabbage for ten minutes. The cabbage should start softening, shrinking in size, and releasing water. Continue massaging until it happens.
3. Add shredded beet, carrot, ginger, turmeric, and garlic and massage once more with clean hands for 4-5 minutes until thoroughly combined. Then taste test and adjust flavor, adding more salt for saltiness, grated ginger for more zing, or garlic for more intense garlic flavor.
4. Use your clean hands to put the sauerkraut mixture into your sterilized jars and press down firmly to pack. There should be enough liquid from the massaging to rise up and cover the vegetables. If this doesn’t happen, top with filtered water until covered (it is unlikely that you will need to add water).
5. Also, make sure there is plenty of room (about 1 ½ inches) between the contents and the lid so it has room to expand. Seal with a lid and set on the counter where there’s not much direct sun exposure or in a cabinet. The ideal temperature for fermentation is above 65 degrees F (18 C), so try to keep your environment on the warmer side to encourage proper fermentation.
6. Fermentation can happen as quickly as 24 hours if your space is hot, or it can take as long as 2 weeks, (again, depending on the environment). 
7. During this fermentation process, open your jars once per day to release air (you should feel pressure release and see air bubbles when you open the jars). Press down with a sterilized object such as a spoon or the bottom of a drinking glass to ensure that the vegetables are still completely covered in the liquid. Doing so helps encourage proper fermentation.
8. The longer it sits and ferments, the tangier it will become, so sample occasionally with a clean utensil to test and see if it is at the right stage for you. Once it has reached the desired tanginess, cover securely and transfer to the fridge, where it should keep at least 3 months and up to 6 months. When serving, don’t double dip to avoid contamination.

column24:

• 1 small lemon

column25:

2. Add coriander leaves to a bowl of water and rinse them, changing water a few times. Place them on a kitchen tissue or colander to remove excess moisture.
3. Julliene or Chop all the vegetables to bite sizes. Peel the cucumbers & deseed them before chopping if you want. Add them to a mixing bowl.
4. Chop coriander leaves and add them too. When you are ready to serve the Kachumber, sprinkle salt and lemon juice. Mix it.
Transfer to serving bowls and garnish kachumber with black pepper, cumin powder and red chilli powder.

column24:
• ½ cup raw cashews
• ¼ cup water
• 2 cups Parsley
• 2 cloves garlic
• 2 tablespoons lemon juice
• ¼ teaspoon kosher salt
• pepper to taste                                                              
To assemble:
• ¼ cup uncooked Israeli couscous Or Quinoa
• 1-pint cremini mushrooms, sliced
• 1 tablespoon olive oil
• 1 bunch of kale, stems removed
column25:
1. Cover the cashews with ½-inch of water and let sit for 1 hour or up to overnight.
2. Drain and rinse the cashews and add to a food processor along with the parsley, garlic, lemon juice, salt, and pepper. Process until smooth, stopping to scrape down the sides once or twice. Taste and add more lemon juice or salt and pepper as desired.
3. Bring ¾ cup of water in a small saucepan to a boil. Add the couscous, stir to combine and remove from the heat. Let it sit for 7 to 10 minutes. Fluff the couscous with a fork and set aside.
4. Heat 1 tablespoon of olive oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add the mushrooms, season with salt and pepper and cook for 7-10 minutes, stirring occasionally until all the water has evaporated and they begin to brown. Set the mushrooms aside and return the skillet to the heat. Cut the kale into 1-inch pieces, and add to the pan along with a few tablespoons of water. 
5. Season with salt and pepper, cover the skillet and let steam for 3-4 minutes until the kale is wilted and a bright green color.
6. To serve plate ¼  cup of couscous, a quarter of the mushrooms and kale and top with a tablespoon of the pesto.

column24:
• 3 cups raw cauliflower florets
• 2 tbsp water
• 4 garlic cloves divided
• 1/3 cup olive oil
• 2 tbsp tahini
• 3 tbsp lemon juice
• 1/2 tsp salt
• 2 tbsp canned jalapenos drained
• 1 tbsp cilantro chopped
• 1/3 cup Cheese
column25:
1. Combine the cauliflower, water, and 2 whole garlic cloves in a microwave safe bowl. Microwave for about 6-10 minutes or until cooked and softened.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                2. Put the cauliflower mixture into a food processor and blend.
3. Add the olive oil, tahini paste, lemon juice, salt, jalapeño, cilantro or parsley, the 2 remaining garlic cloves, and 1/3-cup Cheese. Blend until smooth. 4. Taste and adjust salt as necessary.
5. Serve cauliflower jalapeño hummus in a bowl topped with 2 Tablespoons of crumbled cheese.
6. Use celery sticks or baby carrots for dipping. If you like, you can drizzle a bit of olive oil and sprinkle a dash of paprika on top of the hummus.

column24:
• 2 medium Italian eggplants 
• 2 medium cloves of garlic, pressed or minced
• 2 tablespoons lemon juice, more if necessary
• ¼ cup tahini
• ⅓ cup extra-virgin olive oil, 
• 2 tablespoons chopped fresh flat-leaf parsley, plus extra for garnish
• ¾ teaspoon salt, to taste
• ¼ teaspoon ground cumin
• Pinch of smoked paprika, for garnish
column25:
1. Preheat the oven to 450*F  with a rack in the upper third of the oven. Line a large, rimmed baking sheet with parchment paper to prevent the eggplant from sticking to the pan. Halve the eggplants lengthwise and brush the cut sides lightly with olive oil. Place them in the prepared pan with the halved sides down.
2. Roast the eggplant until the interior is very tender throughout and the skin is collapsing, about 35 to 40 minutes. Set the eggplant aside to cool for a few minutes. Flip the eggplants over and scoop out the flesh with a large spoon, leaving the skin behind.
3. Place a mesh strainer over a mixing bowl, then transfer the flesh to the strainer and discard the skins. Pick out any stray bits of eggplant skin and discard. You want to remove as much moisture from the eggplant here as possible, so let the eggplant rest for a few minutes and shake/stir the eggplant to release some more moisture.
4. Discard all of the eggplant drippings, drain and wipe out the bowl, and dump the eggplant into the bowl. Add the garlic and lemon juice to the eggplant and stir vigorously with a fork until eggplant breaks down. Add the tahini to the bowl and stir until it’s incorporated. While stirring, slowly drizzle in the olive oil. Continue stirring until the mixture is pale and creamy, and use your fork to break up any particularly long strings of eggplant.
5. Stir in the parsley, salt and cumin. Season to taste with more salt (and more lemon juice, if you’d like a more tart flavor.
6.Transfer the baba ganoush to a serving bowl and lightly drizzle olive oil on top. Lastly, sprinkle parsley and smoked paprika on top. Serve with accompaniments of your choice.

column24:

column24:
