• 3 Cloves Garlic
• 1 tbsp Parsley
• 4 Olives
• Salt to Taste
•1 tbsp  Olive Oil                                                     • Paprika 
• Chilly Flakes
column25:
1. Cut the bell peppers in half and remove all the seeds.
2. Place on a roasting tray and roast in the oven for 30 minutes at 220C or till the skins are charred and the peppers soft
3. Cover with foil/lid and allow peppers to cool and then remove the skins
4. Blend the peppers, tahini, garlic, parsley, olives, paprika, chilly flakes in a blender and season to taste.
5. Garnish with some chopped olives and parsley.

column24:
• 500 grams Cauliflower
• 60 grams Tahini 
• 10 grams garlic
• 8 Tbsp Extra Virgin Olive Oil 
• 100 grams Kalamata Olives 
• 1 Tsp Paprika Try this one
• 1 Tsp Cumin Try this one
• 1 Tbsp Chopped Parsley
• Juice of one lemon/lime
column25:
1. Clean and cut the cauliflower and separate the florets.
2. Either microwave the cauliflower for 10 minutes or steam it, boil it and cook till tender
3. Once done add all the ingredients except the parsley in a food processor and blitz till you get a nice smooth hummus
4. Keep tasting for seasoning and flavour and add additional quantities if desired.
5. Once done transfer to a bowl and add the parsley and mix well
Garnish with cayenne pepper, more olive oil , parsley and an olive.

column24:
• For sauteeing before grinding:
• 2 teaspoons Oil
• ½ teaspoon Mustard seeds
• 2-3 Green chilies slit
• 1 cup Mint leaves loosely packed
• For grinding into chutney
• 1 cup Coconut grated
• Salt to taste
• 1 teaspoon Tamarind paste (or seedless tamarind 2 teaspoons)
• ½ to ¾ cup Water
column25:
1. Cooking mint leaves:
2. Heat the oil in a pan on medium heat. Once hot add mustard seeds. Let them pop.
3. Now add green chilies and saute for a minute.
4. Add mint leaves. Cook for 2 minutes only. The leaves will start to wilt. Do not overcook.
5. Let it cool down slightly.
6. Making pudina coconut chutney recipe:
7. In a grinder jar, take grated coconut, add above cooked mint leaves, salt and tamarind paste. Start with ½ cup of water and add 8. little more later as needed.
9. Grind into smooth paste.                                                                                                                                                                  10. Remove it to a serving bowl and serve.

column24:
• take a pan, roast peanuts, a few curry leaves, whole red chili, Asafoetida (Hing) till golden brown on medium flame.
• Add 1/2 cup water in the roasted ingredients, salt, and tamarind,
• Boiled it for 5 minutes And cool it,
• After it’s cool enough, grind in a mixture into a smooth paste along with green chili (optional).
• Now take another pan, add oil, and once it’s hot, add rai, left curry leaves, and pour it hot on the chutney.

• 1 (7-oz) can fire-roasted diced green chilies
• 1 tsp garlic paste (or minced garlic)
• ½ tsp onion powder
½ tsp ground cumin
½ cup chicken broth
2 tbs sour cream
salt and pepper, to taste
column25:
1. Add the diced chiles (no need to drain) to a small blender or food processor, together with the garlic, onion powder, and ground cumin. Blend until smooth.
2. Transfer the mixture to a saucepan and add the chicken broth. Bring to a boil and then reduce to a medium simmer for 5 minutes. Stir in the sour cream.
3. Taste for seasoning and add salt and pepper to taste. If the sauce is too hot, add a little extra sour cream.
4. Let cool then store in the fridge (covered) until required.

column24:
• 50 gm Bedgi/Kashmiri Chillies
• 1/2 Cup Peanut Oil for cooking
• 1/4 Cup Chopped Garlic
• 2 Tbsp Ginger
• 1 tsp Salt
•3 Tbsp Swerve or Sweetener
•3 Tbsp Tomato Paste
•3-4 Tbsp Vinegar
•1/4 tsp MSG (it's declared safe)
•1/4 to 1/2 Cup Oil to top up the bottle
column25:
1. Boil the chillies in water for 10-12 minutes
2. Once the chillies are cooked and pulpy, drain and grind to a rough paste
3. Take oil in a wok, add the garlic and ginger and fry till golden in color on a low flame
4.Once golden add the chilli paste and fry for about 4-5 minutes until oil separates from the sides
5.Add the salt, soya sauce, swerve, tomato paste and the MSG and mix it well.
6.Let it cook for another couple of minutes and give it a taste for seasoning and add 1/4 tsp more salt if needed
7.The sauce should be spicy, on the salty side, slightly sweet and a little tangy

column24:
• 2 kilograms tomatoes (washed, dried, and chopped)
• 1 garlic (peeled)
• 1 handful curry leaves
• tamarind (tennis ball-sized, cleaned thoroughly for seeds and threads)
• 5 whole red chilies
1 teaspoon chili powder (heaped)
1 teaspoon mustard seeds (roasted + ½ tsp)
1 tablespoon jeera (/cumin seeds roasted)
1 tablespoon methi (/fenugreek seeds roasted)
1/2 cup oil
salt (to taste)
column25:
1. Dry grind the roasted 1tsp mustard, fenugreek and cumin seeds to a fine powder
2. Heat oil in a big kadai and add the other 1/2 tsp mustard seeds, curry leaves, whole red chilli and garlic. Fry till the garlic is slightly brown.
3. Add the tomatoes, tamarind, chili powder, salt and the freshly ground powder.
4. Cook on a low heat, stirring frequently to prevent burning the bottom.

column24:
• for making hung curd
2½ cup Curd / Yogurt
muslin cloth
•for making dip
¼ teaspoon garlic, minced
salt to taste
½ teaspoon oregano
chili flakes to taste
¼ teaspoon basil, optional
1 tablespoon regular curd OR cream, optional

• 1 cup chopped coriander leaves
• 6 mint leaves
• 1 tsp chopped ginger
• 1green chili, chopped
• 1-2 tsp lemon juice
½ tsp ground cumin
225 ml water
2 tsp sugar
1½ tbsp grated coconut
1small white onion, chopped
column25:
1. Blend to combine all ingredients. If you over-grind the chutney, there is a chance it will turn bitter, so give it a gentle couple of whirls in the blender.
2. Check seasoning and add lemon and/or salt to taste.
3. Store chutney in a covered bowl or container in the refrigerator until serving.

column24:
• Coconut powder 1/2 cup 
• Curry leaves about 15 - 20 leaves
• Hung curd/coconut curd 1 Tsp
• Water 1/2 cup
• Ginger 1 slice
• Green chili according to taste
• Salt to taste
• For Tempering:
Mustard seeds 1/2 tsp
Curry leaves 2 - 3 leaves
Oil 1 Tsp
Asafoetida a pinch
column25:
1. In a Grinder jar add coconut powder, curry leaves ginger, chillies, salt, hung curd and water. 
2. Churn it till become a fine paste. 
3. Take it out in a bowl.
4. For tempering, heat a small pan. 
5. When heated add Mustard seeds. 
6. When the seed splutters, add curry leaves and a pinch of Asafoetida.
7. Add this to your chutney bowl.

column24:
• 1 cup raw pecans
• 1 cup raw cashews
• 1 cup raw almonds
• ½ cup raw sunflower seeds
• 2 tablespoons chia seeds
• 2 tablespoons flax seeds
• ½ teaspoon sea salt
column25:
1. Combine the pecans, cashews, almonds, and sunflower seeds in your food processor or high-powered blender                      .    2. Process for about 3-6 minutes, scraping down as necessary. Your time might be shorter if you’re using a high-powered blender – it will take a little bit longer in the food processor and require more scraping down.
3. When the nuts have broken down into a smooth, creamy butter, add the chia seeds, salt, and cinnamon and/or vanilla extract, if you’re using. Process to incorporate, and taste. Adjust add-ins as desired. If it’s not blending up as smoothly or thinly as you want, add a little bit of coconut oil here.
4.Transfer to a glass jar or two (like a mason or Weck jar) and store for 2-3 months.

column24: • 3 cups shredded or desiccated unsweetened coconut (270 g)
column25:
1. Add the shredded coconut to a blender or food processor and blend until smooth.
2. Serve your coconut butter

column24:
• 3 cups Roasted, Salted Cashews (450g)
• 2 Tablespoons Coconut Oil Melted
column25:
1. If you only have raw cashew nuts then it will be best to roast them first. Place the cashews in a single layer on a baking sheet and roast them at 350°F for around 10-12 minutes until nicely roasted. Keep a watch on them so they don’t burn. Then add to the food processor and follow the rest of the directions. If you do it this way, you’ll need to add in a little salt to taste.
It is possible to make this without any added oil, but it does tend to take longer.
2. Keep it stored in a glass container (covered) in the fridge for 2 weeks or longer.
3. This recipe makes around 1 ½ cups of cashew butter. 
4. This recipe was first published in November 2017. Now updated with new photos and extra tips.

column24: • 3 cups almonds (one pound)
column25:
1.To make the process faster, warm the almonds in an oven preheated to 350ºF degrees for 10 minutes. 
2. Transfer the almonds to a large food processor fitted with an "S" blade, and process them until creamy. You may want to stop and scrape down the sides every now and then, but this process will take up to 25 minutes. The almonds will first look like a flour with clumps, then will form a ball that moves around the food processor, then it will turn to a grainy almond butter before it becomes silky-smooth. Be patient! Just when you'll want to give up is usually when the magic happens.

3. Once totally smooth and creamy, transfer the almond butter to a glass jar and store it in the fridge. I've found that almond butter with no additives usually lasts at least a month in the fridge, but be sure to check for signs of spoiling (such as mold or a bad smell) each time you use it.

column24:
• 250 grams Salted Peanuts
• 45 grams Melted Butter
column25:
1. Blend everything together
2. Every few minutes scrape down the sides to ensure better consistency  
3. Blend till a smooth butter is formed.
4. Store in the fridge for 2-3 weeks (or maybe even longer)

column24:
•        3 tbsp riced cauliflower
•        1 teaspoon olive oil
•        1 bell pepper,  
•        1/2 medium-sized tomatoe, diced
•        1 tbsp grated cheese, divided
•        1-2 diced onion
•        1 tbsp salsa
•        1/2 tablespoons chopped cilantro
•        1 ½ teaspoons cumin
•        1 teaspoon salt
•        1/2 teaspoon paprika
•        1 teaspoon garlic powder
•        ½ teaspoon onion powder
•        ½ teaspoon black pepper
column25:
1.        Pre-heat oven to 400 degrees F.  Cut the top off of each pepper and scoop out all the seeds and white membrane.  If you prefer a softer pepper: bring a large pot of water to a boil and place peppers in for about 1 minute.  Remove from water and place in a baking dish.
2.        Heat a large skillet and add olive oil and riced cauliflower.  Sautee until cauliflower is tender, about 7 minutes.
3.        Add the cauliflower rice and all the remaining ingredients (except for ¼  cup cheese) to a large bowl and mix until combined.  Pack each pepper with the filling, how much filling will depend on the size of your pepper.  Top with a little sprinkle of cheese.  Pour about 1/3  cup of water in the bottom of the baking dish and bake peppers until mixture is heated through and cheese is melted, about 20 minutes.
4.        Serve hot.

column24:
•        50g Chicken Breast
•        ½ garlic
•        1/2 tbsp extra virgin olive oil
•        ½ tsp cumin powder
•        ½ tsp Chilli Powder
•        1/8 tsp turmeric
•        1/8 tsp cinnamon powder
•        Salt as needed
•        1/8 tsp crushed pepper
•        1 onion quartered layers separated
column25:
1.        Cut chicken to small 1 ½ inch size pieces. Keep it aside.
2.        Mix all the ingredients to marinade. Add lemon juice only if needed. Taste the marinade and add more salt if required.
3.        Marinate chicken with the mix. Cover and refrigerate for at least 12 to 24 hours. 
4.        Preheat the oven to 200C or 400F for atleast 15 mins.
5.        Prepare a grilling tray by spreading a foil and greasing it. 
6.        Place the chicken over the tray along with onions and tomatoes. Space them apart. 
7.        Grill for 15 to 20 mins depending on the size of the pieces. After 10mins flip them to the other side.
8.        Move to the top rack and broil for 2 to 3 mins
9.        Shred the chicken in the tray and serve.

column24:
•        Coconut powder 5tbs
•        Stevia 2tsp
•        Ghee 1tbs
•        Cardamom 2
•        1 tbsp fresh cream
column25:
1.	Heat a nonstick frying pan
2.	Add ghee
3.	Add the coconut powder and sauté in low heat until it starts changing colour
4.	Add the stevia
5.	And sauté for 2-3mins.
6.	Remove from heat and add the fresh cream and mix well
7.	Let it cool slightly and roll them into laddoos

column24:
•        1/4 small Onion, roughly chopped
•        1/4 cloves of Garlic
•        1 tsp of Cilantro
•        1 tsp of Fresh Parsley
•        2 tbsp Cauliflower
•        1 tbsp Almond Flour
•        1/4 Egg
•        1/2 tsp Cumin, ground
•        1 teaspoon of Salt
•        ½ teaspoon of Turmeric, ground
•        ½ teaspoon of Chili Powder
•        1/4 tbsp of Sour Cream
•        1 tablespoon of Lemon Juice
•        ½ teaspoon of Garlic Powder
•        ½ teaspoon of Salt
•        Pinch of Smoked Paprika
•        Pinch of Pepper
column25:
1.	Preheat the oven to 200C/400F. Line a cookie sheet with parchment paper and set aside.
2.	Break the cauliflower into florets and place into your food processor, blend into chunky rice texture. Scrape out into a bowl and set aside.
3.	Without cleaning out your food processor, add the onion, garlic, parsley and cilantro. Blend until finely chopped.
4.	Add the cauliflower back in, along with the remaining falafel ingredients. Blend until just combined.
5.	Gently form the mixture into discs, each about 2 tablespoons of mixture. You can also use a cookie scoop for this.
6.	Bake for 35-40 minutes, turning the cookie sheet halfway through.
7.	To make the dipping sauce, add all the ingredients into a small bowl and whisk together.
8.	Enjoy the falafels hot from the oven, or cool and enjoy cold, with a side of dipping sauce.

column24:
•        1 medium Portobello Mushrooms
•        1 tbsp of Kale (or Spinach)
•        1/2 medium Tomato (diced)
•        1/2 Yellow Onion (diced)
•        1 Tablespoon of Tomato Sauce or Marinara
•        1/2 Tablespoon of Coconut Oil (any oil)
•        2 tbsp of  Cheese 
•        Salt & Pepper to taste
column25:
1.	Preheat you oven to 425 degrees F and line a small baking pan with lightly greased foil.
2.	Prep your mushrooms by brushing clean, removing the stems and gently scraping out the dark/brown part to make room for stuffing. Line them on you baking sheet and cook for 8-10 minutes.
3.	In a medium sauce pan on medium heat, melt your oil and add in your diced onions and tomatoes. Let them cook for a few minutes together, then add in your 3 tbsp of sauce/marinara.
4.	Prep your kale by washing and tearing it into bite sized pieces. Add it into your sauce pan and let everything cook together for about 5 minutes.
5.	Take you mushrooms out of the oven, you’ll notice they’re filled with “water” that’s totally normal. Just take a paper towel and dab each of them to remove the liquid. That’s why you bake them before stuffing, so they don’t get all soggy and gross.
6.	Spoon your filling into each mushroom, you should have plenty to fill 6 medium-sized mushrooms. Top each with a little cheese or any other pizza topping you enjoy.
7.	Bake on broil for about 2-3 minutes, or until cheese is bubbling/light brown. Let rest for a couple of minutes to cool. Serve and enjoy!

column24:
•        1medium zucchini about 
•        3-4 tbsp ground chicken
•        1/4 tsp. salt
•        1/4 tsp. ground black pepper
•        2 garlic cloves minced
•        1 tbsp pasta sauce
•        1 tbsp grated parmesan cheese
•        1 tbsp shredded mozzarella cheese
•        Optional: sliced fresh basil for topping
column25:
1.	Preheat oven to 400 degrees F. Spray a 9x13 inch baking dish with cooking spray.
2.	Place a large non-stick skillet over medium-high heat. Add the chicken and break it apart with a spoon. Add the salt and pepper. Cook for 8 to 10 minutes, until chicken is cooked through. Stir occasionally and break down the chicken into small chunks.
3.	Reduce the heat to low. Add the garlic to the chicken. Cook 1 minute stirring often. Add the pasta sauce. Cook 3 minutes, stirring occasionally.
4.	As the chicken cooks, cut the zucchini in half, lengthwise. Use a spoon to scoop the seeds and center out of each zucchini half, leaving a 1/4 inch thick zucchini boat.
5.	Place the zucchini in the baking dish cut-side up.
6.	Spoon the chicken mixture into the zucchini boats. Press the mixture down into the zucchini using the back of the spoon.
7.	Sprinkle the zucchini evenly with the parmesan, then the mozzarella cheese.
8.	Cover the baking dish with foil. Bake for 35 minutes.
9.	Sprinkle with fresh basil and serve.

column24:
•        1 large cucumber, sliced thin lengthwise
•        1/2 large Carrot- cut into strips about 2.5 - inches long
•        1/2 Roasted red pepper
•        2 tbsp. Microgreens
•        2 tbsp Cheddar Cheese
column25:
1.	On a work surface, lay out two strips of cucumber and pat dry with a paper towel. Next, layer on 1 slice of Mild Cheddar Cheese, 2-3 pieces of carrot, 3-4 thin strips of red pepper placed at the end, and 1-2 tablespoons of micro greens over the red pepper.
2.	Starting at the end with the microgreens and red pepper, roll from end to end until the cucumber roll is complete. Cut in between the two cucumber slices. Turn the roll on its side so that the microgreens and red pepper are now sprouting out of the top of the roll. Repeat for all slices of cucumber. Serve and enjoy!

column3: बेल पेपर पनीर अंडे के कप
column24:
•        1 medium bell peppers, any color
•        ¼ teaspoon salt, divided
•        ¼ teaspoon ground pepper, divided
•        1 egg
•       2 tbsp shredded cheese
column25:
1.	Preheat oven to 400°F. Coat a baking pan with cooking spray.
2.	Cut bell peppers in half through the stem end. Remove ribs and seeds. Place the peppers in the pan cut-side up and sprinkle with 1/8 teaspoon each salt and pepper.
3.	Bake the peppers for 15 minutes. Remove the pan from the oven and crack 1 egg into each pepper cup. Season with the remaining 1/4 teaspoon each salt and pepper, then top each with 1/2 tablespoon cheese.
4.	Bake until the egg whites are set, 15 to 20 minutes. Sprinkle with cilantro, if desired.

column24:
Mozzarella:
•        3 tbsp mozzarella cheese
Cheesecake Filling:
•        1 tbsp cream cheese
•        1 tbsp heavy cream
•        1 tsp powdered stevia
Raspberry Sauce:
•        2 tbsp raspberries
•        1 teaspoon lemon juice
•        2 teaspoon water
•        1 tsp powdered stevia
column25:
1.	Gather the ingredients together. Prep the mozzarella by shredding it if needed. Pre-heat oven to 400F.
2.	On a parchment-lined baking tray, create small circles using the shredded mozzarella. Use about 1/4 cup of mozzarella per taco.
3.	While the oven is heating up, place the raspberries, water, lemon juice, and erythritol in a pan over medium heat. Cook over medium heat and mush together using a fork. Once the raspberries are reduced slightly and thicken, remove them from the heat and let the mixture cool.
4.	Bake the mozzarella for 6-8 minutes or until lightly browned on the edges. Let cool for 1-2 minutes until the cheese is pliable and can still be handled.
5.	Drape the mozzarella tacos over wooden spoons or spatula handles (suspended with glasses) to create the shape.
6.	In a bowl, use an electric mixer (or whisk) to whip the cream cheese, heavy cream, and erythritol together.
7.	Assemble the tacos. Add cream cheese mixture and raspberry sauce to each mozzarella taco.
8.	Serve and enjoy!

column24:
•        1 tablespoon olive oil
•        1/2 medium yellow onion
•        1 tbsp cheese, diced
•        1 medium eggplant, diced
•        1/2 egg
•        1 tablespoon butter, for frying
•         1 tbsp Salsa
•        Salt and pepper to taste
column25:
1.        Measure out and prepare all ingredients.
2.        In a frying pan over medium heat, add the olive oil and onion. Saute until onion is soft.
3.        Add the eggplant and halloumi cheese to the pan and cook until everything is golden brown in color, stirring occasionally. Season with salt and pepper to taste. When finished, plate the hash and cover to keep warm.
4.        Cook the eggs how you like using the butter.
5.        Put the eggs over the eggplant hash. Serve with remaining butter from the pan and Worcestershire sauce. Season with additional salt and pepper if desired.

column3: क्रीम चीज़ टॉपिंग के साथ पैनकेक
column24:
For Cream Cheese Topping:
•        1 tbsp cream cheese
•        1 tsp olive oil
•        1 tablespoon pesto
•        1/2 medium red onion, sliced thin
•        Salt and pepper to taste
For Pancakes:
•        1 large egg
•        1 tbsp cottage cheese
•        1 tsp psyllium husk powder
•        1 teaspoon garlic, minced
•        Salt to taste
•        1 tablespoon butter, for frying
column25:
1.	Gather and prep all ingredients.
2.	In a bowl, make the cream cheese topping by mixing cream cheese, pesto, and half of the olive oil together. Stir until well combined and set aside.
3.	Make the pancake batter next. In a bowl, add the eggs, cottage cheese, psyllium husk powder, minced garlic, and salt to taste. Mix until the consistency is smooth then let it sit for about 10 minutes.
4.	In a frying pan, melt the butter on medium heat. Spoon the pancake batter into the pan, forming small circles about 2-3? in diameter. Fry the pancakes on both sides until golden brown in color.
5.	Plate the pancakes and top with cream cheese topping, sliced onion, and remaining olive oil. Season additionally with salt and pepper if desired. Enjoy!

column24:
•       1 egg, beaten
•        1 tablespoon coconut flour
•        1/4 teaspoon psyllium husk powder
•        Salt to taste
•        2 tablespoon butter
•        2 tablespoon coconut cream
•        1/4 cup raspberries
column25:
1.        Gather and prep all ingredients.
2.        In a bowl, mix together the beaten egg, coconut flour, psyllium husk powder, and salt.
3.        On the stovetop over low heat, melt butter and coconut cream. Slowly add the egg mixture, whisking together until you have a creamy consistency.
4.        Top the coconut porridge with fresh raspberries. Feel free to add a splash of coconut or almond milk if desired.

column24:
For Donut Holes:
•        1/4 medium lemon
•        2 tsp avocado oil
•        1 tablespoon water
•        1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
•        2 tbsp almond flour
•        1 tsp stevia
•        Pinch of salt
For Lemon Glaze:
•        1/2 tsp powdered stevia/erythritol blend
•        2 teaspoons lemon juice, as needed
column25:
1.        Measure out and prepare all the ingredients. Preheat oven to 350F.
2.        Line a baking sheet with parchment paper.
3.        Cut the lemon into small wedges and remove the seeds.
4.        Place the lemon wedges, avocado oil, water, and vanilla extract into a blender. Blend on medium until smooth, then remove any small pieces that will not blend.
5.        Add the almond flour, stevia/erythritol blend, and salt. Continue to blend until thickened and dough forms.
6.        With a cookie scooper or dinner spoon, form balls and roll until smooth with your hands. Place these on the parchment-lined baking sheet. Bake in the oven for 10-12 minutes.
7.        In a bowl, make the glaze by adding powdered stevia/erythritol blend and lemon juice. Add the lemon juice a little bit at a time, stirring together until a smooth glaze forms. Optionally, add yellow food coloring to the glaze.
8.        Once the donuts come out of the oven, let them cool.
9.        Dip the donut holes into the lemon glaze. You may serve right away!

column24:
•        1 large egg
•        1/2 tablespoon butter
•        2 tsp cheddar cheese, shredded
•        1/4 medium red onion, diced
•         2 cremini mushrooms, sliced
•        Salt and pepper to taste
column25:
1.	Prep ingredients: shred the cheese, slice the mushrooms and chop the onion.
2.	In a bowl, crack the eggs and add a little salt and pepper to taste. Whisk with a fork until it is all mixed together and slightly frothy.
3.	Melt the butter in a frying pan. Add the chopped red onion and sliced mushrooms to the pan. Season to taste, then cook until the mushrooms are tender, stirring occasionally. Pour in the egg mixture on top, making sure it gets between the onions and mushrooms.
4.	When the omelet is starting to get done around the sides and on the bottom but still raw on top, sprinkle the cheddar cheese over the top.
5.	With a spatula, get under the omelet carefully and fold it in half.
6.	When the omelet is golden brown on the bottom, remove from the pan and serve hot.

column24:
•        1/4 cup coconut milk
•        1/4 cup unsweetened almond milk
•        1 tbsp heavy cream
•        1 tsp stevia
•        2 tsp chia seeds
•        1 tbsp lemon juice
•        1 tsp lemon zest
column25:
1.	Gather and prep all ingredients.
2.	Put the coconut milk, almond milk, cream, stevia/erythritol blend, chia seeds, lemon juice, and lemon zest into a blender.
3.	Put the lid on the blender and pulse until everything is combined.
4.	Pour the lemon chia pudding into cups.
5.	Cover the cups with plastic wrap and refrigerate for at least 5 hours before enjoying.

column24:
•        1 tbsp cream cheese, softened
•        1/2 egg
•        1 tbsp almond flour
•        1 tsp stevia 
•        1 tbsp unsweetened almond milk
column25:
1.	Gather and prep all ingredients.
2.	Add all ingredients to a blender, then pulse until smooth and well combined. Let rest for a few minutes.
3.	In a non-stick pan over medium-low heat, spray just enough cooking spray to cover the bottom of the pan. Once hot, add about 1-2 tablespoons of batter.
4.	Swirl the pan to spread the batter into a thin layer.
5.	Cook the crepe until the edges are slightly hardened and bottom can be loosened with a spatula. Flip and cook on the other side until a light golden-brown color is achieved.
6.	Repeat this process with all of the batter. Fill or top with your favorite fillings (we love them with keto nutella).
7.	Serve warm and enjoy! Feel free to add a few extra berries or powdered erythritol for some added aesthetic (just make sure you take any additions into account when calculating macros).

column24:
•        1 cup cauliflower 
•         3 tbsp tomato puree
•        1 tbsp olive oil
•        2 tsp coconut milk
•        1/2 tsp cumin seeds
•        1/2 tsp ginger-garlic paste
•        1 tsp dried fenugreek leaves
•        1 tsp tandoori masala 
•        ½ tsp coriander powder
•        ½ tsp garam masala
•        ½ tsp red chili powder
•         ½ tsp turmeric
•        Fresh coriander for garnishing
•        Salt to taste
column25:
1. Remove florets fromcauliflower and clean the same. Season with 1 tablespoon olive oil, salt, and tandoori masala.
Bake the seasoned cauliflower in the oven at 2000C for 15 to 20 minutes. Let it sit in the oven.
Take a saucepan and place it on medium-high heat. Add the remaining olive oil to it and fry the cumin seeds and ginger-garlic paste in it.
Now, add the tomato puree and species to the saucepan. Cover it and cook for about 10 minutes.
Add the coconut milk to the saucepan and garnish it with fresh coriander. Add salt to taste.
Add the sauce to the cauliflower and bake for 10 minutes.
Serve and enjoy!

column24:
•        Eggplants 1
•        Tomato 1/2
•        Bell peppers 1/2
•        Olive oil 1 Tsp
•        Oregano 1/2 tsp
•        Salt and pepper
•        Feta cheese 1 tbsp
•        Parsley 2 tsp
column25:
1.        Toss the eggplant in olive oil, seasoning, sumac and oregano and mix. Roast at 180 degrees Celsius for 8 - 10 minutes or till done.
2.        Toss the tomato and bell peppers in olive oil, herbs and seasoning as well and roast at 180 degrees Celsius for 8- 10 minutes or till done.
3.        For assembly, top each half of the boat with 2-3 tablespoons of the roasted vegetable mixture.
4.        Top with crumbled feta cheese, pomegranate seeds, finely chopped parsley and drizzle with Olive Oil on top. Serve it hot.

column3: पालक और पनीर भरवां शिमला मिर्च
column24:
•        1 bell peppers
•        3 tbsp spinach, frozen defrosted
•        1 tsp Cream cheese
•        1 tsp Feta cheese
•        1 tsp Mozzarella cheese grated keep
•        1 tsp Parmesan cheese vegetarian
•        1 teaspoon garlic powder
•        1/4 teaspoon salt
•        ½ teaspoon black pepper
•        1 teaspoon onion powder
column25:
1.	Preheat the oven to 180C/350F degrees.
2.	Cut the peppers in half lengthways and remove the seeds. Place them in a baking dish or on a baking tray.
3.	In a medium bowl, mix the spinach with the cheeses and seasoning. (Remember to set aside ¼ cup of the mozzarella cheese).
4.	Spoon the mixture into the pepper halves. Top with the remaining mozzarella cheese.
5.	Bake for 20 minutes until the top of the peppers are golden.
6.	Serve whilst warm with chopped chives or parsley on top.

column24:
•        1/2 Carrot-medium sized
•        1/4 Beetroot- small sized
•        1 1/2 cup water – approx. 2 liters of water, boiled
•        1 teaspoon red chili powder -add as needed
•        1 tablespoon yellow mustard seeds 
•        1 tablespoon salt
column25:
1.        Rinse and then peel the orange carrots & beetroots
2.        Chop into long sticks.
3.        First boil water & let it cool at room temperature. Cover the pan when the water cools
4.        In a clean ceramic or glass jars with wide mouth, add carrots, beets, ground yellow mustard powder, pink Himalayan salt and red chilli powder
5.        Mix all ingredients.
6.        Cover loosely with a lid or secure and tie a muslin cloth on the top of the jar. 
7.        Keep the jar in the sun for upto 2 to 3 days or may be more upto 4-5 days depending upon the sun in your area
8.        Stir with a wooden spoon or shake the jar everyday
9.        When the Kanji tastes sour, it means the drink is fermented.
10.      Serve Kanji straightaway or refrigerate. It can be stored in refrigerator for about 4-5 days.

column24:

•        2 tsp Coffee
column25:
1.        Brew a cup of coffee using any brewing method you’d like.
2.        Add butter, MCT oil, and coffee to a blender. Blend on high for 30 seconds. Enjoy.

column24:

•        ½ tsp ginger powder
•        ¼ tsp tsp cinnamon

column25:

2.        Blend on high speed for 40 seconds, or until thick and golden.
3.        Pour into a glass, and sprinkle cinnamon and turmeric.

column25:

2.        Place chia seeds in a tall glass and pour hot tea over the seeds.  
3.        Wait 30 minutes, stir, then place glass in the freezer.
4.        Wait 30 more minutes, or until tea is chilled.

column24:

4.	Pour into glasses and serve immediately!

column24:

3.        Pour into glasses and serve immediately.

column24:

column24:

•        2 tsp hemp seeds

2.	Place all the ingredients in a blender and blend until you reach your desired consistency.
3.	Sprinkle with extra cacao nibs, if desired. Enjoy!

column24:
•        1/2 tbsp Flax seed ground
•        1/2 tbsp Almond Flour
•        1 tbsp psyllium husk
•        1/4 tsp Cumin Powder
•        ½ tsp Coriander + Green Chili paste(optional)
•        ½ tsp Turmeric Powder
•        1 Tbsp Mint leaves (optional)
•        1/2 Tbsp Coriander Leaves (optional)
•        Pinch of Salt
•        4tbsp Lukewarm water
column25:
1.	Mix all the ingredients and make a dough.
2.	Now make small balls out of the dough and cover it with a muslin cloth. Next, take these balls and press them to get a circle shape resembling a very thin chapati. 
3.	Now roast the khakra on the heated griddle and keep on roasting it till you get a golden colour on both sides of the khakra. To make your khakra even crispier, press it gently while it is on the griddle with the help of cotton cloth.

column24:
CURRY PASTE:
•        2 ½   tbsp Kashmiri chilli powder 
•        1 tbsp coriander
•        2 tsp cumin
•        1 tsp turmeric
•        1/2 tsp fenugreek powder 
•        3/8 tsp ground cloves
•        6 cloves garlic, minced
•        1 tbsp fresh ginger, finely grated
•        1 tbsp tamarind puree 
•        1/2 red onion, chopped
•        6 tbsp water (plus more, as needed)
•        CURRY:
•        1 tbsp vegetable oil
•        1/2 tsp black mustard seeds 
•        1/2 red onion, cut in half again (like a quartered orange) and thinly sliced
•        1 tbsp tomato paste
•        2/3 cup water
•        100ml/ 14oz coconut milk, full fat 
•        1 1/4 tsp salt, cooking/kosher (or 3/4 tsp fine table salt)
•       1/2 tsp sugar
•        1/4 tsp chilli powder (pure chilli, not US Chili Powder which is a mix
•        2 long green chillies, cut into half lengthwise and deseeded, optional 
•        1/2 tomato, cut into 8 wedges then into 2.5cm / 1" chunks
•        150g firm-fleshed white fish , cut into 3cm / 1.25" cubes
column25:
1.        Place Curry Paste ingredients in a tall jug or milkshake container (something that fits the head of a blender stick) then blitz on high for 5 to 10 seconds until the onion is pureed. Add more water if needed to make it puree.
2.        Heat oil over medium heat in a large pot. Add black mustard seeds and let them sizzle for 30 seconds - careful, they might pop!
3.        Add red onion and cook for 3 minutes until edges start to tinge with gold.
4.        Add curry paste and cook for 3 minutes - to evaporate water, make spices bloom and cook garlic & ginger.
5.        Turn heat up to medium high. Add tomato paste and tomato pulp, cook for 2 minutes.
6.        Add water, coconut milk, sugar, salt and chilli powder if using. Stir, then bring to simmer, low heat so it's bubbling gently.
7.        Simmer for 2 minutes, add tomato and green chilli.
8.        Simmer for another 3 minutes, stirring every now and then - sauce should be thickened (not watery), it gets looser again when fish is added (because fish will drop some juices = even more flavour!).
9.        Add fish, stir, cook for 3 to 4 minutes until fish easily flakes.
10.        Remove from stove and transfer to serving bowl. Garnish with coriander/cilantro and fresh green chillies if desired.

column24:
•        1 teaspoon Coriander Seeds
•        1 teaspoon Cumin Seeds
•        1 teaspoon Fennel Seeds
•        1 teaspoon Carom Seeds
•        ½ teaspoon Mustard Seeds
•        ½ teaspoon Black Pepper
•        ½ Cinnamon Stick
•        1 Star anise
•        2-3 Cardamom
•        1 teaspoon Poppy Seeds
•        1 Red Chili
•        1 Egg
•        1 Bay Leaf
•        1/2 Onion Chopped
•        1 Red Chili
•        1 teaspoon Turmeric Powder
•        1 teaspoon Red Chili Powder
•        Salt to taste
•        1/2 Tomato Chopped
•        1 teaspoon Chettinad Masala
•        1/2 tablespoon Coconut Paste
•        Sprig of curry leaves
•        Water
column25:
1.	To make Chettinad egg curry, the first step is to fry the eggs.
2.	Heat oil in a pan and add soft boiled eggs in it. Turn the eggs and fry them from both sides.
3.	When the eggs are golden brown carefully take them out in a plate.
4.	Now, in the same pan add a bay leaf, chopped onions, and a red chili. Cook the onions ‘til they are golden brown and then add the spices.
5.	Add a teaspoon of turmeric powder, red chili powder, and salt.
6.	Cook the spices until they are well roasted and then add tomatoes in it.
7.	When the tomatoes are soft and pulpy add a teaspoon of Chettinad Masala and coconut paste in the masala. 
8.	Add a sprig of curry leaves in it. Roast the masala well and when the oil starts to leave the masala to add water in it.
9.	Pierce the eggs with a knife or fork and add them in the gravy. This way the eggs will be able to soak the gravy. Cover it with a lid and cook for another 4-5 minutes.
10.	Serve it hot with fried rice or chapati.

column24:
For Cooking spray
•        1 tsp olive oil
•        1 cloves garlic, crushed
•        1/2 medium scallions, chopped
•        1/4 cup cilantro, chopped
•        1medium zucchini, grated
•        kosher salt and fresh ground pepper
•        1/8 cup grated blend cheese
•        1 8-inch almond flour tortillas

    For the Enchilada sauce:
•        1 garlic cloves, minced
•        2 tbsp tomato sauce
•        1/4 tsp ground cumin
•        1/2 cup fat-free vegetable broth
•        kosher salt and fresh pepper to taste
column25:
FOR THE ENCHILADAS SAUCE
1.        In a medium saucepan, spray oil and sauté garlic.
2.        Add chili powder, cumin, broth, tomato sauce, salt and pepper. Bring to a boil.
3.        Reduce the heat to low and simmer for 5-10 minutes. Set aside until ready to use.
FOR THE ENCHILADAS:
4.        Spray a baking dish with nonstick spray. Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
5.        In a medium nonstick skillet, sauté garlic and scallions in olive oil over medium heat for about 3 minutes; add zucchini and cilantro, salt and pepper to taste and cook until all the liquid evaporates from the zucchini, about 4-5 minutes.
6.        Remove from heat and add 1/2 cup cheese; mix well.
7.        Divide zucchini between in each tortilla, roll and place seam side down in baking dish.
8.        Top with enchilada sauce (you might not use all) and remaining cheese and bake until hot and the cheese is melted, about 20 minutes.
9.        Serve with chopped cilantro and scallions

column24:
For Crust
•        1/4 cup Almond flour
•        ¼ tsp sea salt
•       1  tbsp ghee
•        ½ tsp vanilla extract
For Filing
•        2 cloves Garlic, grated
•        1/4 cup grams Broccoli, cut to florets
•        1 Red Bell pepper 
•        1 Tomato, finely chopped
•        1/4 teaspoon Nutmeg, grated
•        1 teaspoon Red Chilli flakes
•        1/4 cup Cheddar cheese
•        1 tsp Extra Virgin Olive Oil
column25:
For the crust of the Quiche
1.        Preheat the oven to 350 degrees F (177 degrees C). Line the bottom of a 9 in (23 cm) round pie pan with parchment paper, or grease well.
2.        In a large bowl, mix together the almond flour, erythritol (if using), and sea salt.
3.        Stir in the melted ghee, until well combined. (If using vanilla, stir that into the melted ghee before adding to the dry ingredients.) The "dough" will be dry and crumbly. Just keep mixing, pressing and stirring, until it's uniform and there is no almond flour powder left. (Alternatively, you can use a food processor to mix it all together.)
4.        Press the dough into the bottom of the prepared pan. You can flute the edges of desired; if it crumbles when doing this, just press it back together. Carefully poke holes in the surface using a fork to prevent bubbling.
5.        Bake for 10-12 minutes, until lightly golden
For the Filling
6.        Heat a tablespoon of olive oil in a wok; stir fry the red bell peppers and the garlic until the peppers are roasted and lightly soft. Next add in the half way while the peppers are roasting. Stir fry the broccoli until just about tender, but still firm. 
7.        Now we will make the white sauce for the quiche; whisk together bechamel sauce, sun dried tomatoes, nutmeg, red chilli flakes and salt in a large bowl until smooth. Once the pie shell has been bakes until golden, remove from the oven and pour white sauce filling into the pre baked pie shell. Add in broccoli, then sprinkle with cheeses on the top.
8.        Place the Broccoli Quiche back into the oven and bake until the quiche custard is ser and the cheese has a golden crust on the top. The centre will be shaky but it will continue to set as the quiche cools.
9.        Once done, remove from the oven. Serve Broccoli Cheddar Quiche hot.

column24:
•        80 grams paneer
•        1/2 grams capsicum
•        1/2 grams tomatoes chopped
•        1/2 grams onion chopped
•        1tsp grams garlic (chopped)
•        1 tsp grams ginger (chopped)
•        1 green chili
•        1 tbsp butter
•        1 tbsp coriander powder
•        1 tbsp cumin seeds
•        1/2 teaspoon red chili powder
•        1/2 teaspoon turmeric
•        as per your taste Salt
•        as required Fresh coriander
column25:
1.        Start with grating the paneer in a bowl. Set aside.
2.        Place a pan on medium heat and add ghee to it. Once it melts completely, fry cumin seeds and onion in the melted ghee.
3.        Now fry garlic, ginger, and green chili in it.
4.        Next, add the tomatoes, chili powder, coriander powder, and turmeric. Use a spatula to ensure everything cooks fine.
5.        Add some water to the mixture and cook for 5 to 7 minutes.
6.        Now add the capsicum, paneer, and salt and keep cooking for 3 to 5 minutes.
7.        Turn off the heat and garnish with fresh coriander and a tablespoon of butter.
8.        Serve hot!

column24:
•        80 gm Paneer/Cottage Cheese  
•        ½ Onion
•        ½ Tomato
•        ½ Green Pepper/Capsicum
•        2 tbsp Cheddar Cheese
•        ½ tsp Chopped Ginger
•        ½ tsp Chopped Garlic
•        1 Chilly
•        1tsp Ghee/Butter 
•        Salt
•        ½ tsp Cumin Seeds  
•        1/6 tsp Turmeric  
•        1/6 tsp Kashmiri Red Chilli Powder  
•        ½ tsp Coriander Powder  
•        Fresh Coriander
column25:
1.	Grate the paneer or crumble it.
2.	Heat 1 tbsp of ghee/butter/oil in the pan and fry the onions and cumin seeds
3.	Add the ginger, garlic and green chilly and fry.
4.	Add in the tomatoes along with the tumeric, chilli powder, coriander powder and season
5.	Pour some water and cover and cook for 5-6 minutes
6.	Add the green peppers and paneer and season with salt.
7.	Add the cheese and cook for a further 3-4 minutes
8.	Finish with fresh coriander and a tablespoon of butter
9.	Serve

column24:
• 200 gm paneer/cottage cheese (cubes)
• 1/2 Onion chopped
• 1 Tomato chopped
• 1/2 green chili
• 1 Clove garlic
• 1/2 tsp ginger paste
• 3 tbsp Heavy Whipping Cream
• 1 tbsp Butter
• 1/2 tsp Cumin Seeds
• 1/2 tsp Red Chilli Powder
• 1/2 Coriander Powder
• 1 tsp Turmeric Powder
• 1 tsp Garam Masala
• Salt to Taste
• 1/2 tsp dried fenugreek leaves
• fresh coriander leaves/cilantro leaves (for garnish)
column25:
1. Cut paneer into pieces and smear 1/2 tsp turmeric powder, salt and 1/2 tsp red chilli powder all over the paneer pieces.In a skillet, heat 1 tbsp butter and grill the paneer pieces for 2-3 minutes on both sides, till both the sides are slightly done. Don't grill for long; it will make the paneer pieces hard.
2. In a pan heat butter, add cumin seeds and let them splutter. Add ginger paste, chopped green  chilli, onions, garlic, tomato and saute it well for 2-3 minutes till the onions and tomatoes are spongy.
3. Let this mixture cool and then using a grinder, grind this into a fine paste. Don't add any water.
4. In the same pan, add this fine paste and saute well. To this mixture add turmeric powder, red chilli powder, coriander powder, garam masala and saute the mixture for 3-4 minutes.
5. On low heat, add the heavy whipping cream into gravy and mix it well. Add the grilled paneer pieces, dried fenugreek leaves and simmer the gravy for few minutes till oil starts to seperate.
6.Take off heat and finally sprinkle freshly chopped coriander (cilantro) leaves on top. Serve with cauli rice.

column24:
•        small cube Paneer
•        1 Tsp Ginger Garlic Paste 
•        1 Tsp Salt
•        1/4 Tsp Tumeric 
•        1/2 Tsp Red Chilli Powder 
•        1/2 Tsp Coriander Powder 
•        1/2 Tsp Cumin Powder 
•        1 1/2 tbsp Melted Butter/Ghee (Clarified Butter) 
•        Coriander and Lemon for garnish
column25:
1. Mix the ginger garlic paste, salt, chilli powder, tumeric, coriander & cumin powder and half the melted butter/ghee together.
2. Chop paneer into bite size pieces and mix with the paste
3. Heat the remaining ghee/butter/oil in the pan
4. Fry the paneer for 1-2 minutes of each side till nice and golden brown.

column24:
•        Small cube Paneer 
•        1 Onion 
•        1 gram Capsicum 
•        Small piece Ginger 
•        2 pods garlic 
•        2 tbsp Spring Onion 
•        1 Tbsp Vinegar
•         1 Tsp Soya Sauce 
•        1 Tsp Chilly Sauce
•        1 Tbsp olive oil 
•        Salt to Taste Pepper to taste
column25:
1.	Cut the paneer into big chunks, season with salt & pepper. 
2.	Fry till golden brown on either side and cut into bite size pieces Fry the ginger and garlic and green chilli in a wok.
3.	Add in the onions and capsicum. Add in the vinegar, soya sauce, chilli sauce and some water Cook for 2 minutes and add in the paneer.
4.	Cook till all the liquid is dried up. 
5.	Garnish with spring onion greens.

column24:
•        Small cube Paneer
•        1 Onion 
•        1 Tomato 
•        1 Green Peppers 
•        1 tbsp Butter 
•        1 tbsp olive oil 
•        1 tbsp Cumin Seeds 
•        Small piece of Ginger 
•        2 pods garlic 
•        1 tbsp Vinegar 
•        1/2 Tsp turmeric 
•        1/2 Tsp Red Chilly Powder
•        1 Tsp Coriander powder
•        2 Dried Red Chillies
•        1 Green Chilly 
•        Salt to Taste 
•        Fresh Coriander
column25:
1.	Cut the paneer into bite size pieces and set aside.
2.	Heat the oil and butter in a pan and fry the cumin and red chillies till fragrant.
3.	Add in the onion and fry till soft.
4.	Add in the ginger, garlic and green chilly and fry till they start browning.
5.	Add in the tomato, turmeric, chilly powder and coriander powder 
6.	Add the vinegar and a splash of water and cook down 
7.	Finally add the paneer and season with salt and cook for 2 minutes Finish with fresh coriander and serve.

column24:
•        50 gm paneer
•        1 green chilli
•        1 teaspoon chilli garlic paste
•        1 teaspoon coriander powder
•        1 teaspoon kasoori methi powder
•        1 tablespoon lemon juice
•        1 tablespoon virgin olive oil
•        2 cloves garlic
•        1/4 cup yoghurt (curd)
•        1/2 teaspoon garam masala powder
•        1 teaspoon dry mango powder
•        1 teaspoon red chilli powder
•        salt as required
column25:
1.	Take a bowl. Add curd, lemon juice, chilli garlic paste, garam masala, coriander powder, dry mango powder, kasoori methi, red chilli powder and salt as per taste. Give a good mix to prepare a thick marinade.
2.	Chop the paneer into small cubes and add them to the prepared marinade. Mix well to coat all the cubes properly. 
3.	Let them sit aside for 10 minutes.
4.	Now take a non-stick tawa or pan. Add olive oil to it and let it heat up. Add finely chopped garlic and green chillies. 
5.	Cover the pan with a lid and keep the flame low to let the oil absorb the garlic-chilli flavours and aroma. 
6.	After a few minutes add all the paneer cubes one by one to the pan. Cover with a lid and let them cook on low medium heat. 
7.	Toss and turn the paneer to cook it from all the sides.
8.	Once golden brown in colour, your Chilli Garlic Paneer is ready to be served. Serve with a dip of your choice.

column24:
•        1 small cube Paneer 
•        1 tsp Salt 
•        1 tsp Chilli Powder 
•        ¼ tsp Cumin Powder 
•        ½ tsp Turmeric Powder 
•        ½ tsp Garam Masala
•        1 tsp Ghee
column25:
1. Cut the paneer into large cubes and put them in a bowl.
2. To this add salt, chili powder, cumin powder, turmeric powder, garam masala and mix well. Let the coated cubes sit aside for 15 mins.
3. For the coriander mint chutney, add coriander leaves, mint leaves, onion, ginger, garlic, green chilies, lemon juice, salt and a little water to a mixer jar and grind them into a fine paste.
4. To a wide pan, add ghee and place the marinated paneer pieces in it.
5. Roast the paneer pieces on all sides on medium flame.
6. It roughly takes about 1-2 mins to fully roast on each side.
7. Take out the roasted paneer, garnish with chopped coriander leaves and sprinkle some chaat masala powder.
9. Serve it hot with some coriander mint chutney or tomato ketchup by the side.

column24:
•        1 small cube Paneer 
•        1/4 cup fresh methi leaves (fenugreek leaves)
•        ¼ teaspoon turmeric powder
•        ½ teaspoon kashmiri red chili powder
•        ½ teaspoon Coriander Powder (ground coriander)
•        ½ teaspoon Garam Masala Powder
•        ¾ to 1 cup water – i added 1 cup water
•        ¼ cup fresh cream
•        2 tablespoon oil
•        salt as required
column25:
1.	In a pan or kadai heat oil. Add cumin seeds.
2.	Stir and saute till the cumin seeds change color and splutter on low heat.
3.	Now add chopped onions.
4.	Stir very well and saute them on a low to medium heat till they become light brown stirring often.
5.	Then add chopped ginger, chopped garlic, chopped green chilies and chopped cashews. Saute for 10 to 15 seconds or till the raw aroma of ginger and garlic goes away.
6.	Add chopped tomatoes. Mix well and saute the tomatoes till they soften on medium-low heat stirring often. Switch off the heat once the tomatoes soften. Set the pan aside.
7.	When this onion-tomato mixture cools down, add it in a grinder or blender jar. Add about ¼ to ⅓ cup water and grind or blend to a fine smooth paste. Keep aside.
8.	Making Methi Malai Paneer
9.	In the same pan, now add 1 tablespoons of oil.
10.	Add methi leaves. Stir and saute the methi leaves till they wilt and soften on low heat.
11.	Next add turmeric powder, Kashmiri red chili powder and coriander powder.
12.	Mix and stir the spice powders with the sauteed methi leaves.
13.	Now add the ground onion tomato paste prepared earlier. Stir and mix very well.
14.	On a low heat saute the entire mixture for 7 to 8 minutes. Keep on stirring so that the masala does not stick to the pan. Add water. 
15.	Stir again very well. Now add salt as per taste.
16.	On a low to medium heat simmer the gravy for 3 to 4 minutes.
17.	Now add ¼ cup light or low fat cream. Instead of light cream you can add 2 tablespoons of whipping cream or heavy cream.
18.	Stir the cream very well with the rest of the gravy.
19.	Add paneer cubes and garam masala powder. Switch off the heat.
20.	Mix very well. Check the taste of gravy and add salt if needed.

column24:
•        1 small cube Paneer 
•        ½ Tbsp Ginger garlic paste
•        1/2 teaspoon Salt 
•        1/4 teaspoon Black pepper powder
•        1 tablespoons Olive oil 
•        1 divided Bell pepper 
•        1 tablespoons Olive oil 
•        2 pod Green cardamom 
•        1 pod Cloves 
•        1 Cinnamon stick 
•        1 Onion 
•        1 Tomato 
•        ½ tsp Salt
•        ½ tsp Red chili
•        ½ tsp Turmeric
•        1 tsp Coriander powder
•        2 tbsp Heavy cream
•        ½ tsp Garam masala
•        2 tbsp Coriander
•        1 tsp Dry fenugreek leave
column25:
1. In a mixing bowl, add 200 grams paneer, 1 tablespoon ginger garlic paste, 1/2 teaspoon salt, 1/4 teaspoon black pepper powder and mix it well.
2. Marinate for 20 - 25 minutes.
3. Heat 1 tablespoon olive oil in a pan, add the marinated paneer in it and cook for 5 - 7 minutes on medium heat or until it turns golden brown in color from all sides.
4. Heat 1 tablespoon olive oil in a another pan, add 120 grams bell pepper and saute for 3 - 5 minutes on medium heat.
5. Remove it from heat and keep aside.
6. Heat 2 tablespoons olive oil in a another pan, add 2 pods cardamom, 2 pods cloves, 1 cinnamon stick and stir for a minute.
7. Then, add 80 grams onions and fry till translucent or until it turns golden brown in color.
8. Now, add 80 grams tomato and mix it well.
9. Saute for 5 - 7 minutes on medium heat or until it turns soft and pulpy.
10. Cover it with lid and cook for about 3 - 6 minutes on medium heat.
11. Open the lid and give it a nice stir.
12. Add 1/2 teaspoon salt, 1/2 teaspoon red chili, 1/2 teaspoon turmeric, 1 teaspoon coriander powder and mix it well.
13. Then, add the sauted bell pepper, cooked paneer and mix it well.
14. Now, add 280 milliliters heavy cream and mix it well.
15. Cook for 5 - 7 minutes on medium heat.
16. Add 1/2 teaspoon garam masala, 2 tablespoons coriander, 1 teaspoon dry fenugreek leaves and mix it well.
17. Cook for another 2 - 3 minutes on medium heat.
18. Remove it from heat.
19. Garnish with dry fenugreek leaves.
20. Serve

column24:
•         ½  chopped onion
•        2 tablespoons chopped cashews
•        1 tablespoon almonds
•        1 tablespoon magaz or melon seeds without the skin
•        ½ teaspoon chopped garlic or 3 to 4 small to medium-sized garlic
•        ½ teaspoon chopped ginger or 1-inch ginger
•        1 cups water 
•        2 tsp Ghee (clarified butter)
•        1 teaspoon Coriander Powder
•        ¼ teaspoon Garam Masala Powder 
•        ½ teaspoon red chili powder
•        ½ cup Curd (yogurt), 125 grams 
•        1 to 1.5 cups strained stock (got from boiling the onions with nuts) + water or 1 to 1.5 cups water
•        salt as required
•        ¼ teaspoon cardamom powder
•        4-5strands saffron – crushed lightly
•        50 grams Paneer (cottage cheese)
•        1 tablespoon heavy cream or add as required – optional
•        1 teaspoon kewra water
•        1 tej patta
•        2 to 3 cloves
•        2 to 3 green cardamoms
•        1 black cardamom
•        1 inch cinnamon
•        ½ teaspoon (caraway seeds) shah jeera
column25:
1.	Take the nuts and seeds in a bowl and rinse them a couple of times with water. Drain all the water and set aside. 
2.	Cook onions, cashews, almonds, magaz or melon seeds, ginger and garlic in 1.5 cups water for 8 to 10 minutes until the onions soften. 
3.	Strain the stock and set aside. Let the onions cool at room temperature. 
4.	Make a fine paste of the cooked onions, ginger, garlic along with the dry fruits adding 2 to 4 tablespoons of the strained water. 
5.	Whisk fresh curd (yogurt) till smooth and set aside. Sautéing Onion Paste Heat ghee in a frying pan on medium-low to medium heat. 
6.	Fry all the whole spices (listed in the above ingredients) until they release their aroma in the ghee. Be very attentive here, as spices are delicate and can burn quickly if you aren’t paying attention. 
7.	Add the ground onion paste and mix very well. On a low heat sauté stirring non-stop for 7 to 8 minutes or until the fat starts to leave the sides of the paste. 
8.	Add red chilli powder or cayenne pepper, garam masala powder and coriander powder. Mix well. Adding Curd And Simmering Further Reduce heat to a low or switch off the heat. 
9.	Add the whisked yogurt, 1 to 1.5 cups of the strained stock and additional water, sugar and salt as required. 
10.	Mix very well and simmer gravy for 10 to 12 minutes until it thickens. Add the cardamom powder and crushed saffron. 
11.	Stir and add the cubed paneer and cream. Mix gently and switch off heat. Add the kewra water and stir. You can even add rose water. 
12.	Garnish Shahi Paneer with some coriander leaves or mint leaves or a few saffron strands. Serve the Mughlai Shahi Paneer with cumin rice or roti, naan or paratha

column24:
•        1/2 cup extra-firm tofu, cubed
•        3 tablespoons lemon juice, divided (2-3 lemons)
•        1 tablespoon lemon zest
•        3 tablespoons olive oil, divided
•        ⅓ cup water
•       1 tbsp heavy whipping cream
•        ½ cup cauliflower florets
•        1 cloves garlic, minced
•        1 (1-inch) knob ginger, peeled and minced
•        ¼-½ teaspoon red cayenne pepper, as desired
•        1 teaspoon ground coriander seed
•        1 teaspoon ground cumin 
•        1 teaspoon ground turmeric
•        1 teaspoon cardamom 
•        ¾ teaspoon salt
•        ¼ teaspoon black pepper
•        2 cups fresh spinach
column25:
1.        Preheat oven to 375 degrees F and cover a cookie sheet with tin foil.
2.        Press tofu firmly between paper towels to remove excess moisture. Cut into 1 inch cubes and set aside. 
3.        In a medium bowl, whisk together 2 tablespoons lemon juice, lemon zest, and 1 tablespoon olive oil.
4.        Add tofu and toss to coat. Spread tofu evenly over cookie sheet. 5.  Bake until golden brown, about 20 minutes. 
5.        Combine cream, water and cauliflower in a small saucepan and bring to a simmer. 7.  Cook until cauliflower is tender, about 10 minutes. 
6.        8.  Purée mixture using a hand blender or countertop blender. Set aside.
7.        9.  Heat remaining 2 tablespoons olive oil in a large skillet over medium heat until shimmering. Add garlic and ginger and cook, stirring, until fragrant and lightly browned, about 1 minute. Add coriander, cumin, turmeric, cardamom, salt and pepper and cook, stirring, until fragrant, about 30 seconds. 
8.        10.  Add spinach one handful at a time, stirring and adding more as the greens wilt.
9.        Reduce heat to low and cook, stirring occasionally, until greens are fully wilted, about 5 minutes.
10.        Stir in cauliflower purée and continue to cook until greens are very tender, about 5 minutes longer.
11.        Stir in tofu cubes and heat through. Stir in remaining lemon juice and serve.

column24:
•        1 teaspoon coconut oil
•        ½ teaspoon cumin (jeera) seeds
•        2 green chilies finely chopped
•        1 tablespoon ginger garlic paste
•        1 stalk curry leaves
•        a big pinch asafoetida (hing)
•        1 medium onion finely chopped
•        2 medium zucchini cut into ½ inch pieces (about 1.5 - 2 cups)
•        ½ teaspoon turmeric powder
•        1 teaspoon coriander powder
•        ½ teaspoon garam masala powder
•        salt to taste
•        1 teaspoon amchur powder (dry mango powder) (OR lemon juice)
•        2 tablespoons coriander leaves (cilantro)
column25:
1.	Wash and cut zucchini into ½ inch long pieces.
2.	Heat a pan or kadai with some coconut oil and add cumin seeds let them crackle.
3.	Then add ginger garlic paste, green chilies, asafoetida ,curry leaves and saute for 30 seconds till the raw smell of ginger garlic disappears.
4.	Add onions and saute till they turn light brown in color.
5.	Add chopped Zucchini chunks ,turmeric powder ,coriander powder ,garam masala and salt. Mix everything well.
6.	Cover the pan with lid, let it cook on the low flame till it is little bit tender for 3-4 minutes. Stir in between.(i dint add any water).
7.	Once zucchini is cooked add amchur powder ,coriander leaves ,mix well and serve hot with roti, paratha or rice.

column24:
•        Broccoli 1 cup
•        Cumin seeds ½ Tsp
•        Ginger 2 Tsp
•        Onion 1/2
•        Green chili 1Tsp
•        Salt 1 Tsp
•        Turmeric powder ½ Tsp
•        Garam masala 2 Tsp
•        Tomato puree 3 tbsp 
•        Lemon juice 1 Tsp
•        Paneer small cube
column25:
1.	Take a pan add water and boil the broccoli. 
2.	Heat the pan, add 1 Tsp olive oil. 
3.	Add cumin oil, ginger, onion and tomato puree and lemon juice. 
4.	Add all the spices and cook for 5-8 minutes. 
5.	Add the paneer and broccoli and cook for 2 minutes then serve hot.

column24:
•        1 cup fresh green beans, trimmed
•        1 tablespoon avocado oil
•        2 tbsp grated Parmesan
•        1 teaspoon garlic powder
•        1 teaspoon onion powder
•        ½ teaspoon salt
•        ½ teaspoon cracked pepper
column25:
1.	Preheat oven to 425 degrees. 
2.	Add the beans and oil to a large bowl and toss to coat.
3.	Add the Parmesan, garlic powder, onion powder, salt, and pepper to a small bowl and stir to combine.
4.	Pour the Parmesan mixture over the green beans and stir to coat.
5.	Spread the green beans in an even layer in a large baking sheet, being careful not to overcrowd the pan.
6.	Bake for 25 minutes or until beans are as tender as you'd like, flipping halfway through. 
7.	Serve hot.

column24:
•        Olive oil 1 Tsp
•        Onion 1
•        Green chilli 1
•        Capsicum 1
•        Mushroom 1 cup
•        Salt 1 tsp
•        Black pepper ½ tsp
•        Schezwan sauce 1 tsp
•        Soy sauce 1 tsp
•        Garlic powder 1 tsp
column25:
1.	Cut the paneer into pieces. 
2.	Take a pan add 1 Tsp olive oil, add onion cook until get brown.
3.	Add mushrooms, sauté then add salt and cook for 2 minutes. 
4.	Now add capsicum and paneer cook for 2 minutes. 
5.	Sprinkle black pepper, add schezwan sauce, soya sauce and give it a good mix cook for 2 minutes and serve hot.

column3: सब्जियों वाला अलसी का रोल/सब्जियों वाला फ्लैक्ससीड व्रैप
column24:
•        Flax seeds 1Tbsp
