•        Chillies ½
•        Water
column25:
1.        Grind all 3 together in a blender.
2.        Make dough using hot water.
3.        Let dough rest for about 10 mins.
4.        Roll it on a silicon mat or parchment paper using a rolling pin.
5.        Cook it on a non-stick pan as you cook any normal roti/flatbread.

column24:
Thai Chicken Salad Ingredients:
•        1/2 cups chicken cooked, shredded 70
•        1/2 cup white cabbage shredded (30g)
•        1 carrot grated (20g)
•        1tbsp cilantro fresh, chopped (or 20g)
•        1tbsp almonds toasted, chopped (or 36g)
•        1tbsp green onions chopped (or 25g)
•        ½ red pepper sliced (or 82g)
•        ¼ teaspoon sea salt (or to taste)
•        10 ounces chard leaves, stems discarded (or cabbage leaves of choice) (or 280g)
•        1 tsp olive oil for brushing
Dressing: 
•        1 tbsp almond butter smooth   
•        1 tsp low-sodium soy sauce 
•        1 tsp sesame oil toasted
•        1 tablespoon apple cider vinegar
•        ½ lime juiced
•        1 tablespoon sriracha
•        1 tablespoon fresh ginger grated
•        1 clove garlic minced
column25:
1.	Preheat the oven to 350F / 180C / 160 fan.
2.	Dressing
3.	Place all the dressing ingredients in a mixing bowl and whisk with a hand balloon whisk to combine. Adjust consistency with a touch of water if you like it a bit thinner.
4.	Thai Chicken Salad
5.	Toss the chicken salad ingredients with the dressing (except chard leaves and olive oil).
6.	Place the chard or cabbage leaves in mixing bowl and cover with boiling water. Rest for 45 seconds - 1 minute to soften. Remove and place on a paper towel. Pat dry.
7.	Add approx ¼ cup of filling to each large leaf. If your leaves are smaller you can put a couple of leaves together. Tuck in the sides around the filling then roll up.
8.	Place the stuffed leaves (folded side on the bottom) on a baking tray lined with greaseproof paper and brush with a little olive oil. Option to enjoy raw or for more of a crispy warm roll, bake in the oven for about 15 minutes until slightly crisp.

column24:
•        1 Cucumber
•        50 g Smoked Salmon 
•        2 Tbsp Cream Cheese 
•        1/4 Avocado sliced
column25:
1.	Lay the cucumbers on the surface.
2.	Simply 'stuff' the remaining ingredients into the center of the slices of cucumber. Serve.

column24:
• 2 Eggs
• 1/4 Tsp Salt
• 1/4 Tsp Red Chilli Powder I use this one
• 1/8 Tsp Tumeric I recommend this
• 1 Green Chilly
• 10 grams Onion
• 5 grams Coriander
• 1 Tbsp Butter
column25:
1. Beat the eggs with salt, chilli powder, turmeric, coriander, onion and green chilli
2. Fry in butter in a hot non stick pan
3. Flip or Fold the egg when one side is cooked.
4. Serve with keto bread or eat as is

column24:
• 3 Tablespoons butter or margarine
• 2 medium onions, chopped
• 12 oz. (about 2 cups) grated carrots
• ½ cup chopped pitted dates
• ⅓ cup dried currants or raisins
• 2 Tablespoons lemon juice
• 4 large eggs, lightly beaten
• About ½ teaspoon salt
•Butter or margarine for frying
column25:
1. Heat the butter in a large skillet over medium heat. Add the onions and carrots and sauté until softened, 5 to 10 minutes.
2. Add the dates, currants, and lemon juice. Stir into the eggs. Add the salt.
3. Heat the butter or margarine in a large skillet over medium heat. In batches, drop the egg mixture by about 1½ tablespoons to form thin patties.                                                                                                                                                                                    4. Fry until the edges turn golden brown, about 2 minutes. Turn and fry until golden brown. Drain on paper towels.

column24:
• 4 eggs 
• ¼ cup water
• 0.7 oz dill
• 2 tablespoons butter unsalted
• ¼ red pepper finely diced
• ¼ yellow pepper finely diced
• ¼ orange pepper finely diced
• 1 red onion small
• 1 jalapeno pepper optional
• ½ teaspoon salt
¼ teaspoon black pepper
column25:
1. Whisk the eggs with the water until you achieve a uniform mixture.
2. Add the chopped dill and whisk until incorporated. I usually use scissors to cut any fine herbs, and it makes the job SO much faster.

3. Chop your veggies. Depending on what way you plan to 'finish' off your omelette (read the section below), you may need smaller pieces vs. larger.
4. Heat up the butter in a large non-stick frying pan/skillet. For a single-serve omelette then a 6-inch pan will be more than enough. 5. For two servings, then between an 8-10-inch pan.
6. Finely dice your onion and add it to the pan. Lightly saute on medium heat for about a minute, then add in the remainder of the vegetables.
7. Saute the vegetables for just a few minutes, until they begin to soften. At this point, you could add some additional seasonings to the vegetables, if you prefer (like salt & pepper, cayenne, paprika, turmeric, etc.).
8. Reduce the heat to low and pour in the egg mixture. Allow it to sit for just a few seconds to firm up, give the pan a little shake to dispense the egg on top, and then using a small rubber spatula gently push/gently fold the egg away from the sides.
Tilt the pan slightly and allow excess egg to flow into the corners. This way all the uncooked eggs will move to the sides, and your omelette will cook faster. You want your omelette to be vibrant and fluffy but without overcooking the eggs.

As an optional step, you could place a lid over the omelette for a couple of minutes. This will allow the water in the egg mixture to steam up further and help cook the top of the eggs even faster.
Just before it's served, sprinkle with salt and pepper and then serve immediately. I usually shake the pan a bit to make sure the egg mixture is loose and then, holding a plate below the pan, tilt the pan and allow it to slowly slide onto the plate.

column24:
• 2 tomato
• 1 tablespoon refined oil
• 1/2 teaspoon chilli powder
• 4 egg
salt as required
• 1/2 teaspoon black pepper
column25:
1. Chop the tomatoes
To prepare this delicious recipe, wash the tomatoes with cold water and chop them finely.

 2. Beat the eggs and next, heat some oil in a non-stick pan over medium flame and stir-fry the tomatoes. On the other hand, take a bowl and beat the eggs along with salt, chilli powder and pepper.

3. Cook the eggs ,now pour the eggs into the pan and cook until it gets golden brown in colour. Now flip the omelette. Cook from both sides.

4. Ready to be served
Once done, remove from the heat and serve hot. You can even garnish it with cilantro.

column24:
•        2 large eggs
•        1/2 large avocado (100 g/ 3.5 oz)
•        1/2 package smoked salmon (50 g)
•        2 heaped tbsp full-fat cream cheese 
•        2 tbsp freshly chopped chives
•        1 medium spring onion, chopped 
•        1 tbsp ghee or butter
•        sea salt & pepper, to taste
column25:
1.	Crack the eggs into a mixing bowl with a pinch of salt and pepper and beat them well with a whisk or fork.
2.	Mix the cream cheese with chopped chives. Slice the smoked salmon, peel and slice the avocado.
3.	Pour the eggs evenly in a hot pan greased with ghee. Cook over a medium-low heat. Don't rush it and don't try to cook it fast or the omelet will end up being too crispy and dry.
4.	Use a spatula to bring in the egg from the sides towards to centre for the first 30 seconds. Cook for another minute or two. Make sure you don't cook the omelet for too long. The desired texture should be soft, fluffy and not too juicy.
5.	Slide the omelet onto a plate and spoon the cheese spread all over.
6.	Add the salmon, avocado, chopped spring onion and fold into a wrap.
7.	Serve immediately or store in the fridge for up to a day.

column24: •        Eggs 2
column25:
1.        Bring a large pot of water to a boil, then reduce the heat to low.
2.        While waiting for the water to boil, crack an egg into a small fine mesh sieve over a bowl. Swirl the egg in the sieve until all the liquidy egg whites have been removed. Then, place the egg in a ramekin.
3.        Stir the vinegar into the water and create a vortex. Add the egg to the middle of the vortex and cook the egg for 3 minutes.
4.        Remove the egg with a slotted spoon and dab it on a paper towel to remove any excess water. Serve immediately.
5.        Alternatively, if making the poached eggs for meal prep or ahead of time, transfer the cooked poached eggs to an ice water bath and refrigerate for a couple of days. When ready to serve, add boiling water to a bowl, then add the cold poached egg and submerge for 20-30 seconds or until warmed through. Remove the poached egg with a slotted spoon, dab dry and serve immediately.

column24:
•        2 to 3 eggs
•        Extra-virgin olive oil, for the pan
•        Sea salt and freshly ground black pepper
column25:
1.	Crack each egg into a ramekin or small bowl.
2.	Brush a nonstick skillet with olive oil and heat over low heat. Pour in the eggs, cover with a clear glass lid, and continue to cook over low heat for about 2 minutes, or until the whites are set.
3.	Season with salt and pepper and serve hot.

column24:
•        125 gm Bottle Gourd, finely grated
•        Dried rose petals, a few
•        1.50 Finely chopped almonds
•        1 tbsp Ghee / clarified butter
•        0.50 tsp Cardamom Powder
•        1/4 tsp Stevia sweetener powder
•        100 gm Cream
column25:
1.	Grate the bottle gourd and squeeze out water and liquid.
2.	Heat the pan and add ghee. Keep it on low flame.
3.	Add squeezed bottle gourd to the pan. Saute for 2-3 minutes until it becomes a little dry.
4.	Add cream and saute for at least 5-7 minutes until the cream starts getting absorbed by the bottle gourd.
5.	Then add sweetener and cardamom powder to it. Saute for a few seconds until it mixes up properly.
6.	Lauki halwa is ready! Garnish with almonds and rose petals and serve hot in a bowl.

column24:
•        150g grated lauki.
•        100g heavy whipping cream or heavy cream.
•        25g ghee.
•        1 tbsp sweetener or as per taste.
•        2 tbsp mixed nuts crushed (use almonds, macadamia nuts and few strands of saffron).
•        Reserve some for topping later.
•
column25:
1.        Squeeze out all the moisture of grated lauki using a kitchen towel or napkin.
2.        Heat up the ghee in a pan and add the Lauki.
3.        Let it cook for 7-8minutes.
4.        Add the cream and let it cook on a low to medium flame for 10minutes.
5.        Keep stirring so that it does not burn. The kheer should have a much thicker consistency by now.
6.        Add the sweetener and the nuts and cook for another couple of minutes. 
7.        You can add a few drops of water to reduce the thickness of kheer .
8.        You can serve this warm or once cooled, you can refrigerate it and serve. Garnish with the reserved mixed nuts.

column24:
•        30 gms Hershey's Dark Unsweetened Cocoa
•        200 gms Urban Platter Almond Flour
•        1 cup or 100gms of sweetener, according to taste, 1 have used Magic Leaf,
•        1 pinch Salt
•        1 tsp Baking Powder
•        150 ml Olive Oil
•        3 Large Eggs
For the Icing
•        200 gms Mooz Mascarpone Cheese
•        10 gms Davidoff Coffee
•        30 gms Amul Whipping Cream
•        5 gms Sweetener
column25:
1.	Start by taking 3 mixing bowls.
2.	Boil 150ml of water and sift the cocoa while the water boils.
3.	Add the hot water to a bowl, add the cocoa and stir till dissolved completely.
4.	Keep it aside and let it cool.
5.	In the second bowl add the flour, salt and baking powder and mix well.
6.	In the third bowl or a blender mix together the olive oil, eggs and sweetener till the foam
7.	Ensure you preheat your oven to 170°C or 325ºF, for about 8 mins. Grease an 8-inch baking pan with a little oil and keep it ready.
8.	Pour the mixture into the pan and first bake for 30mins at 180 degrees Celsius. Check with a toothpick at 25 mins and ensure that the cake is not overbaked.
9.	I had added the slivered Almonds at 15mins and by the time they reached the 30mins mark they were nice and toasted.
10.	My cake was moist at 30mins so I baked it for another ten mins at 200 degrees Celsius.
11.	Either serve the cake while still warm or wait for it to cool before you start icing it.
12.	For the icing I whipped together the Mascarpone Cheese and a little Amul cream.
I also added some Davidoff coffee and very little sweetener to it, to give it the perfect coffee taste.
13.	I think I am going to try this dark chocolate cake next time, without the cocoa and probably with walnuts. Give it a try and let me know if you enjoyed it, as much as I did this recipe and will share more recipes for sure.

column24:
•        3/8 cup (178.5 g) Heavy Whipping Cream
•        0.50 cup Unsweetened almond milk
•        1/4 cup (56 g) superfine almond flour
•        1 tbsp Keto Sweetener
•        1/4 tsp Grounded Cardamom
•        1 Saffron Strands crushed
column25:
1.        In a medium saucepan, whisk cream, almond milk, almond flour, keto sweetener, crushed saffron and cardamom all together.
2.        Put the pan over medium heat until the mixture is boiling, whisking frequently to prevent lumps.
3.        Once the kheer boils, turn down the heat and cook until the mixture is about the consistency of a thin pancake batter.
4.        Refrigerate it for one to two hours. Sprinkle with additional ground cardamom, before serving.
5.        If you are not on keto and still want to make this, then try coarsely ground rice flour or whirl about some rice in your blender, until you get a coarse finish and substitute that for the almond flour.
6.        And your delicious Almond Kheer is ready to serve.

column24:
•        1 egg
•        33.33 Gram Butter (melted and unsalted)
•        0.50 Tsp Baking Powder
•        33.33 Gram Almond Flour
•        0.33 Tsp Vanilla Extract
•        33.33 ml Coconut Cream or 2/3 cup heavy cream (prefer coconut cream)
•        1/6 Cup Stevia
•        1/6 Cup Sugar-Free Chocolate Chips (you can break any sugar-free slab of chocolate into small pieces)
•        1/6 Cup Cocoa Powder (preferably unsweetened)
column25:
1.	A step by step instruction guide is mentioned below. Trust us, it's not rocket science, they are easy to prepare, so lets try making them:
2.	Take a bowl & mix almond flour, baking powder, cocoa powder, and stevia.
3.	Meanwhile, preheat the oven to 170 degree celsius and prepare 12-hole muffin tray using cupcake papers.
4.	Add and blend thoroughly; eggs, heavy cream, and vanilla extract to the above mentioned mixture.
5.	Add melted butter to the mixture and combine it well.
6.	Add the sugar-free chocolate chips to the mixture and mix well so that each chocolate chip gets covered completely.
7.	Now, pour the mixture evenly on the muffin tray. Make sure that the mixture is homogeneous.
8.	Keep the muffin tray in the pre-heated oven and set the timer for 20 minutes baking.
9.	Keto chocolate muffins are ready to be served. You can have them right away or allow them to cool.Please note, muffins can shrink a little after cooling.
10.	Now you can enjoy your favourite dessert without thinking about the “ carbs”.If you like the taste, you can share the recipe with others too.

column24:
•        1 cup Almond Flour
•        1/4 cup Erythritol/ Stevia
•        2 tsp Baking Powder
•        1 tsp Cinnamon
•        1/8 tbs Sea salt
•        1/4 cup Butter unsalted; measured solid, then melted
•        1/4 cup Unsweetened almond milk
•        2 eggs
•        1/2 tsp Vanilla Extract
column25:
1.	Preheat the oven to 177 degrees Celsius (350F). Grease a donut cavities using butter.
2.	Take a bowl,add ingredients; almond flour, sweeteners, baking powder, cinnamon, sea salt & stir them together.
3.	In another bowl, whisk melted butter, almond milk, egg & vanilla extract. Now add the wet mixture into dry mixture.
4.	Pour batter evenly into the donut pan cavities. The cavities should not be completely filled but should be filled 3/4th of the total depth giving it space, so that the doughnuts can rise on baking
5.	Place the tray in the preheated oven
6.	Bake for about 22-28 minutes, until dark golden brown.
7.	Remove donuts from pan after sufficient cooling,so that it’s easy to remove them
8.	You can have donuts without coating too

column24:
•        3 oz. (6 tbsp) unsalted butter
•        ½ cup (1½ oz.) unsweetened finely shredded coconut
•        1 tsp ground cardamom (green)
•        1 tsp ground cinnamon
•        ½ tsp vanilla extract
column25:
1.        Bring the butter to room temperature.
2.        Roast the shredded coconut carefully, over medium-high heat, until lightly browned. This will create a delicious flavor, but you can skip this if you want. Let cool. 
3.        Mix together butter, half of the shredded coconut, and spices in a bowl. 
4.        Chill mixture in the refrigerator for 5 to 10 minutes, until slightly firm.

column23: All Day I Dream About Food
column24:
•        2 cups smooth peanut butter
•        1/2 cup sticky sweetener of choice
•        3/4cup coconut flour
column25:
1.	Line a large plate or tray with parchment paper and set aside.
2.	In a large mixing bowl, combine all your ingredients and mix well. Add some milk or water until a thick batter remains.
3.	Form the dough into small balls from your hands and place it on the lined plate/tray.
4.	Refrigerate the balls for 30 minutes, or until firm.
5.	Your delicious peanut butter no bake balls are ready to eat. Enjoy!

column24:
•        1 cup unsalted butter
•        60 gm baker’s chocolate
•        20 packets Stevia Sugar
•        4 tbsp Heavy Cream
•        1/3 cup natural peanut butter
column25:
1.	Take chocolate in pieces and chop the butter first. Then put them in the microwave.
2.	Melt for about a minute in the microwave, it won’t be totally melted, just mix the chocolate around in the hot butter until completely melted. Add your sweetener and mix until all melted.
3.	Stir in cream and peanut butter and taste to adjust to your own particular taste by adding more sweetener, peanut butter, etc.
4.	Line 12 or 6 cup muffin tins (depending on how thick you want to get) with cupcake papers. Use a cooking spray you prefer to grease them.
5.	Divide the chocolate mixture between the cups.
6.	Freeze until firm. They melt quickly, so you want to store them in the freezer, and they’ll be the perfect texture to eat straight out of it!

column24:
•        20 gm melted butter melted
•        1 tbsp granulated sweetener (stevia or erythritol)
•        1/2 tsp Vanilla essence
•        1 tbsp almond flour (15gm)
•        1 cup Almond milk
•        1 tsp vinegar
•        1/2 tsp Baking Powder
•        1/4 tsp Baking soda
•        2 tsp unsweetened cocoa powder
•        2 tsp walnut pieces, chopped
column25:
1.	Preheat the oven to 325 degrees. Grease a cross sectioned baking pan, and set aside.
2.	In a microwave safe bowl, add butter and microwave for about 1- - 1 ½ minutes. Now add cocoa powder and stir until fully mixed.
3.	Now add erythritol or stevia sweetener and continue to stir until fully mixed. Set it aside.
4.	In a large bowl, add almond milk and vinegar. Let it sit for a minute and when curdling starts, start whisking and whisk it well.
5.	Now add cocoa powder, baking soda, baking powder and almond flour in the milk mixture. Also add vanilla essence to it and mix it until fully incorporated. Now add walnuts and stir further until the flour is completely incorporated and walnuts are evenly distributed in it.
6.	Now spoon the batter into the greased baking pan and it bake for 20-25 minutes. Be careful not to over bake.
7.	Delicious keto walnut brownie is ready! Enjoy it with fruits or roasted nuts on the side.

column24:
•        90g butter
•        2 medium onions, roughly chopped
•        1 garlic clove, crushed
•        500g mushrooms, finely chopped (chestnut or button mushrooms work well)
•        1l hot chicken stock
•        1 bay leaf
•        4 tbsp single cream
•        small handful flat-leaf parsley, roughly chopped, to serve (optional)
column25:
1.	Heat the butter in a large saucepan and cook the onions and garlic until soft but not browned, about 8-10 mins.
2.	Add the mushrooms and cook over a high heat for another 3 mins until softened. Sprinkle over the flour and stir to combine. Pour in the chicken stock, bring the mixture to the boil, then add the bay leaf and simmer for another 10 mins.
3.	Remove and discard the bay leaf, then remove the mushroom mixture from the heat and blitz using a hand blender until smooth. Gently reheat the soup and stir through the cream (or, you could freeze the soup at this stage – simply stir through the cream when heating). Scatter over the parsley, if you like, and serve

column24:
•        1 large cauliflower (1.5kg), cut into florets
•        ½ tbsp ground cumin
•        2 tbsp olive oil, plus extra for drizzling
•        4 thyme sprigs
•        1 onion, finely chopped
•        1 celery stick, finely chopped
•        1 garlic clove, crushed
•        750-850ml veg or chicken stock
•        100ml single cream
•        ½ small bunch of parsley, finely chopped
column25:
1.	Heat the oven to 220C/200C fan/gas 7. Toss the cauliflower florets in a roasting tin with 1 tbsp olive oil, the cumin and the thyme. Roast for 15 mins or until golden and tender. Discard the thyme. 
2.	Heat the remaining oil in a saucepan with the onion and celery and fry over a medium heat for 10 mins or until softened. Add the garlic and cook for 1 min. Stir through most of the cauliflower, reserving some to top the soup with later. Add 750ml of the stock to the pan and bring to a simmer. Cook for 10 mins. 
3.	Blitz the soup until smooth using a hand blender or food processor. Stir through the cream and season to taste. Add extra stock if you like your soup a little thinner. Ladle into bowls and top with the parsley, reserved cauliflower and an extra drizzle of olive oil.

column24:
•        1/2 small onion, chopped
•        ½ tsp ground coriander
•        200g carrots, peeled and chopped
•        300ml vegetable
•        2 Tbsp coriander
column25:
1.        Put all the ingredients into the soup maker, except the coriander, and press the ‘smooth soup’ function. Make sure you don’t fill the soup maker above the max fill line. 
2.        Once the cycle is complete, season and add the coriander. Blend once again until the coriander is mixed well and serve.

column2: Red Pepper Squash And Harrisa Soup
column3: लाल मिर्च, स्क्वॉश, और हरीसा सूप
column24:
•        1/4 small butternut squash (about 200g), peeled and cut into chunks
•        1 red pepper, roughly chopped
•        1/2 red onion, roughly chopped
•        1 tbsp olive oil
•        1/4 garlic cloves in their skins
•        1 tbsp ground coriander
•        2 tsp ground cumin
•        300 ml vegetable stock
•        2 tbsp harissa paste
•        5-6 Tbsp double cream
column25:
1.        Heat oven to 180C/160C fan/gas 4. Put all the veg on a large baking tray and toss together with rapeseed oil, garlic cloves in their skins, ground coriander, ground cumin and some seasoning. Roast for 45 mins, moving the veg around in the tray after 30 mins, until soft and starting to caramelise. 
2.        Squeeze the garlic cloves out of their skins. Tip everything into a large pan. 
3.        Add the chicken or vegetable stock, harissa paste and double cream. Bring to a simmer and bubble for a few mins. 
4.        Blitz the soup in a blender, check the seasoning and add more liquid if you need to. 
5.        Serve swirled with extra cream and harissa.

column24:
•        4 ripe tomatoes, off the vine and quartered or halved
•        1 small onion, chopped
•        ½ small carrot, chopped
•        ½ celery stick, chopped
•        1 tsp tomato purée
•        pinch of sugar
•        350ml vegetable stock
column25:
1.	Put all the ingredients into the soup maker and press the ‘smooth soup’ function. Make sure you don’t fill the soup maker above the max fill line. 
2.	Once the cycle is complete, season well, and check the soup for sweetness. Add a little more sugar, salt or tomato puree for depth of colour, if you like.

column24:
•        2 tbsp olive oil
•        1 large onion, finely chopped
•        2 celery sticks, finely chopped
•        1 large carrot, finely chopped
•        30g smoked pancetta, diced (optional)
•        1/4 Savoy cabbage, shredded
•        1 garlic cloves, crushed
•        1 heaped tsp sweet smoked paprika
•        1 tsp finely chopped rosemary
•        1 chopped tomatoes
•        350 ml hot vegetable stock
•        ¼ cup chickpeas, drained and rinsed
•        shaved parmesan (or vegetarian alternative), to serve (optional)
•        crusty bread, to serve (optional)
column25:
1.	Heat the oil in a casserole pot over a low heat. 
2.	Add the onion, celery and carrot, along with a generous pinch of salt, and fry gently for 15 mins, or until the veg begins to soften. If you're using pancetta, add it to the pan, turn up the heat and fry for a few mins more until turning golden brown. 
3.	Tip in the cabbage and fry for 5 mins, then stir through the garlic, paprika and rosemary and cook for 1 min more.
4.	Tip the chopped tomatoes and stock into the pan. Bring to a simmer, then cook, uncovered, for 30 mins, adding the chickpeas for the final 10 mins. Season generously with salt and black pepper.
5.	Ladle the soup into six deep bowls. Serve with the shaved parmesan and crusty bread, if you like.

column24:
•        1 onion, chopped
•        1 large carrot, chopped
•        ½ tbsp thyme leaves, roughly chopped
•        350 ml chicken stock
•        ¼ cup  frozen peas
•        150g leftover roast chicken, shredded and skin removed
•        1½ tbsp Greek yogurt
•        ½ small garlic clove, crushed
•        squeeze lemon juice
column25:
1.	Heat the olive oil in a large saucepan set over medium heat. When the oil is shimmering, add the garlic, celery and onion. 
2.	Season with salt and pepper and cook, stirring, for 3 to 5 minutes, or until the onion is translucent and the vegetables begin to soften.
3.	Add the broth, thyme, oregano and parsley. Increase the heat to high and bring the soup to a boil, then reduce it to low and simmer for 5 minutes. 
4.	Add the chicken and carrot noodles. Cook for about 5 minutes then add the zucchini noodles and cook an additional 1 to 2 minutes until all of the noodles have softened. Serve immediately.

column24:
•        1 large onion, chopped
•        3 cloves garlic, minced
•        1 tablespoon butter
•        1 pound boneless skinless chicken breast
•        8 cups low-sodium chicken broth
•        3 tablespoons dry sherry
•        2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
•        1 teaspoon cornstarch
•        1/2 teaspoons smoked paprika
•        1/4 teaspoon crushed red pepper
•        4 ounces fat-free cream cheese, cut into cubes
•        3 cups small fresh broccoli florets
•        Salt and pepper
•        Possible garnishes: Low fat shredded cheese, chopped scallions, fresh parsley
column25:
1.	Place the butter in a 4-quart soup pot and set over medium heat. Once the butter has melted, add the onions and garlic. Sauté for 3-4 minute, stirring to make sure the garlic doesn’t burn.
2.	Place the whole chicken breasts at the bottom of the pot. Add the broth, sherry, Dijon mustard, corn starch, smoked paprika, crushed red pepper, 1 teaspoon salt, and 1/2 teaspoon ground black pepper.
3.	Bring the broth to a boil. Lower the heat, cover, and simmer for 15-20 minutes to cook the chicken.
4.	Remove the chicken breast with tongs. Then add in the cream cheese. Whisk to melt the cream cheese into the broth. Then use two forks to shred the chicken.
5.	Add the broccoli florets and the shredded chicken to the soup. Stir well and turn off the heat. The small broccoli florets will cook quickly in the hot broth.
6.	Taste, then salt and pepper as needed. Serve warm.

column24:
•        2 tablespoons unsalted butter
•        1 large sweet onion, peeled and chopped
•        1 cup chopped celery
•        5-6 cloves garlic, peeled and minced
•        18 ounces sliced mushrooms, mixed varieties
•        1 teaspoon fresh chopped rosemary
•        1 teaspoon dried thyme
•        1/3 cup dry sherry
•        1 pound boneless chicken breast
•        8 cups chicken broth
•        2/3 cup heavy cream
•        1 tablespoon cornstarch (or arrowroot for ketogenic)
•        1/4 cup chopped parsley
•        Salt and pepper
column25:
1.        Add the butter to a large 6-8 quart soup pot and set over medium heat. Once melted add the onions, celery, and garlic. 
2.        Sauté for 2-3 minutes, then add in the mushrooms, rosemary, and thyme. Sauté until the mushrooms soften and cook down. 
3.        Deglaze the pot with dry sherry. Then add in the whole chicken breasts, chicken broth, 1 teaspoon salt, and 1/4 teaspoon black pepper. Bring to a boil. Then lower the heat and simmer for 15 minutes, or until the chicken breasts have cooked though.
4.        When the chicken is fully cooked, remove the breasts with tongs, and chop into bite-size pieces.
5.        Whisk the cornstarch into the heavy cream, making sure there are no clumps. Then whisk the heavy cream into the soup pot and allow it to simmer and thicken. Stir the chopped chicken back into the soup and add the parsley. Taste, then salt and pepper as needed.

column24:
•        2 tablespoons butter, or olive oil
•        1 large sweet onion, peeled and chopped
•        1 cup chopped celery
•        1 cup chopped carrots
•        5-6 cloves garlic, minced
•        1 pound boneless chicken breasts
•        2 teaspoons lemon zest
•        1 tablespoon Italian seasoning
•        8 cups chicken broth
•        1/2 cup heavy cream
•        1/4 cup cornstarch (2 tsp glucomannan powder for keto)
•        1 cup grated parmesan cheese
•        1 cup baby spinach, packed
•        1/4 cup chopped parsley
•        salt and pepper
column25:
1.	Place a large 6-8 quart saucepot over medium heat. Add the butter, onions, and celery. Sauté for 3 minutes. Then add in the carrots and garlic and sauté another 2 minutes to soften.
2.	Place whole raw chicken breasts in the pot. Add in the lemon zest, Italian seasoning, chicken broth, 1 teaspoon salt, and 1/4 teaspoon black pepper. Cover and bring to a boil. Lower the heat if needed and simmer for about 15 minutes (covered) to cook the chicken.
3.	Meanwhile, whisk the heavy cream and cornstarch (or glucomannan) together until very smooth.
4.	Once the chicken has cooked through, pull the chicken breasts out of the pot with tongs and set on a cutting board.
5.	Stir the heavy cream mixture and parmesan cheese into the soup base to thicken. Stir another minute, until the parmesan melts and blends smoothly into the soup base.
6.	Use two forks to shred the chicken breasts. Then stir the shredded chicken, spinach, and parsley in the soup. Taste, then salt and pepper as needed. Serve warm, with extra parmesan if desired!

column24:
•        2 tsp olive oil
•        1-1/2 cups scallions, chopped fine
•        2 cloves garlic, minced
•        1 medium tomato, diced
•        5 cups reduced-sodium chicken broth
•        2 cups shredded chicken breast, 12 oz
•        8 ounces from 2 small ripe Hass avocados, diced
•        1/3 cup chopped cilantro
•        4 lime wedges
•        kosher salt and fresh pepper, to taste
•        1/8 teaspoon cumin
•        pinch chipotle chile powder, optional
column25:
1.	Heat a large pot over medium heat.
2.	Add the oil, 1 cup of scallions and garlic. Sauté about 2 to 3 minutes until soft then add the tomatoes and sauté another minute, until soft.
3.	Add chicken stock, cumin and chile powder and bring to a boil. Simmer, covered on low for about 15 minutes.
4.	In four bowls, fill each with 1/2 cup chicken, 1/2 avocado, remainder of the scallions, and cilantro. Ladle 1 cup chicken broth over the chicken and serve with a lime wedge.

column2: Cream Of Broccoli And Coconut Soup
column3: क्रीम ऑफ ब्रोकली और कोकोनट सूप
column24:
•        2 tbsp virgin coconut oil (30 ml)
•        2 cloves of garlic, peeled and crushed
•        2 shallots (45 g/ 1.6 oz)
•        1 head broccoli, cut in florets (300 g/ 10.6 oz)
•        4 cups vegetable stock  (960 ml/ 32 fl oz)
•        1/3 tsp salt or to taste
•        1/4 tsp cracked black pepper
•        Optional: a handful of watercress
•        3/4 cup full-fat coconut milk (180 ml/ 6 fl oz)
•        2 tbsp coconut cream (30 g/ 1.1 oz)
column25:
1.        Place the stock in a saucepan and simmer on a medium heat for 20 minutes until the stock reduces to almost half its volume. Concentrating the stock like this is my top tip to making the tastiest soup!
2.        Meanwhile, peel and finely dice the onion and garlic. Add 1 tablespoon of coconut oil to a new saucepan and sweat the onion for 2 minutes on a medium heat. Add the garlic and cook for 1 further minute. Turn off the heat.
3.        Once the stock is reduced, chop the broccoli Add the raw broccoli and remove from the heat. Allow to stand for 10 minutes. Place back on the heat and add the coconut milk, onion and garlic mix, salt and pepper and heat through, takes 1 - 2 minutes.
4.        Place the soup in a high speed food blender like a Vitamix. Add the coconut cream, remaining 1 tablespoon of coconut oil and optional watercress. Blitz until smooth. Place back in a pan and heat through.
5.        To serve, place in your favourite bowls and top with coconut chips, seeds, coconut yoghurt.

column2: Fennel And Cream Of Celery Soup  With Chicken
column3: सौंफ और अजमोद क्रीम सूप चिकन के साथ
column24:
•        1/2 pound cauliflower
•        1/2 pound celery
•        1/2 pound fennel bulb
•        6 ounces onion
•        32 ounces unsalted chicken broth
•        1/3 cup dry sherry or dry white wine
•        4 tablespoons butter
•        2 cups heavy cream
•        1 pound rotisserie chicken
•        2 teaspoons salt
•        lots of black pepper
column25:
1.	Cut the cauliflower into chunks and place into a small pot. Cover the cauliflower with water and boil/simmer until completely tender.
2.	Meanwhile, chop the celery, fennel and onions into small pieces. Heat a soup pot over medium high heat and add the butter and vegetables and sherry. Turn the heat to medium, cover the pot and cook until the vegetables are completely tender. Add a little water as necessary and stir the vegetables periodically to prevent burning.
3.	While the vegetables are cooking, begin removing the meat from the rotisserie chicken and dice it.
4.	When the cauliflower is cooked, drain and it to a blender. Add half of the chicken broth and blend until it is pureed and smooth. Pour it back into the cooking pot until ready to add to the soup.
5.	When the celery is completely cooked, put it into the belnder and add enough chicken stock to puree it as smoothly as possible. Scrape it back into the soup pot and add the pureed cauliflower and the rest of the chicken stock. Stir.
6.	Add two cups of heavy cream and the salt. Add lots of pepper to taste. Heat gently as not to burn or curdle the cream.
7.	While the soup is gently heating, continue removing the meat from the rotisserie chicken and cutting it into cubes. When the soup is hot, add the chicken just long enough to heat-through and serve.

column24:
•        300 ml chicken broth
•        1 teaspoon ground ginger
•        1 tablespoon soy sauce
•        2 eggs, beaten
•        1/4 cup chopped green onions (about 2 green onions)
•        salt and pepper
column25:
1.        Add chicken broth, ground ginger and soy sauce to a saucepan; bring to a simmer.
2.        Slowly stream in beaten eggs while stirring the soup in one direction.
3.        Add green onions. Salt and pepper to taste.

column24:
•        1 Egg
•        ½ cup Almond Flour
•        1 ounce Parmesan Cheese finely grated
•        1 tablespoon Dried Parsley
•        1 Lemon zest only
•        ½ teaspoon Salt
•        ¼ teaspoon Pepper ground
•        4 fillets White Fish 150g/5.3oz pieces
•        Oil for frying
column25:
1.	Heat your deep fryer to 180C/355F.
2.	Crack the egg into a bowl and whisk well.
3.	In another bowl, add the almond flour, parmesan, parsley, lemon zest, salt, and pepper. Mix well.
4.	Dip the fish into the egg, then press into the breading. Repeat with the other pieces of fish. (For a thicker crust, dip the breaded fish into the egg and breading a second time).
5.	Gently add the fish to the hot oil. Cook for 4-7 minutes, until golden brown and cooked through.
6.	Drain off the excess oil.
7.	Serve with Keto Coleslaw, lemon wedges, and Keto Tartar Sauce.

column24:
•        500 gms Rohu Fish without bones
•        50 gms Onions finely chopped
•        1 tsp Ginger paste
•        2 green Cardamom small
•        1 tsp Garlic paste
•        ½ tsp Cinnamon powder
•        ½ tsp Cloves powder
•        1 tsp Black Pepper powder
•        1 tsp Turmeric / Haldi powder
•        1 tbsp Vinegar or Juice of 1 lime
•        10 tsp Coconut oil
•        100 ml Coconut Milk
•        Salt / Pink Salt to taste
•        A few curry leaves (optional)
•        2 slit Green Chillies (optional)
column25:
1.	Wash the fish and pat dry.
2.	Apply the turmeric, black pepper, salt and vinegar to the fish with your hands, and keep it aside for atleast 30 minutes.
3.	In a flat pan put half the coconut oil and heat it. Place the fish pieces on the pan and start frying.
4.	After three to four minutes turn their side.
5.	Keep frying on medium heat, till the fish gets a nice golden color on the outside. Switch off the heat and keep aside.
6.	In a thick bottom pan, now heat the rest of the coconut oil. Keep the spices ready.
7.	Add the cardamom, cinnamon and cloves fry for thirty seconds. Add the slit green chilies and curry leaves, if you have them.
8.	Next add the ginger and garlic paste, and fry till it looks cooked.
9.	Add the onions next and fry till they become dark pink.
10.	Once the masala looks well cooked, in about three to four minutes, add the coconut milk and raise the heat.
11.	Add The Coconut Milk
12.	The coconut milk needs to be thin, so dilute it with enough water if required.
13.	Once the coconut milk starts boiling, lower the heat and drop the fried fish in it.
14.	Cook covered for about three to five minutes, check the salt and switch off the heat.
15.	Allow the fish to sit in the milk and absorb the flavor of the coconut milk.

column24:
•        600 gms Cauliflower cut in florets
•        150 gms chopped Spring onions with the greens
•        60 gms chopped Red Onion
•        200 ml Amul fresh cream
•        6 cubes of grated Parmesan cheese
•        20 gms of homemade white Butter
•        6 hard-boiled Eggs
•        1 tsp Mustard Powder
•        350 gm Rohu fish ( locally called Malli) Any boneless fish with skin will do
•        1 tsp Black Pepper Powder
•        ¼tsp Nutmeg powder
•        50 ml or half a cup melted Ghee
•        2 Bay leaves
•        2 Cloves
•        ½ tsp Garam Masala
•        ½ Cup chopped Coriander for garnish
•        Salt to taste
column25:
1.	Start by boiling the eggs and then keeping them aside to cool off.
2.	Once they are cold peel them and cut them length wise. Make four pieces of one.
The Cauliflower Mash:
3.	Wash the cauliflower and cut it into small florets. Now put it in a pressure cooker and just lightly sprinkle some water on it.
4.	Add some salt and when the first whistle is halfway, switch off the heat.
5.	Once the steam is out, pick the pieces of cauliflower and put them in a food processor or a blender.
6.	Start blending and after a minute or so add the melted ghee. Add the salt, pepper, and garam masala and blend some more. Set this mash aside.
Poaching the fish:
7.	Cut the fish into two inch by inch pieces, wash it thoroughly and pat dry.
8.	Place the fish in a wok or a heavy bottom pan.
9.	Mix the Amul cream with a cup of water.
10.	Now pour it over the fish.
11.	When the fish is poaching add the bay leaves, cloves to the cream.
12.	Add the chopped red onion to the pan.
13.	Once the cream starts boiling lower the heat and let the fish cook for about ten minutes.
14.	When the fish is cooked, transfer it to the dish in which you intend to bake it. Just shift the fish not the cream.
15.	Ensure you pick a dish, which has enough space to add the eggs and the cauliflower mash.
The Cream Sauce-
16.	Keep cooking the cream on medium heat.
17.	Add the nutmeg and mustard powder to the sauce and cook some more.
18.	To the sauce add half of the grated cheese and keep stirring on medium heat.
19.	Once the cheese melts sauce thickens, remove from heat and pick the bay leaves and cloves.
Layering the fish pie-
20.	Start by placing the boiled eggs on the fish.
21.	Pour the cheese sauce over the eggs and fish.
22.	Sprinkle the chopped spring onions on the eggs.
23.	Now spread the cauliflower mash evenly in the dish.
24.	Now sprinkle the rest of the cheese on this mash.
25.	Melt the butter and sprinkle it on the cheese.
26.	Bake at 250 degrees Celsius for 45 minutes or until the top gets a nice golden crust.
27.	Before serving garnish with chopped coriander, or any fresh herb that you prefer.
28.	The pie stays fine in the fridge for five to seven days.

column24:
•        Finely Ground Pepper As per taste
•        Fresh Lemon Juice 1 tablespoon
•        Salt As per taste
•        Unsalted Butter 60 grams or 4 tablespoons
•        Oil 2 tablespoons
•        Pepper As per taste
•        Thin White Fish Fillets 2 (120 to 150 grams each)
•        Almond Flour 2 tablespoons
•        Finely Chopped Parsley (Optional) As per taste
•        Lemon Wedges As per taste
column25:
For lemon butter sauce:
1.	Take a small skillet or saucepan and place it over a medium heat setting. Put the butter in it.
2. Once the butter melts, keep stirring it frequently until it turns golden brown and gives out a nutty smell. This shall take about 3 minutes.
3. Remove butter from the stove and pour into a small bowl.
4. Add a pinch of salt and pepper along with a squeeze of lemon juice to the melted butter. Stir and let it cool for a few minutes. 5.Taste and add lemon/salt as per requirement and put it aside.
Procedure For Crispy Pan Fried Fish
5. Dry the fish using paper towels and sprinkle a little salt and pepper on it followed by sprinkling some flour. Use fingers to spread the flour thoroughly.
6. Put a non-stick skillet over high heat setting and heat some oil in it.Add fish to shimmering oil giving out light wisps of smoke.
7. Cook on one side for about 90 seconds, until it turns golden brown and crispy on the edges. Turn and cook on the other side.
8. Remove the fish from the skillet and place it in a plate.
9. Drizzle each fish with 1 tablespoon

column24:
•        1 kg King Fish, cut into neat fillets
•        4 tbsp Olive Oil
•        2 tsp Thyme, dried
•        2 tsp Rosemary, dried
•        1 tsp Paprika powder
•        Pink Salt
•        Table Salt
column25:
1.	Wash the fish and cut it into pieces. Make diagonal slits on the skin side.
2.	Now measure out the dry spices on a plate. Take out the dried Thyme, Rosemary, Salt, Pepper and Paprika powder. Mix them well with your hands.
3.	Now place the washed and dried fish in the dish in which you want to marinade the fish. Apply the dried spices marinade mix to the fish. Measure out the oil and apply it to the fish too, till the time the fish is coated well with the spice mix.
4.	Allow the fish to marinade for at least 30 minutes to an hour.
5.	Preheat the oven to 350 degrees Celsius and place the fish on a grilling rack.
6.	Grill the fish for 15 mins at 350 degrees Celsius, along with the high power function of the micro. Remember to turn the fish after 8 minutes.
7.	After the remaining eight to ten minutes the fish will be ready to be served. Add a small portion of any veggies you want, like broccoli or capsicum and serve it hot.

column24:
•        500 gms King Fish cut in fingers
•        1/2 cup Almond Flour
•        1 tbsp Red Chilli (to taste)
•        1 tsp Carom Seeds
•        1 tsp Ginger paste
•        1 tsp Garlic Paste
•        1 tbsp Lemon Juice
•        1 egg
•        1 tsp Chaat Masala, optional
•        10 tbsp Olive Oil to deep fry
•        2 Lemon wedges
•        Salt to taste
column25:
1.	Place the fish fingers in a bowl.
2.	Add the red chili powder, carom seeds, ginger paste, lemon juice, garlic paste, salt and gram flour to the fish. Mix well. Keep it aside for half an hour or so.
3.	Heat the oil sufficiently. Break an egg and beat it in a separate bowl. Now pick one finger dip it in the egg and drop it in the hot oil.
4.	Take it out of the oil when it gets a golden outer crust.
5.	Place them on a kitchen sheet. If you are going to eat them later, you can deep fry them again before serving.
6.	Before serving sprinkle chaat masala and place lemon wedges beside it.

column24:
•        275 gm King Fish
•        3 tsp Ghee
•        0.50 tsp Cumin seed
•        2 tsp Lime juice
•        15 gms Garlic Cloves of Garlic paste
•        2 dried Red Chillies
•        ½ tsp Turmeric Powder
•        ½ tsp whole Fennel seeds
•        ½ tsp whole Coriander seeds
•        100 gm Homemade Greek Yogurt
•        White Salt according to taste
•        Pink Salt according to taste
column25:
1.	Dry roast the cumin seeds, coriander seeds and fennel seeds, and grind to a powder.
2.	Grind garlic, red chilly to a paste with a pinch of salt.
3.	Combine the ground spices and garlic and red chilly paste, with turmeric powder, salt, lime juice, hung curd and ghee. Mix well until a fine paste is formed. Add in chopped coriander to the marinade and mix some more.
4.	Apply the marinade to the fillets of fish till they are well coated with the paste. Do it with your hands and in the baking dish in which you intend to bake it. Remember to apply some paste to the bottom of the dish.
5.	Cover the fish properly with the marinade and then cover the dish with a kitchen foil and keep it aside for three to four hours.
6.	Pre-heat the oven and place the baking dish in the oven and bake at 180 degrees for 25 minutes.
7.	After twenty-five minutes the fish should be ready. Remove the foil and serve it hot.

column24:
•        500 gm cauliflower rice finely shredded cauliflower
•        100 gm grams hung full-fat yogurt
•        20 gm 2 butter pieces (melted)
•        2 tbsp ghee
•        2 tbsp fresh coriander and mint paste
•        1 kg 1 chicken (marinated and cut into small pieces)
•        30 gm 1 onion (shredded or in paste form and fried)
•        1 tbsp fresh mint leaves
•        1 tbsp ginger-garlic paste
•        ½ tbsp coriander powder
•        ½ tbsp cumin powder
•        ½ tbsp garam masala
•        ½ tbsp red chili powder
•        ½ tbsp turmeric
•        ½ tsp lime juice
•        A few drops of kewra optional
•        A few drops of shahi biryani essence optional
•        A pinch of saffron (soaked in warm water)
•        Salt to taste
column25:
1.	Cut the marinated chicken into smaller pieces.
2.	Take a deep skillet – or saucepan – and place over a low heat setting. Pour 1 tablespoon ghee in it and let it melt.
3.	Add the chicken to the saucepan and then pour over the cauliflower rice.
4.	Top the chicken-cauliflower-rice mixture with coriander, kewra, mint leaves, onions, saffron, and shahi biryani essence.
5.	Cook the non-veg biryani until the chicken pieces are cooked through. This should take about 15 to 20 minutes, on medium heat. Try cooking without a lid, or the rice will become very soggy.
6.	Serve with butter and ghee.

column24:
Cook the ground meat
•        500 gm Grounded Chicken Meat
•        1 tsp Cumin powder
•        1 tsp    Coriander powder
•        1 tsp Red Chilli Powder according to taste
•        1 tsp Chat masala powder
•        ½ tsp Garam Masala powder
•        1 tsp Onion powder
•        ½ tsp Salt
•        2 tsp Ginger and Garlic paste
Stage 2: Make the Mixture of Kebab
•        50 gm Almond flour
•        50 gm  Coconut flour
•        Egg whites of 2 Eggs
•        2 tsp of Sliced Coriander leaves
•        6 tsp Ghee for frying
column25:
1.	Mix all of the ingredients, with a light hand and make a soft dough.
2.	Giving the dough time to rest after kneading. Now roll them in small balls and flatten them in your palm.
3.	On a non-stick pan heat the ghee on medium heat.
4.	Fry the kebabs until golden on all sides.
5.	Serve hot with fresh mint chutney.

column24:
•        1 kg Boneless Chicken
•        1st MARINADE
•        Juice of 2 limes
•        1 tsp Salt
•        ½ tsp Red Chilly Powder
•        2nd MARINADE
•        125 gm Greek Yogurt
•        100 gm Full Fat Cream
•        2 tsp Ginger paste
•        2 tsp Garlic paste
•        1 tsp Pink Salt
•        ½ tsp Red Chilly powder Optional and according to taste
•        20 gm Garam Masala
•        Fresh Coriander chopped
•        2 to 3 Green Chillies Optional
•        5 Ghee for basting
•        Chaat Masala Optional
•        A few drops of red food color optional
column25:
1.        Wash the chicken pieces and pat them dry.
2.        Marinate the chicken in the 1st marinade for atleast half an hour.
3.        In another bowl mix the hung curd or  greek yogurt, cream, ginger and garlic paste, black salt, garam masala, red chilly powder and normal salt.
4.        Now add the chicken to the 2nd marinade, mix well with your hands. Cover the bowl and keep in the refrigerator for four to six hours.
5.        When you are ready to eat pre-heat your oven or grill or tandoor.
6.        Place the chicken pieces on a skewer or grill plate.
7.        Baste them with melted ghee and grill for 20 minutes at 250 degrees Celsius or for 12 to 14 minutes at 350 degrees Celsius.
8.        Turn the chicken once atleast and baste it with ghee one more time.
9.        Sprinkle some chaat masala on it and serve hot.

column24:
•        250  gm Chicken Breast with bone
•        30 gm Butter
•        1/4 cup Fresh Garlic leaves chopped
•        150 ml  Butter Milk or Lassi or Chaach
•        Salt according to taste
•        ½ tsp  Black Pepper powder
1        tbsp  Freshly Chopped Coriander
2        Green Chilies finely chopped optional
•        1/4 tsp  Pink Salt
column25:
1.	Marinate the chicken in buttermilk and all the other ingredients overnight, or for at least three to four hours. 
2.	Cook the chicken on medium heat until thoroughly cooked and the buttermilk dries up.
3.	Now add the butter raise the heat ,and sear the chicken until it gets a nice golden colour on the outside.
4.	Switch off the heat, cover it and let it rest for five to seven minutes.
5.	Slice the chicken and carry it to work. Enjoy!

column24:
•        800 gms broiler chicken
•        1 onion chopped
•        1 tbsp chopped garlic ginger
•        2 green chilies chopped optional
•        3 tbsp olive oil
•        Grind together for the rub
•        2 tsp coriander seeds
•        1 tsp cumin seeds/jeera
•        1 tsp mustard seeds/ sarson
•        2 red chilies
•        6 peppercorns
•        1 clove
•        4 green cardamom
•        half stick cinnamon
•        2 tbsp vinegar
•        ¼ cup tamarind water
•        1 cup water/ salt/ chilly powder to taste
•        2 drops of stevia
column25:
1.        Heat oil and fry the garlic until golden.
2.        Add onions fry until tender.
3.        Add the chicken, grated ginger, green chillies, fry until golden.
4.        Now add the ground masala paste and stir fry for 5 to 7 minutes.
5.        Add the tamarind, water, stevia, salt and chilly powder.
6.        Cook on slow heat till you get a gravy and chicken is tender.
7.        Garnish with fresh coriander.

column24:
•        225 gm Chicken Breast Boneless
•        ½  tbsp Black Peppercorns Whole
•        1/1 tbsp Bay Leaf/Bay Leaf Powder 
•        1 Clove Garlic
•        3/4th tbsp Soy Sauce
•        1 tbsp Olive Oil 
•        1 Tbs Ghee
•        ½ Tbs Pink Salt
column25:
1.        Wash the chicken and cut it into small pieces.
2.        In a bowl add the chicken pieces, vinegar, soy sauce, bay leaf, garlic, olive oil and peppercorns.
3.        Mix well and add enough water, which submerges the chicken completely.
4.        Cover and let it marinate for at least four to 14 hours.
5.        Next day, drop the chicken, with the marinade in a heavy bottom pan and bring it to a boil.
6.        Once it starts boiling, cover the pan, lower the heat and let it cook for five to seven minutes. My chicken was fully done in this time.
7.        Now pick out the chicken pieces and reduce the sauce, till half the quantity is left. Switch off the heat and let it cool down.
8.        In a wok add the ghee and heat it.
9.        Drop the chicken pieces in it ,and fry till they turn golden in colour.
10.        Lower the heat and strain the gravy over this chicken. Cook for just another minute and switch off the heat.

column24:
•        200  gm florets of Broccoli Blanched or Raw
•        50  ml Amul Whipping Cream
•        100 ml Dabur Coconut milk
•        10 gm Amul Butter
•        300 gm Chicken Breast or Broiler
•        1 Slice of Amul Cheese
•        2 Cubes of Amul Processed Cheese
•        ½ tsp  Black Pepper Powder
•        1/4 tsp  Paprika Powder  Optional
•        White and Pink salt according to taste
column25:
1.        Start by washing the chicken and cutting it into small pieces. Wash the broccoli and cut its florets too. Place the chicken in the dish in which you are going to bake it and sprinkle it with salt and pepper.
2.        Now in a thick bottomed pan or wok put the coconut milk and let it come to a boil. If you think it is too thick, dilute it with a little water.
3.        Drop the butter in the milk and let the sauce to continue to boil on medium heat.
4.        Add the pepper, salt, paprika powder.
5.        Next add the grated cheese cubes and keep stirring on medium heat.
6.        Drop in the broccoli, I had some blanched lying in the fridge so i am using that.
7.        Cook the sauce with the broccoli for another five to eight minutes. Now drop in the heavy cream and lower the heat.
8.        Cook for another five minutes till the sauce reduces (Simmer On Low Heat). Switch off the heat.
9.        Pour this sauce along with the brocolli over the chicken which is lying in the bakig dish.
10.        Now break a cheese slice and place it on the dish.
11.        Bake at 350 degrees Celcius for 60 mins or untill the bake looks nice and creamy and chicken well done. Serve hot.

column24:
•        100 gm Chopped Spinach
•        400  gm Chicken wings
•        ½ tbsp Ginger Paste 
•        1.5 tbsp Olive Oil 
•        50  gm Greek Yogurt/Hung Curd
•        ½  tbsp Pink Salt 
•        2tbsp Red Chilly powder
•        1 tbsp Turmeric powder 
•        Salt According to Taste
column25:
1.	Wash the chicken and add the Greek Yogurt to it.
2.	Next wash and chop the spinach roughly.
3.	Add spinach, salt, garlic paste, ginger paste, dry masalas and mix well with your hands. Add the oil and mix more.
4.	When you are ready to cook, place it in a heavy bottomed pan, and cook on low heat covered for about ten minutes.
5.	Switch off the heat, let the chicken rest for five to ten minutes. Then pack it and take it to work.

column24:
•        Spinach 1 cup
•        Onion 1 medium
•        Mozarella cheese ½  cup
•        Red chilies powder ½ tsp
•        Salt, to taste
•        Coconut flour 2 tbsp
•        Beaten egg 1
•        Ghee 2-3 tsp
column25:
1.	Mix all the ingredients in a big bowl together
2.	Grease the appe stand
3.	Fill in the stand with the batter
4.	Change the side of each bite when it’s cooked
5.	In around a total of 20 minutes they will be ready
6.	Serve hot with mint or coconut chutney

column24:
•        Curd 100g
•        Onions 20g 
•        Curry leaves, a few
•        Cumin seeds ½ tsp 
•        Mustard seeds ½ tsp
•        Oil 1 tsp
•        Salt, to taste
•        Water 1 cup 
•        Dry Red chilies 1
•        Green chilies paste- ½ tsp
•        Coriander leaves- a few
column25:
1.	Saute the oil in a pan, add dry red chillies, cumin seeds, mustard seeds, and curry leaves. 
2.	Add chopped onions and saute for a while
3.	Then add all salt, turmeric powder and saute for a while
4.	Then add curd and cook for a while on low heat to prevent curdling and add water after a while.
5.	Add chilli paste, curry leaves and cook for around 15-20 minutes.
6.	Serve hot.

column24:
•        250 gms Gooseberry
•        ¼ tsp Turmeric Powder
•        1 tbsp Red Chili Powder
•        1 tbsp Salt
•        1 pinch Asafoetida (Asafetida / Hing) a Generous Pinch
•        ¼ tsp Fenugreek Powder
•        4 tbsp Sesame oil
FOR TEMPERING
•        2 tbsp Sesame oil
•        1 tsp Mustard Seeds
column25:
1.	Wash thoroughly gooseberry and pat dry them and keep it ready. 
2.	Heat 2 tablespoon of Sesame oil and add the gooseberries and saute in oil for couple of minutes. 
3.	Then, close the pan with a lid and allow the gooseberry to cook in low flame till it is soft.
4.	It usually takes around 10 minutes for the gooseberries to cook completely and become soft. 
5.	We can also boil the gooseberries in hot water till it is soft instead of sauteing in the oil. 
6.	We prefer sauteing process as she believes sauteing process helps the pickle to stay fresh and have longer shelf life.
7.	Now that the gooseberries are cooked, you can use a spoon or fork to split the gooseberry and discard the seeds.
8.	Now sauteed de-seeded gooseberries ready!
9.	Take the de-seeded Gooseberries in a mixer jar and grind it to a coarse paste. 
10.	I would recommend to use the Pulse mode for grinding and that way the pickle will not be so smooth. Its completely ok to have some chunks.
11.	Heat rest of oil and add mustard seeds and allow it to sputter. Then, add the asafoetida and turmeric powder.
12.	To the pan, then add the ground Gooseberry paste. Then, add the salt and red chilli powder and mix everything well. Adjust the salt and chili powder as per the sourness of the gooseberry.
13.	Cook the thokku for 5 mins in low flame. We can add more oil if the thokku is very dry. 
14.	Then finally add fenugreek powder and mix well and switch off the flame.
15.	Store the delicious Nellikai Thokku (Gooseberry pickle) in an air-tight container. Always use dry spoon to serve. Refrigerate to save its freshness and to increase the shelf life.

column24:
•        2 eggs, at room temperature
•        1/3 cup coconut milk or almond milk (any milk will work)
•        1 tablespoon olive oil, melted coconut oil, or homemade butter
•        Stevia, as per taste (optional)
•        1 teaspoon vanilla extract
•        1/4 teaspoon almond extract (optional, but recommended for yummy flavor!)
•        1 ¼ cup packed fine blanched almond flour (do not use almond meal)
•        ¼ teaspoon baking soda (or sub 1 teaspoon baking powder)
•        1/4 teaspoon salt
•        Butter, olive oil, or coconut oil, for greasing the pan
•        Optional add-ins:
•        blueberries, fresh or frozen
•        mini dairy-free chocolate chips
column25:
1.	In large bowl, whisk together the eggs, milk, oil, pure maple syrup, vanilla and almond extract together until smooth and well combined. Next, add in almond flour, baking soda and a pinch of salt; stir with spoon until well combined.
2.	Lightly coat a large nonstick skillet with butter, olive oil or coconut oil and place over medium heat. Once oil or butter is hot, drop about 1/4 cup of batter onto the skillet. It's important to cook until bubbles appear on top and the edges are well cooked.
3.	Flip cakes and cook until golden brown on underside, 2 minutes. If you find that the pancakes are browning too quickly then you need to lower your skillet heat a bit. I normally start on medium or medium low, then decrease to lower heat later so that my pancakes don't burn.
4.	Wipe skillet clean and repeat with more butter/oil and remaining batter. Makes 3 servings, 2 pancakes each (6 pancakes total).

column24:
•        1 cup Button Mushroom
•        ½ cup bell pepper
•        ½ cup spring onion
•        1 green chili
•        1 tbsp Garlic
•        1-2 tsp Olive oil
•        1 tbsp Soya sauce
•        1 tbsp Chilli Paste
•        1 tbsp tomato paste
•        ½ tsp black pepper
•        2-3 tbsp Water
•        Salt, to taste
column25:
1.	Rinse mushrooms well under running water. Slice or halve or quarter them
2.	Heat a wide skillet with oil on high flame
3.	Add garlic and saute for 30-60 seconds until aromatic. Do not brown it
4.	Next add mushrooms and slit green chilli. Saute for 2 mins
5.	Add bell peppers and half of the spring onions, toss and fry till capsicum are almost cooked yet crunchy
6.	Make sure mushrooms are cooked yet not mushy
7.	Add the sauces to the skillet all over and pour 2-3 tbsp of water. Quickly stir well. The water immediately blends with the sauce and evaporates.
8.	Next sprinkle black pepper. Toss and fry for another min or until the sauce thickens
9.	Add salt as per taste and add more sauces to suit your taste.
10.	Serve chilli mushroom with zoodles or cauliflower rice.

column24:
•        4 cups blanched French beans, cut diagonally
•        2tsp finely chopped garlic
•        1 tbsp Oil
•        Salt, to taste
•        2 tsp soy sauce
•        2 tbsp roasted sesame seeds
column25:
1.	Heat oil in broad non stick pan, add garlic and saute on medium flame for few seconds.
2.	Add French beans and salt, mix well and cook on medium flame for 1 minute, while stirring occasionally
3.	Add soy sauce, mix well and cook on medium flame while stirring continuously
4.	Serve immediately topped with sesame seeds

column24:
•        Medium Eggplants 2
•        Eggs 3
•        Sliced Scallions 3 Tbsp
•        Chili Flakes 1/2 Tsp
•        Chicken Seasoning  1 Tsp
•        Carrot, Zucchini, Bell Peppers Chopped, To Taste
•        Shredded Cheese
column25:
1.	Slice eggplants in half lengthwise, scoop all the flesh, trying to not poke through the skin.
2.	Season eggplant halves with salt, brush with olive oil and bake for 190°C/375°F for 15 minutes.
3.	Whisk eggs with scallions, salt, pepper, chili flakes and chicken seasoning.
4.	Add vegetables of your choice.
5.	Pour the egg mixture into the boats (if it spills out a little – add rolled up foil underneath to lift the eggplant up).
6.	Top with cheese and bake for 20-25 minutes more.

column3: अंडे के साथ ककड़ी की नावें
column24:
•        2 small cucumbers garden cucumber variety
•        4 hard-boiled eggs
•        1 stick celery
•        2 tablespoons dill chopped
•        1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
•        ¼ cup Hung Curd or Greek Yogurt
•        ½ teaspoon salt
•        ½ teaspoon black pepper
column25:
1.	Cut the cucumbers in half lengthwise.  Scoop out the seeds with a small spoon.  Set them aside.
2.	Peel the eggs and chop into small pieces. Place in a small bowl and mash lightly with a fork.
3.	Chop the celery into small pieces and place in the bowl with the dill, mustard, hung curd, salt and black pepper.
4.	Mix to combine the ingredients.
5.	Spoon the egg mixture into the cucumber boats and garnish with a sprig of dill.

column24:
•        7 mini cucumbers
•        12 oz cream cheese room temp
•        1 Tablespoon fresh dill chopped
•        1 teaspoon fresh flat-leaf parsley chopped
•        1/8 teaspoon garlic powder
•        salt and pepper to taste
column25:
1.	Wash cucumbers and slice in half length wise. Using a small melon baller, scoop out the seeds and discard. Place cucumbers cut side down on paper towels for about an hour to let the excess water run out.
2.	Place the cream cheese and remaining ingredients in a microwave safe bowl and mix to combine. Microwave for 10 seconds, just to loosen up the cheese slightly. If piping, place in a piping bag with a large star tip and pipe cream cheese into cucumbers.
3.	If you are just filling the cucumber with the cheese with a knife, then you do not need to microwave the cheese at all. Serve and enjoy!

column24:
•        150 ml Almond Milk Unsweetened
•        20 ml Fresh Cream
•        125 Grams Almond Flour
•        30 Grams Ghee
•        1/4 tsp Cardamom Powder
•        Stevia to taste
•        10 Grams Roasted Almonds as garnish
column25:
1.	Add almond flour in a cooking pot, let it roast on a low flame till you see it turning slightly brown.
2.	Add ghee to it. Mix it well let it cook for a while.
3.	Add almond milk in two parts.
4.	Let it cook well, when it slightly starts binding, add fresh cream and cardamom. Mix it well, cook for 2 minutes more. Switch off the gas and mix stevia.
5.	Garnish it with roughly chopped almonds

column24:
•        2 cups broccoli
•        ¼ cup fresh dill chopped
•        ½ cup greek yogurt or hung curd
•        salt and pepper to taste
•        1 tablespoon lemon juice
•        2 tablespoons pumpkin seeds optional
column25:
1.	In a large covered pot, cook broccoli in a small amount of boiling water for about 2 minutes or until crisp-tender. Drain and rinse with cold water. Then transfer it to a paper towel-lined bowl to fully dry.
2.	Meanwhile, In a large bowl, whisk to combine greek yogurt, lemon juice or vinegar, salt, pepper, and dill leaves. Set aside.
3.	Then add the cooked broccoli, pumpkin seeds into the dressing and toss well until evenly coated.
4.	Refrigerate this salad for at least 1 hour so that broccoli gets a chance to soak in some of the dressing and adds more flavor to the salad!

column24:
•        1 head green cabbage (you won't use it all!), carefully cored with a knife
•        1 paneer patty with amaranth coating
•        1 slice onion
•        2 slices tomato
•        Optional toppings: tomato dip, Cream cheese
•        Coconut flour: 2 tsp
column25:
1.	Place the head of cabbage in a large microwave-safe bowl and microwave for about 4 minutes, until the outer leaves begin to loosen.
2.	Once cool enough to handle, remove the cabbage from the bowl. Gently remove 2 whole outer leaves from the cabbage, and place them back in the bowl. (Reserve the rest of the cabbage for another use.)
3.	Add 2 tbsp. of water to the bowl with the cabbage leaves. Cover and microwave for about 2 minutes, until leaves are very soft.
4.	Meanwhile, spray a skillet with nonstick spray and bring to medium heat on the stove.
5.	Take a rectangular paneer slice, coat it in coconut flour paste. 
6.	Grill the patty on the non-stick tawa
7.	Add the burger patty and onion slice and cook for about 4 minutes per side, until cooked through.
8.	Top one cabbage leaf with the burger patty, followed by a tomato slice, the onion, and the remaining tomato slice. If you like, top with tomato dip or cream cheese and mustard. Gently top with the other leaf. Chew!

column24:
•        Zucchini (no need to peel!)
•        Runny tahini
•        A large lemon, zested and juiced
•        Garlic
•        Salt
column25:
1.        Place chopped zucchini, tahini, lemon zest and juice, garlic and salt in a high speed blender and blend on the highest speed until completely smooth and creamy.  Do not over-blend if you plan to enjoy right away or it will get warm.  Add 1 tablespoon of water if your blender is having trouble getting started.
2.        Taste and adjust seasonings/flavors if desired.  Add more water to thin but not too much or it will get runny.  
3.        Use a mini spatula to transfer to a bowl and enjoy immediately with raw veggies, or with falafel.  
4.        Store leftovers in an airtight container in the refrigerator for up to five days

column24:
•        2 English cucumbers, shaved into long strips (24 strips)
•        1 green bell pepper, cut into thin strips about 3” tall
•        1 red bell pepper, cut into thin strips about 3” tall
•        1 carrot, cut into sticks about 3” tall
•        ¾ cup Radish Mini sticks
•        24 cilantro springs
•        ¼ cup low-fat cream cheese
•        ¼ cup goat cheese
•        1 teaspoon vinegar
•        ⅛ teaspoon salt
•        pepper to taste
column25:
1.	Prepare all vegetables and set aside in individual bowls. Shave long strips of English cucumber with a vegetable peeler.
2.	Add cream cheese, goat cheese, vinegar, salt, and pepper to a small bowl and stir until smooth and creamy.
3.	Lay one cucumber strip on a flat surface. Add 1 tablespoon of cheese filling to one end of the strip, spreading it to cover about 2 inches. Add a few of each vegetable and a sprig of cilantro.
4.	Starting at the filling end, roll the vegetables up in the cucumber strip tightly. Chill before serving.

column24:
•        2 eggs
•        1/4 cup of water
•        Salt and pepper to taste
•        1/4 cup chopped spring onions
•        1/2 cup of sliced button mushrooms
•        1/2 cup of fresh spinach leaves
•        1/2 cup of freshly torn lettuce leaves
•        Salad of your choice, to accompany omelet wrap
•        Oil 1/2tsp
column25:
1.        In a small bowl, beat the eggs with the 1/2 cup of water
2.        Add in salt and pepper and beat some more
3.        Heat a bit of oil in a large skillet over medium-low heat
4.        Pour half the beaten egg mixture into the skillet, making sure the entire surface is covered
5.        Sprinkle half the amount of spring onion evenly on the top of the omelet and let it cook gently before flipping over to the other side (about 2 – 3 minutes). Once the other side is cooked, remove omelet from skillet and set aside.
6.        Repeat with the rest of the egg mixture and spring onions
7.        Place omelets (spring onion side facing down) on a large plate
8.        Dividen sliced mushrooms, spinach and lettuce evenly between both omelet and roll the omelets like you would roll a burrito
9.        Serve omelet wraps with salad of your choice

column24:
•        500 grams Bhindi (Lady Finger/Okra), cut into 1-inch pieces
•        1 Onion, big, sliced
•        1 Green Chilli, slit
•        1 cup Coconut milk, thick
•        2 teaspoons Ginger, grated
•        1 teaspoon Mustard seeds (Rai/ Kadugu)
•        1 sprig Curry leaves
•        1 tablespoon Coconut Oil
•        Salt, to taste
column25:
1.	To begin, first wash, dry and cut the okras into 1 inch long pieces and keep aside.
2.	Heat coconut oil in a pan on medium heat, add the mustard seeds and let it splutter.
3.	Add the curry leaves and let it splutter.
4.	Add the sliced onions and saute until it turns translucent.
5.	Add the grated ginger, slit green chilli and saute for a minute.
6.	Add the cut okras and mix well.
7.	Season with salt and saute for around 10 minutes till its half cooked.
8.	Close with the lid and let the okras cook well.
9.	Once its cooked, add the coconut milk and a cup of water and bring it to a rolling boil.
10.	Switch off the flame and serve the Okra or Vendakka Stew.

column24:
• 2 big handfuls of baby spinach
• 1 medium green apple, cut into large chunks
• 3 to 4-inch piece cucumber preferably peeled, cut into chunks
• 1 cup unsweetened almond milk
• 1 tablespoon hemp seeds or chia seeds
• 2 teaspoons another liquid sweetener
• 1 tablespoon lemon juice
column25:
1. Combine all the ingredients in a blender.
2. Process until completely smooth.
3. Divide between 2 or 3 glasses and serve at once.

column24:
• 2 to 3 medium fresh tomatoes
• 1/2 medium red onion
• 1 jalapeño pepper, stems, ribs, and seeds removed (less or more to taste)
• Juice of 1 lime
• 1/2 cup chopped cilantro
• Salt and pepper to taste
• 1 pinch dried oregano (crumble in your fingers before adding), or more to taste
• 1 pinch ground cumin, or more to taste
column25:
1. Roughly chop the tomatoes, chili peppers, and onions.
2. Place all of the ingredients in the bowl of a food processor fitted with the blade. Pulse only a few times, just enough to finely dice the ingredients and not enough to purée. If you don't have a food processor, you can finely dice by hand.
3. Place in a serving bowl. Add salt and pepper to taste. If the chilis make the salsa too hot, add some more chopped tomato. If it's not hot enough, carefully add a few of the seeds from the chilis, or add a little more ground cumin.
4. If you like, let the salsa sit for an hour (room temperature or chilled) for the flavors to combine.
5. Serve with chips, tortillas, tacos, burritos, tostadas, quesadillas, or pinto or black beans. The salsa will keep refrigerated for up to 5 days.

column24:
•        30ml olive oil
•        2 teaspoons minced garlic or 8 to 10 small to medium-sized garlic or 5 grams
•        2 cups crushed tomatoes or 5 to 6 medium to large tomatoes or 500 grams
•        ¼ cup chopped fresh basil or 1 to 2 tablespoons dried basil
•        2 teaspoons dried oregano or 2 tablespoons chopped fresh oregano
•        salt as required
•        ½ teaspoon crushed black pepper or add as required
column25:
1.	Rinse and then chop the tomatoes.
2.	Crush the tomatoes in a blender.
3.	You can even make a smooth puree of the tomatoes.
4.	Heat olive oil in a pan.
5.	Then add the minced garlic and sauté for 4 to 5 seconds on a low heat.
6.	Add the crushed tomatoes and sauté for 4 to 5 mins on a low to medium-low heat.
7.	Add the chopped basil, dried oregano, salt and pepper.
8.	Cover and cook for 25 minutes on low heat till the sauce has thickened and the tomatoes are cooked.
9.	When tomatoes are cooked you will some oil specks on top or on the sides. But cook till the sauce thickens. 
10.	Check the seasonings add more salt or pepper if required.
11.	Remove from pan and let sauce cool.
12.	When the sauce has cooled, you can use it right away as a pizza topping or a dip.
13.	Otherwise, store the pizza sauce covered or sealed in a bowl or a small to medium jar in the refrigerator. You can even freeze the sauce for a couple of months.

column24:
•        2 kiwis, peeled and quartered
•        1/2 medium avocado
•        1 cup coconut water
•        2 tablespoons Coconut milk
•        1 lemon, juiced (more to taste)
•        1 tsp Melon seeds
•        4 to 5 ice cubes
column25:
1.	Place all ingredients in a blender and blend on high until smooth and creamy, about one minute. 
2.	Serve over ice.

column24:
•        1 ½ cup black sesame seeds
•        2 cups almonds raw
•        2-3 fresh dates
•        3 cups water
column25:
1.        Place the raw almonds in a medium-sized bowl and fill the bowl with enough water to cover the almonds. Place the black sesame seeds in a small-bowl and also cover them with water. Cover both bowls and leave out at room temperature for at least 8 hours or overnight to soak.
2.        Drain the almonds and black sesame seeds and rinse them under cool water. Place them into a blender. Add 3 cups of cool water and overnight soaked dates.
3.        Blend the mixture on high for 1-2 minutes, or until the mixture is completely smooth and there are no chucks of seeds or almonds left.
4.        Place 2 layers of cheesecloth over a large bowl (preferably with a spout) and pour the nut milk mixture into it. Fold the edges into the center and raise the entire cheesecloth out of the bowl to drain the nut milk. Squeeze the bag until all of the milk is drained out.
5.        Put aside the pulp mixture and cheesecloth. (You can use the pulp mixture in cookies or in your chapati dough).
6.        Pour the nut milk into a pitcher and place in the fridge. You can enjoy this nut milk either cold or warmed.

column24:
•        1 cup mulberries
•        ¼-½ cup almond milk 
•        ½ cup homemade full fat Unsweetened Coconut Milk or Organic Coconut Cream 
•        1 pinch of sea salt
•        ½ teaspoon pure vanilla extract
•        ¾ cup crushed ice
•        1tsp basil seeds (soaked for 3 hours
column25:
1. Combine all ingredients, except for the ice and ¼ cup almond milk, in a blender, and blend until well-combined, add extra almond milk if needed for thinning.
2.Turn off blender to scrape the sides as needed. Add ice and blend until smooth.
3. Pour into your favorite glass and enjoy!

column24:
•        1 cup unsweetened shredded coconut
•        2 tbsp water and stevia to taste
•        2 tbsp virgin coconut oil
•        1/4 tsp pure vanilla extract
•        1/8 tsp salt
•        4 paan leaves, also known as betel leaves
•        5 teaspoons crushed rose petals
•        1/2 cup coconut cream
column25:
1.        Blend coconut cream and paan leaves in blender or food processor (not by hand or they’ll fall apart). 
2.        Heat ghee in a pan on medium heat. Once ghee is hot, add desiccated coconut and roast for 2-3 minutes on medium-low heat.
3.        Add the coconut cream- paan mixture and stir to combine. You may add few drops of green food color at this point.
4.        Cook for another 2 minutes on low heat, mixture will thicken. Remove from heat and let the mixture cool down a bit.
5.        Grease your hands with little ghee, take small portion from the coconut mixture, flatten it and add 1/2-1 teaspoon of crushed rose petals in the center.
6.        Bring the edges together and roll to form a ladoo.
7.        Roll the prepared ladoo in desiccated coconut. Repeat the same process with the remaining ladoos.
8.        Refrigerate or freeze leftovers.

column24:
•        2 tablespoons coconut oil (or ghee)
•        2 cups lauki (bottle gourd) peeled and shredded
•        ½ cup unsweetened almond milk
•        10 serves stevia (adjust as per your taste)
•        ¼ cup almond flour 
•        ⅛ teaspoons cardamom powder
•        2-3 tablespoons sliced almonds or pistachios
column25:
1.	Peel the skin, remove the seeds if any and grate lauki using medium sized blade.
2.	In a heavy bottom pan add ghee into the pot, once hot add shredded lauki/bottle gourd and saute them in the ghee for about 2-3 minutes.
3.	Next add milk. Give a quick stir.
4.	Cook on medium low flame for about 10 minutes till milk thickens or till the gourd is fully cooked, stir occasionally.
5.	Add stevia, almond flour to this mixture, and cook on medium flame for another 2-3 minutes or until it thickens a bit.
6.	Lastly add cardamom powder and nuts. Mix well. Turn off the gas. Bottle Gourd Halwa is Ready. Serve hot or chilled.
