column2: HiFi Chapati with 1 tsp Ghee (High- Fibre Chapati)
column3: 1 चम्मच घी (उच्च-फाइबर चपाती) के साथ हिफी चपाती
column24:
INGREDIENTS
2tbsp Bajra flour
2tbsp Ragi flour
2tbsp Green moong flour 
2tbsp Bengal gram flour (Whole Black chana flour and not besan)
Luke warm water (required to knead)
Ghee ½  tsp
Psyllium Husk 1 tbsp
column25:
METHOD
Heat water in a bowl. 
Mix all the flours together. Keep adding water enough to make soft pliable dough. 
Knead for few minutes untill it turns sticky. Add ghee and knead again. 
Brush ghee over the kneaded dough and keep it aside covered in moist muslin cloth for 15-30 minutes. 
Make small balls of the dough
Dust the rolling base with little amount of flour and roll using the rolling pin.
If the chapati is not rolling properly,  take two parchment papers or rice papers and keep the rolling dough in between them and then roll on to the plastic sheet.
Heat a griddle
When the griddle becomes hot, transfer the roti on it. Squeeze off excess water from the muslin cloth and smear water over the roti including the edges with the cloth. Do not pour water on roti. The roti must become moist all over.  By now the roti firms up from the centre. 
Flip the roti to the other side. Repeat dampening and then cover it. 
When the roti is cooked, remove from griddle and rub ½ tsp ghee over it. 
Serve hot with curries or vegetables. 


*NOTE: Do not discard the husk after sieving. Add the sieved husk if it is free from any kind of contamination.

column24:
INGREDIENTS
½ cup finely grated unpeeled beetroot
¼ tsp green cardamom powder
10 cashew nuts/equivalent number of walnuts, soaked for 8 hours
2 tsp water
½ cup pitted soft black dates, ground between fingers or otherwise ground into a paste
8-10 almonds, slivered
column25:
METHOD
Steam the grated beetroot with cardamom powder, for about 5 minutes. 
Blend the cashew nuts or walnuts with the water to make a thick cream. 
Add this  and the ground dates to the steamed beetroot and mix very well. 
Transfer to a serving bowl. 
Garnish with the slivered almonds. Chill before serving.

column24:
INGREDIENTS

1 tbsp dry dates powder
A pinch cardamom powder
⅛  cup raisins, or as required to bind the barfi
A pinch Himalayan pink salt
column25:
METHOD
Mix all the ingredients together (except the raisins), very well. 
Mash the raisins and knead them into the coconut mixture. 
Press this mixture into a wide stainless steel dish and cut into desired shapes. 
Garnish with desiccated coconut. 
Refrigerate the barfi for 6-8 hours before unmolding.
Store in the refrigerator.

column24:
INGREDIENTS
Methi (Fresh Fenugreek Leaves) - 200 gms
Bajra Flour: 1 cup (About 200gms)
Besan : 1 Cup (About 200gms)
Salt to taste
Red chili powder: 1 tsp
Ginger Garlic paste 1/2 tsp
Ajwain: 1/2 tsp
Pinch of Sugar
Amchur : 1/2 tsp
Warm Water to knead the dough
2 tablespoons Sesame seeds (Til seeds)
column25:
METHOD
To begin, heat water in a pot, when it starts to boil, add cleaned fenugreek leaves. Let them boil for 5 mins. Turn off the heat.
When a little cooled, strain the water and chop the leaves roughly. Keep Aside. This step is important to soften the leaves so they become easy to knead
In a bowl, take both flours, add salt to taste (About 1/2 tsp) , Ajwain, Red chili powder, Amchur and mix well
Add in the ginger garlic paste, add sesame seeds and using little warm water at a time knead to a smooth dough (Your may use the left over water in which the leaves were boiled)
Make small rounds of the dough and keep aside.
Heat a non stick pan or iron griddle, drizzle 1 tbsp oil. While the oil heats up, dust flour on a plain surface and using your palm, press a small portion of the dough into a flat round shape
Cook the flattened dough in the pan for 3 mins on each side.. drizzle a little oil to aid in even cooking on both sides.
When the theplas are nice golden brown on each side remove from pan and serve hot with achar or sauce
These bajra theplas are to be eaten hot and not stored for later as they start to become tough.

⅛  tsp green cardamom powder
¼  cup grated fresh coconut

5-7 almonds, slivered
column25:

Knead the ground dates into the carrot coconut mixture. 
Repeat this process until all the dates are kneaded into the mixture.
Transfer to a serving bowl and chill in the refrigerator for 2 hours.

column24:
INGREDIENTS
¼  cup ragi/nachni (finger millet) flour
½ -1 cup warm water
¼  cup finely chopped onion
1 green chilli, finely chopped
1 tbsp finely chopped fresh coriander leaves
4-5 curry leaves, finely chopped
½ tsp Himalayan Pink salt
column25:
METHOD
Mix ragi flour with warm water until there is no lump left. Then, add onion, green chilli, coriander leaves, curry leaves and salt. The batter should be thin.
Heat the dosa tawa (pancake griddle), pour a ladleful of batter from the outer corners of the tawa and fill the inside of the tawa. You cannot spread this batter like a normal dosa.
It will take time to cook dosa, so have patience. Keep the heat medium to high. Once cooked, turn it over and allow the other side to get cooked.
Remove the dosa from the tawa and serve hot with chutney or sambar. 
This dosa will taste good only when served hot, direct from the tawa.
If you have difficulty in preparing this style of ragi dosa, you should prepare like regular dosas. Add less water in batter and make small regular dosa.

INGREDIENTS
⅔ cup thick, creamy coconut milk
2 tbsp Bengal gram flour (besan)
3 cups water
½ tsp cumin (jeera) seeds
2 green chillies, slit
2” pc ginger, ground to paste
Curry leaves
Pink Himlayan salt- to taste
½ tsp turmeric powder
1 lemon
column25:
METHOD
Prepare a slurry of the bengal gram flour in 3 cups of water. If the coconut milk is watery instead of thick, use less than 3 cups of water here
Dry roast the cumin seeds. When the cumin seeds begin to sputter, add large pieces of the green chillies, ginger paste and curry leaves. 
To this seasoning, add the gram flour slurry and salt.
If you like the curry to be yellow, add turmeric powder. 
Heat this liquid mixture until it comes to a boil.
Then reduce the heat to low, add the coconut milk and simmer for just a minute (Important to keep the heat low and heat coconut milk only for a short duration, otherwise coconut milk splits)
Turn the heat off and add the juice of half a lemon. 
Serve with hot rice, millets or chapatis

4. Keep the pomegranate immersed in water and with your fingers remove the pomegranate seeds (arils). the seeds settle down and the white pith floats on top. Remove the pith and discard them.
5. drain all the water using a strainer.
6. add the pomegranate arils in a blender, grinder or mixer jar.
7. Blend well.
8. Take a pan or bowl and keep a juice strainer on it. Now pour the pomegranate juice in the strainer.

column18: Sesame seeds are a good source of calcium.
column24:
•        Sesame seeds  1 tbsp
•        Jaggery 5 gm                                                                                                                            •        Peanuts- 3 gm
•        Cardamom powder 1 tsp
•        Ghee- 4 g
column25:
1.        Heat a kadai or pan and add ⅓ cup sesame seeds to it. The pan should not be too hot but on low heat.
2.        On a low flame roast the sesame seeds. Stir at intervals.
3.        The sesame seeds pop and change color. On a low heat, this takes about 2 to 3 minutes. Do not brown them.
4.        Once the sesame seeds are roasted well, remove them and set aside in a plate.
5.        Then add ¼ cup of peanuts to the same pan. These are raw peanuts and not toasted or salted peanuts.
6.        Dry roast the peanuts on a low heat stirring often until they become crunchy and get a few black spots or blisters on them.
7.        In the same pan, add ¼ cup desiccated coconut.
8.        Add the roasted coconut to the roasted sesame seeds.
9.        When the peanuts have cooled, crush them coarsely. You can also crush them in a blender or spice grinder.
10.        Add the coarsely crushed peanuts to the roasted coconut and sesame seeds.
11.        Next add ¼ teaspoon cardamom powder.
12.         In the same pan or kadai, take ½ heaped cup powdered jaggery or grated jaggery.
13.        Add 3 tablespoons water.
14.        Keep the kadai or pan on the stovetop on a low heat.
15.        Mix quickly and thoroughly the dry roasted mixture with the jaggery solution.
16.        When the mixture is still hot, begin to form and shape til laddu from it. If it is too hot, then wait for a minute and then form the laddu.

column24:
•        Amaranth leaves – 1 cup
•       Onions – 1 medium (1 cup when chopped)
•        Besan (gram flour) – 1 tablespoon
•        Amchoor powder (dry mango powder) – 1/2 teaspoon 
•        Red chili powder – 1/2 teaspoon
•        Turmeric powder – 1/3 teaspoon
•        Salt – to taste
•        Dry red chilies – 1
•        Asafoetida powder – 1/3 teaspoon 
•        Cumin seeds – 1/2 teaspoon

column25:
1.	Pluck the leaves and tender stems for use in the saag. Discard the thick stem/root.
2.	Wash the amaranth leaves well.
3.	Chop the leaves.
4.	Chop the onions finely.
5.	In a pan, heat the oil. When hot, add asafoetida powder and cumin seeds, let the seeds crackle. Add a dry red chili, toss it over quickly as it turns shade, then add finely chopped onions.
6.	Fry the onions on medium heat till golden. Add turmeric powder and red chili powder, cook for a minute.
7.	Add the chopped amaranth leaves along with salt. Cook covered, stirring every other minute, till the leaves have wilted and released water (around 10 minutes).
8.	Add amchoor powder and stir. Sprinkle besan all over. Quickly mix the besan in before it forms lumps. Continue to cook the saag on medium-high heat, stirring regularly, for about 5 minutes or till the besan has cooked and blended well.
9.	Chaulai saag is ready to serve.

column18: Strong bones are the main contribution of agathi leaves. The vitamins and rich calcium, iron.
column24:
•        28 grams Agathi keerai , washed and coarsely chopped
•        1/4 cup Yellow Moong Dal (Split) , soaked for 2 hours
•        1/2 teaspoon Cumin seeds (Jeera)
•        1/4 teaspoon Mustard seeds (Rai/ Kadugu)
•        1/4 teaspoon Asafoetida (hing)
•        1 tablespoon Jaggery
•        2 Dry Red Chillies
•        1 tablespoons Fresh coconut
•        1 teaspoon Oil
•        Salt , to taste
column25:
1.	To begin making the Agathi Keerai Recipe, we will first cook the Agathi Keerai and the Moong Dal.
2.	I am assuming the Moong Dal has been soaking for a couple of hours. When we soak it, it will take less time to get cooked along with the greens. Once soaked, drain the excess water from the dal.
3.	Place the chopped Agathi Keerai and the soaked Moong Dal into the pressure cooker. Add 2 to 3 tablespoons of water, sprinkle some salt and cover the pressure cooker. Place the weight on and pressure cook the greens and the lentils until you hear a couple of whistles. Turn off the heat after a couple of whistles and allow the pressure to release naturally. 
4.	Once the pressure has released naturally, our next step is to season the Agathi Keerai.

6.	Transfer the chopped radish, spring onions and Chinese chives and mix well. Set aside. 
7.	Transfer the cabbage on a plate and discard the water from the container. Rinse the cabbage with fresh water and squeeze to remove excess water and place on a sieve. 
8.	Apply the prepared mixture on to each layer of the cabbage. Transfer into an air tight jar and set aside for 1 day.

5. Flip the shrimps over as they have turned into opaque color.
6. Lower heat to medium and add in the spice of 1/2 teaspoon salt, 1/2 teaspoon black pepper, 1 teaspoon red chili flakes, and some of the chopped parsley.

8. Turn off heat and dish up prawns onto a serving platter.
9. Garnish the rest of the parsley onto prawns.

2 cups Leftover roti 
(phulka or chapati)
 chopped into 
half inch squares

 (about 10 Rotlis)

column25:
To begin making the Vaghareli Rotli, in a large bowl, combine the chopped rotlis.
Heat oil in a pan on medium high; add mustard seeds, cumin seeds and allow them to crackle. 

Add the turmeric powder, curry leaves, red chilli powder and asafoetida. Stir for a few seconds

Stir in the torn roti until well combined with the seasoning. Turn the heat to low and roast the vaghareli rotli mixture until slightly crisp, stirring occasionally.

Once the desired texture is achieved turn off the heat and serve the Vaghareli Rotli immediately.

Serve the Vaghareli Rotli Recipe (Roti Ka Poha) along with a hot cup of Adrak Chai for breakfast or as a tea time snack.

column25:
Take 1/4th cup sabudana, wash it and sprinkle water on and leave it for 3 hours - This will be used to coat the sabudana outer part
In another bowl Take 1/4th cup sabudana, wash it and sprinkle water and leave 4-5 spoon water inside for it to soak for 3 hours - This will be inside 
Take 3 potatoes boil grated
Add salt
Add 3-4 finely chopped chilli
Add finely chopped coriander leaves
Add 2-3 tbs  crushed roasted peanuts 
Add 1 tsp jeera (cumin seeds)
Take the more water soaked soft sabudana into mixture
Mix it while crushing sabudana inside
This will ensure sabudana gets crushed inside well and will give binding to sabudana pops
Add 1/2 lemon juice
Make small balls 
Dip these in watery butter milk
Now roll and cover these by the less soaked sabudana balls
Press with hand little so that sabudana sticks
Now keep the sabudana balls in fridge for 10 minutes
now shallow fry them in appam pan
and on very slow flame cook it on all sides by covering with lead
Sabudana ball pops are ready
You can serve them by sticking toothpick and dipping them in curd

1-1/4 cup Gram flour( besan)
1-1/2 tbsp Fine rava/ Sooji
1/2 cup Curd (yogurt)
1/2 cup Red Beetroot puree thick
1-1/2 tsp Green chili paste
1-1/2 tsp Ginger paste
2 tbsp Oil
1/8 tsp Asafoetida (hing)
1-1/8 tsp Salt

1 tsp Citric acid (limu ka ful)
2 tsp Fruit salt (ENO)
For Tempering
3 tbsp Oil
1 tsp Black mustard seeds
1 tsp Sesame seeds
2 big Green chilies
6-7 Curry leaves
1 tsp Sugar
1/3 cup Fresh coriander leaves chopped
column25:
1, Keep all ingredients ready before you start making dhoklas. Strain the besan (gram flour) using a strainer. Peel one beetroot, chopped it into small pieces. Cook beetroot along with a little water in a microwave for 3-4 minutes. Cool down and grind it to make a puree.
In a mixing bowl, add besan, rava, salt, citric acid (limu ka ful), sugar, hing, green chili and ginger paste. Mix it well. Add curd and beetroot puree, a little bit at a time, and make a lump free batter. Add oil and mix it well. Cover it and keep it aside for 10-15 minutes.                                                          2. In a mixing bowl, add besan, rava, salt, citric acid (limu ka ful), sugar, hing, green chili and ginger paste. Mix it well. Add curd and beetroot puree, a little bit at a time, and make a lump free batter. Add oil and mix it well. Cover it and keep it aside for 10-15 minutes.                                                      3. Also boil a little water with the stand in a big pot at medium to high heat. The water level should be under the stand. Grease a 7'' dhokla pan or thali with oil and keep the greased pan on the stand in the boiling water                                                                                                                                       4. Once the water starts boiling, take out the dhokla pan. Add 2 tsp ENO into the batter. Mix it gently and very well.                                                                 5. Immediately pour the batter into the dhokla pan.
6. Place the dhokla pan into the steamer on the stand. Cover it and let it cook for 12 minutes. During this period do not open the lid.                              7. Once it is done, insert the toothpick into the dhokla, it should come out clean. Take out the dhokla from the steamer. Let it cool down. Cut the dhokla into small pieces.                                                                                                                                                                                                          8. Meanwhile, prepare tempering, and keep all tempering ingredients ready                                                                                                                              9. Heat oil in a pan at medium heat. Once the oil is hot, add mustard seeds and sesame seeds. Once it starts crackling, add green chilies and curry leaves. Saute it for few seconds. Add 1/3 cup water and 1 tsp sugar into the oil. Stir and turn off the heat.                                                                             10. Pour hot tempering all over the dhokla evenly.
11. Lastly, sprinkle some coriander leaves and coconut on top. Let it settle for 20 minutes.

column25:
1. Combine all the ingredients in a bowl and knead into a stiff dough using enough water. 
Keep aside for 10 to 15 minutes.
2. Divide the dough into 20 equal portions and roll out each portion
 into a circle of about 75 mm. (3") diameter
3. Grease a baking tray using oil, place 6 to 8 puris at a time on it and prick all over using a fork.
4. Bake in a pre-heated oven at 180°c (360°f) for 15 to 20 minutes or 
till the puris are golden brown, turning them once in between.
5. Repeat with the remaining dough to make more puris in 2 more batches.
6. Cool and store in an air-tight container.

column25:
1. Combine all the ingredients in a bowl, mix well and knead into a semi-soft dough using enough water.
2. Put the mixture into a chakli press and press out round swirls of the dough onto a greased baking tray, working closely from the centre to the outside to the swirls (approximately 50 mm. (2") diameter). You will get about 30 chaklis.
3. Bake these chaklis in a pre-heated oven at 180°c (360°f) for 30 to 35 minutes, turning all the chaklis once after 15 to 20 minutes.
4. Cool and store in an air-tight container.

column24:
For the dhoklis
1 cup whole wheat flour (gehun ka atta)
1½ tbsp besan (Bengal gram flour)
Salt to taste
½ tsp chilli powder
½ tsp turmeric powder (haldi)
¼ tsp carom seeds (ajwain), optional 
1 tbsp oil
Whole wheat flour (gehun ka atta) for rolling
 
For the dal
1 cup toovar (arhar) dal
Salt to taste
5 kokum, soaked for 15 minutes and drained
½ tbsp lemon juice
5 tbsp chopped jaggery (gur)
1 tsp ginger-green chilli (adrak-mirchi) paste
1 tsp chilli powder
3 tbsp broken cashews (kaju)
10 curry leaves (kadi patta)
¼ tsp turmeric powder (haldi)
2 tbsp ghee
1 tbsp oil
¼ tsp cumin seeds (jeera)
¼ tsp mustard seeds (rai / sarson)
¼ tsp asafoetida (hing)
2 round red chillies (boriya mirch)
1 stick cinnamon (dalchini)
2 cloves (laung / lavang)
Other ingredients
4 tbsp chopped coriander (dhania)
1 tbsp ghee
column25:
For the dhoklis
1. Combine all the ingredients in a deep bowl and knead into a semi-stiff dough using enough water.
2. Cover the dough with a lid and keep aside for atleast 15 minutes
3. Divide the dough into 5 equal portions and roll out each portion into a 200 mm. (8”) diameter thin circle using a little whole wheat flour for rolling. 
4. Heat a non-stick tava (griddle) and cook each chapati lightly from both the sides.
5. Cool and cut each chapati into diamond or square shapes and keep aside.
For the dal
1. Clean, wash and drain the dal. 
2. Combine the dal and 2 cups of hot water in a pressure cooker and pressure cook for 3 whistles.
3. Allow the steam to escape before opening the lid. 
4. Combine the cooked dal and 1 cup of hot water in a deep non-stick pan and blend it well using a hand blender till smooth. 
5. Add more 2½ cups of hot water and mix very well. 
6. Place the deep non-stick pan on the flame , add the salt, kokum, lemon juice, jaggery, ginger-green chilli paste, chilli powder, cashewnuts, curry leaves and turmeric powder, mix well and cook on a medium flame for 10 to 15 minutes, while stirirng occasionally. 
7. Meanwhile, for the tempering, heat the ghee and oil in a small non-stick pan, add the cumin seeds and mustard seeds and allow them to crackle.                                                                                                                                                                                  
8. When the seeds crackle, add the asafoetida, red chillies, cinnamon, cloves and sauté on a medium flame for 30 seconds. 
9. Add this tempering to the dal, mix well and cook on a medium flame for 2 to 3 minutes, while stirirng occasionally. Keep aside.
How to proceed
Just before serving, boil the dal, once it starts boiling, add the dhoklis, coriander and ghee, mix well and cook on a medium flame for 1 to 2 minutes, while stirring occasionally. 
Serve immediately with ghee.

column24:
60g puttu flour
¼ tsp salt
¾-1 cup water (as required)
2 tbsp coconut (grated)
column25:
firstly in a large bowl take 60g puttu flour and ¼ tsp salt. mix well.
now add ¼ cup water and crumble the flour.
add water in batches and mix well with your fingertips.
the flour need to hold shape when pressed between the fist, and need to break on further pressing.
make a moist flour with crumbly texture.
break all the lumps with your finger. alternatively, blend it in a mixer for 2 pulses.
now take a puttu steamer and layer with 2 tbsp of fresh grated coconut.
followed by 3 tbsp of puttu flour. again layer with 2 tbsp of coconut, 3 tbsp of 3 tbsp of puttu flour.
lastly add 2 tbsp coconut and level it up.
close the puttu kutty (cylindrical tube) and steam for 5 minutes or till the steam escapes from top holes of puttu kutty (cylindrical tube).
carefully open it and push the puttu using a wooden ladle from the back.
finally, serve kerala puttu hot along with kadala curry.

column24:
•        1 cup Rice flour 
•        Salt to taste 
•        Water
•        Oil
column25:
1.	In a mixing bowl, take rice flour. Add salt and mix well. 
2.	Add water. Stir well. No lumps should be formed. 
3.	Add little water at a time and mix well. It should be thin and not too thick. 
4.	Heat a pan on medium heat.
5.	When the pan is enough hot add oil. Spread the oil over the pan. 
6.	Mix the rice batter well. While preparing ghavan, put the batter on the sides of the pan first and the come to the center. 
7.	Cover and cook for a minute. Remove the lid and cook for another 4 – 5 minutes. 
8.	Flip over and cook for 2 – 3 minutes. 
9.	Take it off the pan and serve hot. 
10.	Ghavane go well with mushroom sabzi or chicken. 
11.	Can be served with peanut or green chutney too.

column24:
•        1 tbsp - Oil 
•        Asafoetida 
•        1 tsp - mustard seeds 
•        5-6 Split Chilies 
•        100 g- Jackfruit (Chopped & boiled in salt ) 
•        1 tsp - turmeric powder 
•        1 tsp - red chili powder 
•        1 tsp - jaggery 
•        Juice of ½ lime 
•        1 tbsp grated coconut Coriander
column25:
1.	Heat a wok, add oil and once the oil is hot add asafoetida, mustard seeds.
2.	Once the mustard seeds start to crackle add chilies, jackfruit, cashew, turmeric powder, red chili powder, jaggery, lime juice. 
3.	Mix them well. Add grated coconut and mix them well. 
4.	Close the lid and let it cook for 5 minutes on low flame.
5.	Mix it once and then garnish it with coriander. 
6.	Our Fansachi Bhaji is ready to serve.

column24:
•        1 Banana Blossom/Plantain Flower/Banana Flower, cleaned and finely chopped ½ tsp. 
•        Cumin seeds ¼ tsp. 
•        Turmeric powder 
•        2 onions, finely chopped 1 tbsp. 
•        Mix Masala 
•        Salt, to taste 
•        Freshly Grated Coconut
column25:
1.	In a bowl add salt to the chopped banana blossom and let it rest for 30 minutes. 
2.	In a kadhai, heat oil and add cumin seeds, turmeric powder, mix masala, salt and mix well. 
3.	Now add the banana blossom and mix well. 
4.	Cover with the lid and simmer for 15 minutes. 
5.	Add grated coconut and stir. 
6.	Simmer for 5 more minutes covering with the lid. 
7.	Garnish with coriander leaves and serve.

column25:
1.        Wash the poha. Add curd in to it. 
2.        Heat the oil, add mustard seeds, hing and jeera, ginger, garlic, chilli and curry leaves. 
3.        Add this tadka to the curd. 
4.        Add the coriander.

column24:
•        1 cup Pohe / Flattened rice
•        8~9 Garlic cloves
•        3~4 Green chilies
•        1/4 tsp Ajwain / Carom seeds
•        1/2 tsp Cumin seeds
•        1/2 cup grated Cabbage
•        1/2 tsp Red chili powder
•        1 tsp Coriander powder
•        1/2 tsp Turmeric powder
•        Salt to taste
•        1/4 cup Jawar flour
•        Water 
•        Finely chopped Coriander leaves
•        Finely chopped Onion
•        Oil
column25:
1.	Wash pohe really good 2-3 times with water and soak them in a little water.
2.	Take garlic cloves, green chilies, ajwain, cumin seeds in a blender jar and blend it into coarse 
3.	paste. 
4.	You can add coriander leaves if you want. 
5.	Vatan or masala is ready. 
6.	Wash and grate the cabbage. 
7.	You can chop the cabbage finely if you want. 
8.	Mash the soaked pohe really good and add vatan, red chili powder, coriander powder, turmeric 
9.	powder, salt. 
10.	Mix everything well together and add jawar flour. 
11.	Mix well and add water and mix well. 
12.	Add cabbage, coriander leaves, onion water and mix well. 
13.	The consistency of batter should be a little thick than dosa batter. 
14.	Spread oil on the pan. 
15.	Add batter and spread it evenly. 
16.	Cover and cook for about 2 minutes. 
17.	Remove the lid and cook until the lower side gets nice golden color. 
18.	Flip over carefully and cook well from other side too. 
19.	When the thalipeeth is cooked well from both sides take it off into a dish. 
20.	Kobiche thalipeeth is all ready.

column24:
•	Cucumber
•	2 tsp Roasted peanut powder
•	Finely chopped Coriander leaves
•	Salt to taste
•	Sugar
•	1/2 tsp Cumin seeds
•	1 finely chopped Green chili
•	Lemon juice
•	1 tsp Ghee
column25:
1.        Peel the cucumber and cut off its both ends. 
2.        Take “vili” and cut the cucumber vertically from all sides. 
3.        Once done cut the cucumber horizontally. 
4.        Repeat the process. This is known as “kakdi chochavane” in Marathi. 
5.        If you don’t want to use vili then you can use knife. 
6.        Take the cucumber into a bowl. 
7.        Add coconut, roasted peanut powder, coriander leaves, salt, sugar and lemon juice. 
8.        Mix everything well together. 
9.        Heat up ghee in a pan. 
10.        Add cumin seeds and let them splutter. 
11.        Add green chili and add the tadka into cucumber mixture. 
12.        Khamang kakdi is already. 
13.        You can have this khamang kakdi as it is as salad.
14.        You can serve this as a side dish too.

column24:
•        1/4 Cup Shredded Cabbage
•        A Small Sized Sliced Onion 
•        2 Tbsp Finely Chopped Coriander Leaves
•        1 Tbsp Raw Peanuts
•        1/2 Tsp Sugar
•        1 Tbsp Fresh Lemon Juice
•        Salt To Taste
For The Tempering :
•        1/3 Tsp Mustard Seeds
•        3/4 Tsp Cumin Seeds
•        1/8 Tsp Turmeric Powder
•        2 Green Chillies Minced (Medium Spicy)
•        1 Tsp Finely Chopped Ginger
•        1 Tsp Oil
column25:
1.	In a small kadai,
2.	Roast the peanuts on medium heat till golden brown
3.	Then off the flame
4.	Keep aside to cool
5.	Rinse the cabbage well and remove the outer leaf one
6.	Chop the cabbage thinly lenghtwise Or grate it
7.	You can chop it into small dice
8.	Remove the shredded cabbage in a mixing bowl
9.	Once cooled, you can remove the skin of the peanuts
10.	Grind it coarsely in a mortar-pestle
11.	You can grind it in a mixer
12.	Add the coarsed peanut in the mixing bowl
13.	Add the sliced onion, coriander leaves , lemon juice,
14.	Sugar and salt to taste
15.	Mix the ingredients well
16.	Keep aside
17.	For the tempering,
18.	Heat the oil in the small kadai Or pan
19.	Add the muster seeds and cumin seeds
20.	Saute on low heat till the seeds crackle
21.	Add the minced ginger in the kadai
22.	Saute for 30 seconds on low flame
23.	Add the minced green chilli, turmeric powder and 
24.	A pinch of salt , saute for 30-40 seconds on low flame
25.	You can a pinch of asafoetida in it
26.	Off the flame
27.	Leave it for a minute
28.	Pour the tempering in the mixing bowl
29.	Mix well
30.	Give it a taste lemon, sugar or salt as if needed
31.	Kobichi Koshimbir is ready
32.	Remove in a serving plate
33.	Serve

2.	Serve immediately or refrigerate for 1 hour and serve chilled.

column24:
•        Tomatoes pureed 2 medium
•        Gram Flour 2 teaspoons
•        Salt to taste
•        Red chilli powder 1 teaspoon
•        Turmeric powder 1/2 teaspoon
•        Mustard seeds 1/2 teaspoon
•        Cumin seeds 1/2 teaspoon
•        Asafoetida a pinch
•        Whole dry red chillies 4-5
•        Curry leaves 5-6
•        Sugar 1 teaspoon
•        Fresh coriander leaves chopped2 tsp
column25:
1.	Combine all the ingredients in a bowl and toss well. 
2.	Serve immediately or refrigerate for 1 hour and serve chilled.
3.	Take gram flour in a bowl. Add salt, red chilli powder, turmeric powder and mix. Add fresh tomato puree and whisk well. Add two cups of water and mix.
4.	Heat a non stick pan. Add mustard seeds and cumin seeds and roast till the mustards seeds crackle.
5.	Add a pinch of asafoetida, broken dry red chillies and curry leaves and roast till a nice aroma is given out. Add the tomato mixture and mix.
6.	Once the mixture comes to a boil, reduce heat and cook for about ten minutes till the mixture is thickened and well cooked. Add sugar if the kadhi is too sour. Add coriander leaves and mix.
7.	Serve hot with boiled brown rice.

column24:
•        200 ml Buttermilk
•        1/2 tsp Oil
•        1 tbsp Ginger Garlic crush
•        1 tbsp Gram Flour
•        1/2 tsp Mustard Seeds
•        1/2 tsp Cumin Seeds
•        10-12 Curry Leaves
•        1 Green Chiili
•        1/2 tsp Turmeric Powder
•        1 tsp Sugar
•        Salt to taste
column25:
1.	In a large bowl, take buttermilk. Add turmeric powder, sugar, salt, gram flour. Mix everything well.
2.	Heat some oil in a pan. Add mustard seeds, cumin seeds, green chilli, curry leaves & crushed ginger garlic. Saute everything well.
3.	Then add the buttermilk mixture and some water.
4.	Boil the kadhi for 5 minutes.
5.	Garnish it with coriander leaves and serve hot!

column24:
•        1 glass Buttermilk
•        Grated Ginger
•        A pinch of finely chopped Green chilli
•        1/2 tsp Roasted Cumin powder
•        1/4 tsp powdered Sugar
•        1/2 tsp Black salt
•        Finely chopped Coriander leaves
column25:
1.	In a bowl, take buttermilk. 
2.	Take grated ginger and sieve its juice into buttermilk. 
3.	Add a pinch of green chilli. Add just a little green chilli. Do not add more as we don’t want to make buttermilk hot. 
4.	Add roasted cumin powder, powdered sugar, black salt and finely chopped coriander leaves. 
5.	Mix everything well. Taste and adjust any spices if required. 
6.	Add lots of ice cubes and serve chilled.

column24:
•        1 number Beetroot
•        1 tbsp Coriander powder
•        1 tbsp cumin
•        1 tbsp Cumin powder
•        1/4 cup dal
•        3 number Green chillies
•        1 tbsp Mustard
•        1 tsp Oil
•        1 number Onion
column25:
1.        Remove the upper skin of beetroot using peeler and grate the beetroot. Soak moong daal for around 30 min . 
2.        Chop some onions if you would like to use onions but it really adds taste to the curry. Chop green chillies. Heat oil in a pan. 
3.        Add musturd seeds, cumin seeds. Add hing if you would like. Now add green chillies and onions and cook it till it is light brown. 
4.        Add grated beetroot and cook it for some time. Add moong daal. If required add water, else fry it in oil itself. Fry till moong daal is cooked properly and if needed add water. 
5.        Add salt, chilli powder, cumin powder, sesimi powder, coriander powder and fry till all the moisture is gone.

column24:
•        1/2 cup whole Chana
•        2 cups Water
•        3~4 bay leaves
•        Finely chopped Tomato
•        1 tsp Oil
•        1/2 tsp Cumin seeds
•        Curry leaves
•        Finely chopped Onion
•        1 tsp Ginger-Garlic paste
•        1 tsp Kala masala
•        Red chili powder
•        Salt to taste
•        Finely chopped Coriander leaves
column25:
1.	Wash and soak chana in enough water for 1 day. You can soak it for 1 1/2 day too. 
2.	Transfer the soaked chana into cooker. 
3.	Add water, bay leaves, tomato and mix well. 
4.	Cook on medium heat until 7-8 whistles. 
5.	Heat up oil in a pan. 
6.	Add cumin seeds and let it splutter. 
7.	Add curry leaves, onion and fry until onion gets nice golden color. 
8.	When onion gets light golden color add ginger-garlic paste, kala masala, red chili powder and mix well.
9.	Fry everything for just 2 minutes. 
10.	You can use goda masala or kanda lasun masala or any other masala available in your home in place of kala masala. 
11.	When masala begins to release oil add cooked chana, salt and mix well. 
12.	You can decide the consistency as per your choice. 
13.	Simmer on medium heat for another 7-8 minutes. 
14.	Garnish with coriander leaves and chana masala is all ready.

column24:
•        10 ripe jackfruit seeds, boiled, peeled and cut into quarters
•        ½ tbsp oil
•        1-2 green chillies, chopped
•        2 tsp grated ginger
•        2 tsp finely chopped garlic
•        1 medium onion, finely chopped
•        1 cup fresh tomato puree
•        1½ tsp Tata Sampann Garam Masala
•        1½ tsp red chilli powder
•        ½ tsp turmeric powder
•        ¾ tsp coriander powder
•        1½ tsp cumin powder
•        Salt to taste
•        2 tbsp freshly chopped coriander leaves
•        Coriander sprig for garnish
column25:
1.	Heat oil in a non-stick pan, add green chillies, ginger and garlic. Sauté for 1-2 minutes.
2.	Add onion, mix well and cook till translucent. Sautéing occasionally. Add tomato puree and mix well. Cook for 2-3 minutes.
3.	Add Tata Sampann Garam Masala, red chilli powder, turmeric powder, coriander powder, cumin powder and mix well. Cook for 1 minute.
4.	Add salt, mix well and cook for 2-3 minutes. Add ½ cup water and mix well. Cover and cook till the oil separates.
5.	Add jackfruit seeds, chopped coriander and mix well. Cook for 1 minute and take it off the heat.
6.	Transfer into a serving plate garnish with coriander sprig. Serve hot with chapatis.

column24:

•        1 tsp Mustard Seeds
•        1 tbsp Ginger Garlic crush
•        Coriander Leaves
•        1 Onion, chopped
•        Salt to taste
•        1/2 tsp Turmeric Powder
•        2 tsp Mix Masala
•        20 gms Gram Flour
•        Water
column25:
1.	Heat oil in a pan and add mustard seeds. Once the mustard seeds start spluttering, add ginger garlic paste, coriander leaves, onion, salt, turmeric powder & mix masala. Let all the ingredients cook for some time. 
2.	Add spring onion and mix well. It enhances the taste of Zunka.
3.	Add gram flour & mix well. Make sure there are no lumps.
4.	Add little water to keep the Zunka moist. Repeat this step for two more times and mix well. 
5.	Cover it with a lid and let it cook for 5 to 10 mins on a low flame.
6.	Garnish it with coriander leaves and serve hot.

column24:
•	2 tsp Coconut
•	1 tsp Oil
•	3~4 Garlic cloves
•	1 medium size sliced Onion
•	For Amti:
•	1 tsp Oil
•	1 tsp Goda masala
•	1 tsp Red chilli powder
•	Chana dal stock
•	Salt to taste
column25:
For Amti Masala:
1.	Heat up a pan and add coconut. 
2.	Roast until coconut nice and red. 
3.	Transfer the roasted coconut into a blender jar. 
4.	In the same pan add oil, garlic cloves and onion. 
5.	Fry until onion turns nice and red. 
6.	Transfer the onion into blender jar and blend. 
7.	Vatan or masala for amti is already.
For Amti:
8.	Heat up a pan and add oil. 
9.	Add blended masala, goda masala and red chilli powder. 
10.	Fry masala on medium heat for about 3-4 minutes. 
11.	When oil begins to release from sides, add chana dal stock and salt to taste. 
12.	Mix well and boil amti for about 7-8 minutes. Katachi amti is a bit runny. 
13.	Turn off the gas and katachi amti is already. 
14.	Serve it with hot puran poli and ghee.

column25:
1.	Soak the urad dal in water for 5 hours. 
2.	Soak the rava/semolina in water for 5 hours. 
3.	Grind the semolina and urad dal by adding little water. 
4.	Add salt. Then keep this for 10 hours.
5.	Then make amboli on the pan by adding the batter in round shape.

column25:

2.	Divide the dough into 6 small balls. Roll the dough into 3â€ circles and cook on a hot griddle on both sides, until the parathas are golden brown.
3.	Serve hot with pickle or tomato sauce.

•        2 tbsps chopped fresh coriander leaves
•        Whole wheat flour for dusting
•        Ghee for cooking
column25:
1.	Heat oil in a shallow nonstick pan. Add cumin seeds and once they start to change the colour, add green chillies, onion and sauté till translucent.
2.	Add turmeric powder, red chilli powder, cumin powder, chaat masala, garam masala powder, salt and mix well. Take the pan off the heat and allow to cool slightly.
3.	Take boiled yam in a bowl. Add the cooked onion mixture. Add mint, coriander and mix well.
4.	Dust some whole wheat flour on the surface, take a portion of the dough and make cavity in the centre.
5.	Stuff a portion of the yam mixture, bring the edges together and seal properly.
6.	Dust some more flour and roll into thick disk.
7.	Heat a nonstick tawa. Place the prepared parantha and cook for a minute on medium heat or till the underside is golden brown.
8.	Flip and cook on other side for a minute more.
9.	Drizzle some ghee, increase the heat and cook for 30 seconds on each side.
10.	Serve hot with yogurt.

column24:
•        1/4 bunch spinach leaves, shredded
•        1 cup buttermilk (chaas/taakh) 
•        1 tbsp Bengal gram, soaked for 5-6 hours and drained
•         1 tbsp raw peanuts, soaked for 5-6 hours and drained (optional)
•        1-2 green chillies
•        3-4 tsps gram flour (besan)
•        Salt to taste
•        Tempering
•        1 tbsp ghee
•        1 tsp cumin seeds
•        ¼ tsp asafoetida (hing)
•        ¼ tsp Tata Sampann Turmeric Powder
column25:
1.	Heat a pressure cooker, add soaked Bengal gram, soaked peanuts, spinach leaves, green chillies and 1 cup water, cover and cook on medium heat under pressure for 2 whistles are given out.
2.	Switch the heat off and open the cooker once the pressure has reduced completely, transfer the mixture into a non-stick pan and place it back on heat.
3.	Sprinkle gram flour and immediately start mixing, add buttermilk, mix and cook for a minute.
4.	Add sugar, mix and add salt, mix and cook for 3-4 minutes. Using a steel churner, mix the buttermilk mixture to remove of the any lumps.
5.	For the tempering, heat ghee in a non-stick small pan, add cumin seeds and let them change colour. Add asafoetida and Tata Sampann Turmeric Powder and mix well. Pour the tempering over the spinach-buttermilk mixture and mix well. 
6.	Switch the heat off and transfer the bhaji into a serving bowl and serve hot with steamed rice.

column24:
8-10 small brinjals (baingan), vertically halved
1½ cups Basmati rice, washed, soaked for 20 minutes and drained 
¼ cup oil
2 inch cinnamon stick
8-10 cloves
3-4 green cardamoms
1 bay leaf
3-4 green chillies, slit
1½ tbsps chopped garlic
½ tbsp chopped ginger 
2 medium onions, sliced
15-20 cashew nuts (optional)
½ cup browned onions + for garnish
Salt to taste
½ tsp red chilli powder
½ tsp turmeric powder
¾ tsp cumin powder
1 tsp Tata Sampann Coriander Powder
3 tbsps chopped fresh coriander leaves + for garnish
2½ cups buttermilk  
Raita to serve
column25:
1. Heat oil in a wide deep pan, add cinnamon stick, cloves, green cardamoms, and bay leaf and sauté till fragrant. Add green chillies, garlic, ginger and onions and sauté till translucent. 
2. Add cashew nuts and brinjals and sauté for 2-3 minutes. Add browned onion and sauté for a minute.
3. Add salt, red chilli powder, turmeric powder, cumin powder, and Tata Sampann Coriander Powder and mix well. Cook for 1 minute.
4. Add coriander leaves and mix well. Add the soaked rice and gently mix.
5. Pour the buttermilk, mix, cover and cook on high heat for 5-6 minutes. Reduce the heat to low and continue to cook till the rice is done.
6. Garnish with browned onion and coriander leaves and serve hot with raita of your choice.

column24:
2-3 tbsp Oil
2-3 Green Chillies, chopped
10 Colocasia Leaves, chopped
1 Cup Arbi, chopped
1 Cup Sweet Potato, chopped
5-6 Lady Fingers, chopped
1 Cup Raw Banana, chopped
1 Cup Colocasia Roots, chopped
1 Cup Yam, chopped
1 Cup Pumpkin, chopped
1 Cup Ridge Gourd, chopped
1 Cup Red Leafy Vegetable, chopped
1 Corn
1 Cup Groundnuts (optional)
1 Cup Grated Coconut
Salt to taste
column25:
- In a large pan, heat some oil. Once the oil is hot add green chillies.
- Then add all the vegetables one after the other.
- Add salt and grated coconut. Give it a good stir.
- Add some water and cover it with a lid for 10 minutes.
- Remove the lid after 10 minutes and mix well.
- Again cover it for 5 minutes and let the vegetables cook.
- Rushichi Bhaji is ready. This bhaji tastes best with plain rice or roti.

column24:
Serving: 4-5
1 cup of peanuts soaked for at least 4-5  hours/overnight
½ tbsp of tamarind soaked in 1/4 cup of warm water for 10 mins and then the tamarind juice extracted
½   tsp of mustard seeds/rye
½ tsp asafoetida/hing
½  tsp haldi /turmeric powder
½ cumin seeds/jeera
A few curry leaves
1 tbsp of goda/kala masala
½ tsp of gul/jaggery (Optional)
½ tsp of red chilli powder
Salt to taste
1 & ¼ cup of water
column25:
Heat Oil in a pan.
Once the oil is hot add rye/mustard seeds, hing, haldi, cumin seeds, curry leaves and fry well.
Add the peanuts after draining out the water and add the goda masala, red chilli powder, tamarind juice, salt to taste, gud (optional) and mix well.
Add the water and mix well. Close the cooker & cook for 1 whistle on high and simmer for 10 mins.
Once done garnish with a mix of fresh coconut & chopped coriander leaves.

column24:
1 ½ cup of Poha
Water (as required)
1 tbsp Oil
½ tsp Mustard Seeds
7-8 Curry Leaves
½ cup Peanuts
2 Onions (chopped)
1 ½ tsp Salt
1 tsp Sugar (optional)
4 Green Chillies (chopped)
½ Lemon Juice
3 tbsp Coriander Leaves (chopped)
column25:
1. Take poha in a bowl and add the required amount of water to moist it and soak it for 5 minutes.
2. Now take a pan and add oil. Once heated add mustard seeds, curry leaves and peanuts. Mix well.
3. Further, take a bowl and add onion, salt sugar (optional), green chilli, lemon juice and coriander leaves. Mix it well.
4. Once mixed add soaked poha to the bowl of mixture.
5. Post that add roasted peanuts from the pan and mix it well. Serve.

column3: गुड़ के साथ टिल गोंड लडू
column24:
1. 50 grams makhana/fox nuts
2. 50 grams gond/edible gum
3. 100 grams til/sesame seeds
4. 200 grams gur/jaggery, crushed
5. 4-5 tablespoon desi ghee/clarified butter
6. water as needed
column25:
1. Dry roast the til on low heat, stirring constantly until they become crisp and aromatic, about 2-3 minutes. Remove to a plate.
2. Melt 1 tbsp desi ghee and fry half the gond on low heat until they turn fluffy and crisp.
3. Melt 1 more tbsp desi ghee and fry the rest of the gond. Stir constantly. Remove to another plate.
4. Melt 2 tbsp desi ghee and fry the makhana until they become crispy on low heat stirring constantly. Transfer to a bowl.
5. Once the til and makhane have cooled down coarsely grind each of them separately. With a pav bhaji masher coarsely crush the gond. Thoroughly combine all these ingredients in a bowl.
6. Put the crushed gur in a wok. Add 4 tbsp water and keep heat on low-medium heat. Stirring constantly first let the gur melt then cook the mixture until the gur just starts becoming sticky. Take off the heat, add in the coarsely crushed mixture and stir until everything combines well. Let cool until you can handle it comfortably.
7. Make round laddoos from the mixture. This mixture will prepare 12-15 medium-sized laddoos. Let cool completely then store in an airtight box.

column24:
1. 1 cup sesame seeds
2. 1/2 cup deseeded soft dates
3. 2 tablespoon almonds
4. 2 tablespoon cashew
5. 1 tablespoon sunflower seeds
6. 1 tablespoon pumpkin seeds
7. 1 tablespoon flax seeds
8. 1 tablespoon chia seeds
9. 2 tablespoon ghee (optional)
10. 1 teaspoon dry ginger powder
11. 1 teaspoon cardamom powder
column25:
1. Take a pan and roast the sesame seeds on medium heat. Roast until they slightly change their colour and starts to crackle.
2. Let the sesame seeds cool down first and then grind them in the mixer.
3. Next step is to take almonds and cashews and roast them in the pan. Take them out in a bowl.
4. Now take all the seeds, pumpkin, sunflower, flax seeds and chia seeds and roast them. Roast them on medium heat. Take them out in the same bowl as of nuts.
5. Grind the nuts and seeds once they cool down, in a mixer. Make a coarse powder.
6. Take deseeded dates and gind them also into a fine paste.
7. Now take a pan and put ghee (optional). Add dates paste, powdered sesame seeds, grounded nuts and seeds mixture, dry ginger powder and cardamom powder. Mix and cook thoroughly for 2-3 minutes.
8. Once the mixture is ready transfer it to a bowl. Then form ladoo once it cools down a bit.

column2: Dry fruit panjiri  without sugar/ jaggery
column3: चीनी/ गुड़ के बिना सूखे फल पंजरी
column24:
1. 200 grams desi ghee
2. 150 grams almonds
3. 150 grams walnuts
4. 150 grams makhana
5. 50 grams gond
6. 50 grams magaz (watermelon, muskmelon, pumpkin and cucumber seeds)
7. 50 grams kamar kas
8. 250 grams roasted black chana
9. 1/2 cup sugar free powder
column25:
1. Take a vessel and add some ghee in it. Once it melts, then fry the gond until it gets crisp.
2. Then keep gond aside and in the same pan roast kamar kas. Keep that also aside.
3. Now add more ghee in the vessel and roast walnuts. Then roast almonds afterwards.
4. Keep the nuts aside and roast the magaz now which is a combination of seeds (watermelon, pumpkin, muskmelon and cucumber seeds). Keep them also aside.
5. Add a little bit more ghee and roast makhane until crispy, on low flame. 
6. Simultaneously grind the roasted chana in a mixer. Grind until it turns into a fine powder. Then put in an empty pan.
7. Once makhane gets roasted add them in a mixer and grind them into a coarse powder. Add this powder also in the same pan of chana powder.
8. Then grind other ingredients like almond, walnut, kamar kas and gond into a mixer. 
9. Add this mixture in the same bowl and also the seeds as it is. 
10. Now in the mixture of all ingredients add sugar free powder and mix thoroughly.
11. The panjiri is ready to be served.

column24:
1. 1 cup fenugreek seeds (methi dana)
2. 2 cups milk
3. ½ + ⅛ cup ghee
4. ½ cup whole wheat flour (gehun ka atta)
5. ¾ cup almonds
6. 1 cup grated dried coconut
7. ½ cup edible gum resin (dink), fried
8. ½ tsp green cardamom powder
9. ¼ tsp white pepper powder
10. ¼ tsp dried ginger powder (saunth)
11. ¼ tsp long pepper (peepli) powder
12. 2 cups chopped jaggery
column25:
1. Dry roast the fenugreek seeds in a non-stick pan till fragrant. Allow to cool completely. Transfer into a mixer jar and grind into a fine powder. Transfer into a large bowl. Pour 1½ cups milk and mix well. Set aside for 3 hours.
2. Heat ¼ cup ghee in a non-stick pan. Add the soaked fenugreek seeds mixture and sauté on low heat for 2-3 minutes. 
3. Add remaining milk and mix well. Cook till it turns golden brown. Transfer on a large plate and allow to cool completely.
4. Heat ¼ cup ghee in the same pan and add whole wheat flour and mix well. Continue to roast till it turns golden brown and fragrant. Transfer on to the same plate and allow to cool completely. 
5. Heat ⅛ cup ghee in the same pan. Add almonds and roast till golden. Transfer on to another plate. Set aside to cool completely. 
6. Dry roast the dried coconut till golden brown in the same pan. Transfer into the fenugreek-whole wheat mixture and set aside to cool completely. 
7. Put the fried almonds into a mixer jar and grind to a coarse powder. 
8. Put the fried dink on a worktop and coarsely crush it using a rolling pin. Transfer on to the same plate. 
9. Add green cardamom powder, white pepper powder, dried ginger powder, and long pepper powder and mix well. 
10. Heat jaggery and ¼ cup water in a pan till the jaggery melts. Immediately pour this into the mixture along with the ground almonds and mix well. Take small portions of the mixture and shape each portion into a ball. 
11. Arrange on a serving plate and serve.

column3: चीनी/ गुड़ के बिना मेथी लाडू
column24:
1. ½ kg wheat flour
2. 50 grams methi seeds
3. 50 grams gond
4. 250 grams ghee
5. ½ grated coconut
6. 50 grams poppy seeds
7. 50 grams almonds
8. 50 grams walnuts
9. 50 grams raisins
10. 250 grams deseeded dates
11. 50 grams halim seeds
column25:
1. Take a utensil and keep it on flame. Put methi seeds and roast it. Keep it aside.
2. Then roast the poppy seeds and halim seeds together. Once it's done, keep them aside.
3. Now roast the grated coconut and raisins together. Keep them also aside.
4. Add 1 spoon of ghee in the utensil now. Roast gond in it until it turns crispy. Put it aside to cool down.
5. Add the remaining ghee in the utensil and add wheat flour. Roast it until it turns slightly brown and then switch off the flame.
6. Take a mixer and grind gond first. Then pour the gond powder in a separate bowl.
7. Next, grind the methi seeds and add in the same bowl. Now grind almonds and walnuts and put the powder in the same bowl.
8. Grind dates in a mixer and once it's done add the paste in the bowl.
9. Add remaining ingredients like poppy seeds, halim seeds, raisins in the bowl and mix the mixture.
10.Slowly keep on adding roasted wheat flour in the bowl and keep on mixing continuously.
11. Once the mix is ready, start forming the small round balls out of it to make laddoos.

column2: Alsi Ladoo with jaggery/ Flaxseed ladoo with jaggery
column3: गुड़ के साथ अलसी लाडू/ गुड़ के साथ अलसीका लादू
column24:
1. 250 Gram alsi/flaxseeds
2. 4 Tablespoon ghee
3. 150 Gram jaggery
4. 100 Gram desiccated coconut
5. 50 Gram gond
6. 50 Gram almonds
7. 10 Gram pistachio
column25:
1. Take a pan and roast flaxseed in it on medium to low flame. Stir it continuously.
2. Once it starts crackling and shows slight colour change, turn off the flame. Keep the flaxseed aside on a plate.
3. Now grind the flaxseeds into a fine powder in a mixer.
4. Take a pan and add some ghee in it. Roast flaxseed powder for 1-2 minutes to give texture. Put it aside.
5. Now in the same pan add 2 tablespoons of ghee and roast gond on low flame. 
6. Once gond cools down, add it in a mixer and grind it.
7. Now in the same pan add jaggery and melt it on low flame. Do not make syrup of it.
8. Once it's done add roasted flaxseed powder made before. Mix.
9. Further add powdered gond, grated coconut, chopped almonds and pistachio in a pan. Combine it properly.
10. Remove it from the flame and make small balls out of it. Your ladoos will be ready to get served.

column2: Alsi Ladoo without sugar/jaggery/ Flaxseed ladoo without sugar/jaggery
column3: चीनी/गुड़/बिना चीनी/गुड़ के अलसी लाडू/गुड़ के बिना लादू
column24:
1. 2 cup almonds
2. ¾ cup pistachio
3. ¾ cup walnut
4. ½ cup watermelon seeds
5. ½ cup pumpkin seeds
6. 1 cup flax seeds
7. ¼ cup makhana
8. ¼ cup gond
9. 2 cup dates
10. 2 tablespoon ghee
11. 1 cup coconut powder
column25:
1. Take a pan and roast almonds on low to medium heat. Roast it for 1-2 minutes. Keep it aside on a plate.
2. Now roast the walnuts and pistachio together for 1-2 minutes. Stir continuously.
3, Keep nuts aside in the same plate.
4. Roast watermelon and pumpkin seeds in the pan now. Roast on low flame for 1-2 minutes. Put them also aside on a plate.
5. Next roast the flaxseeds on lower flame for 1-2 minutes. Transfer on the plate.
6. Now roast the makhana for 2-3 minutes on lower flame. Roast them until crispy and put it aside to cool down.
7. Once all the ingredients cool down transfer them to a mixer and grind it into a coarse powder.
8. Now take the dates and soak them in hot water for 10 minutes. Once it’s done, grind them in a mixer into a fine paste.
9. Take a pan and add 1 tablespoon of ghee. Pour the dates pulp and cook it until it turns thick. Stir it continuously.
10. Further add the coarse powder of dry fruits and seeds prepared before. Mix it and stir it properly.
11. Next add coconut powder in the mixture. Cook the mix thoroughly.
12. Once it gets cooked properly, transfer it to a bowl and let it cool down.
13. Now you can make laddoos out of the mix in desired size.

column24:
1. ½ cup ghee / clarified butter
2. 1½ cup besan / gram flour
3. 2 tbsp rava / semolina / suji (fine)
4. 2 cup milk
5. ½ cup sugar
6. 2 tbsp saffron milk
7. 2 tbsp cashew / kaju (chopped)
8. ¼ tsp cardamom powder
column25:
1. Firstly, in a large kadai take ½ cup ghee.
2. Once the ghee heats up, add in 1½ cup besan.
3. Also, add 2 tbsp rava. if you are using coarse besan then you can skip the addition of rava.
4. Roast on low flame stirring continuously.
5. Roast for almost 25-30 minutes or until the besan turns golden brown.
6. Now add 2 cups of milk and stir well.
7. Keep stirring continuously, until the besan absorbs all the milk without forming lumps.
8. Cook until the mixture separates the pan.
9. Further, add ½ cup sugar and 2 tbsp saffron milk (you can use water too). 
10. Mix well until the sugar dissolves completely and separates the pan.
11. Further, add in 2 tbsp cashew and ¼ tsp cardamom powder. mix well.
12. Finally, enjoy the besan ka halwa recipe garnished with more cashew (optional).

column24:
2 cups poha
1 tablespoon oil
1 teaspoon jeera seed
1 green chilli
1 chopped onion
1 chopped capsicum
1 chopped tomato
½ teaspoon red chilli powder
¼ teaspoon turmeric powder (haldi)
Salt as per taste
2 eggs
Coriander leaves to garnish
column25:
1. Take poha, wash and keep aside.
2. Then take a pan and add oil. Heat it.
3. Now add jeera seeds and green chilli. Roast.
4. Furthermore, add onion and cook until golden brown. Then add capsicum.
5. Fry on medium flame and after 2-3 minutes add tomato.
6. Stir. Cover and cook for 2 minutes.
7. Now add red chilli powder, haldi and salt. Mix well.
8. Add eggs in the pan and cook them properly.
9. Once the eggs are cooked add poha. Mix well and cover and cook for 2 minutes on low flame.
10. Garnish with chopped coriander leaves and serve.

column24:
1 cup paneer (grated)
2 tbsp carrot (grated)
2 tbsp capsicum (chopped)
2 tbsp boiled corn (optional)
1 tbsp coriander (finely chopped)
¼ tsp kashmiri red chilli powder
¼ tsp cumin powder (jeera powder)
¼ tsp salt
2 tbsp tomato sauce (optional, try avoiding)
4 slice bread (whole wheat/atta bread)
2 tsp  green chutney
2 tsp butter
column25:
1. Firstly, in a large mixing bowl take 1 cup grated paneer and add carrot, capsicum, boiled corn (optional) and 1 tbsp coriander.
2. Additionally, add chilli powder, cumin powder, salt and tomato sauce ( try avoiding sauce).
3. Mix well making sure all the spices are combined well.
4. Now spread green chutney over a bread slice.
5. Furthermore, spread 2 tbsp of prepared paneer stuffing.
6. Cover again with bread slices spread with green chutney.
7. Now grill golden or toast on tawa by spreading butter.
8. Finally, cut half and serve paneer sandwich.

column24:
3 eggs
2 Tablespoon onion
1 teaspoon green chilli
Salt as per taste
1 tablespoon coriander leaves
4 bread slices (atta bread)
1 tablespoon butter
1 tablespoon oil
column25:
1. Take a bowl and add eggs in it.
2. Add chopped onion, green chilli, salt and coriander leaves. Whisk or mix well and keep it aside.
3. Now take a pan and put butter or oil on it to toast the bread pieces.
4. Once done, keep it aside. Now in a pan add oil and pour the egg mixture.
5. Place 2 bread slices on it and cook for 1 minute on low flame.
6. Flip the batter and bread to cook it from the other side and fold. Put 2 more breads and flip again to cook.
7. Once done, divide it between and enjoy.

column25:
1. Take Chana flour/sattu, grated paneer, chopped onion, green chilies, coriander, Kasuri methi, carom seeds, salt, red chili powder, cumin powder, coriander powder, ginger garlic paste, and pickle masala in a bowl and mix well.
2. Now add some water and mix it well.
3. Use prepared dough for the next steps.
4. Divide the dough into small balls. Take each ball and dust it with flour and roll it into a circle.
5. Place about a tsp of sattu mixture in the circle and bring the edges together to seal the filling.
6. Pinch the dough on top and flatten it and dust again with flour if needed.
7. Now Roll it gently into a circle.
8. Heat a Tawa and place the rolled paratha on it.
9. Flip over in a minute and drizzle a tsp of oil.
10. Flip over again in about a minute and drizzle some oil.
11. The paratha is done with both sides cooked and here the paratha is ready to be served.

Serving:2
For the Dough
1 cup Wheat Flour
Salt
2 tbsp Oil
Water
column25:
Let's make the dough first for which add Wheat Flour in the bowl with Salt, Oil. Next, Mix it together properly then add Water now knead the dough nicely (as shown in the video) and let it rest for 10 minutes.
Next, for making the Paratha take a big portion and make the ball add a little dry Wheat flour also on the board. 
Next, start rolling it with the rolling pin brush little bit with Oil then sprinkle it with Dry Wheat flour. Now fold it into half and again fold it another half to make the triangle shape, dip it into the dry wheat flour and start rolling it again (as shown in the video).
Next, roast the paratha into the hot pan on medium flame, cook it on each side for about 20 seconds to apply the oil on both sides while cooking. Do the same with the remaining dough and your Plain Paratha is ready to serve.

1 tsp coconut oil 
10-12 curry leaves 
½ cup soaked mix lentils 
1 small carrot, 
cut into ½ inch pieces
 10-12 French beans, cut into½ inch pieces
 ½ tsp cumin seeds 
Salt to taste 
Tempering 1 tbsp coconut oil
 1 tsp cumin seeds 
1 tsp mustard seeds 
1 large onion sliced
 Salt to taste 
6-7 garlic cloves chopped
 ½ inch ginger piece roughly chopped
 2-3 green chillies chopped
 8-10 curry leaves
column25:
1. Heat 2½ - 3cups water in a deep pan.
2. Dry roast daliya in a pressure cooker for 2 minutes or till fragrant. Add 1 tsp coconut oil, 10-12 curry leaves, ½ cup mix of soaked split skinless red lentil and soaked split skinless green gram, 1 small carrot cut into ½ inch pieces and 10-12 french beans cut into ½ inch pieces, ½ tsp cumin seeds, salt, and mix and fry  for 1-2 minutes. 
3. Add the hot water, mix, increase the flame to high and cook till 1 whistle is given out, reduce the flame to low and cook for 5-7 minutes further. 
4. To make the tempering, heat coconut oil in a non-stick pan, add 1 tsp cumin seeds and mustard seeds 1 tsp and fry for a few seconds. 
5. Add 1 large fresh onion sliced and a pinch of salt, mix and stir for 1 minute. Add 6-7 garlic cloves roughly chopped, ½ inch ginger finely chopped, 2-3 green fresh chillies chopped, 8-10 curry leaves and fry well.
 6. Add ½ tsp Turmeric Powder, ½ tsp red chilli powder, salt and 1 medium chopped fresh red tomato and mix well. Cook for 2-3 minutes. 
7. Mix 10-12 broccolli florets, ½ cup frozen green peas and fry for a minute. Cover and cook for 2 minutes. 
8. Open the cooker once the pressure has reduced completely, transfer the cooked daliya into the pan and mix well. Add ½ cup hot water and mix. 
9. Add a sprinkle of garam masala powder and mix, cover and cook for 1 minute. 
10. Add 2tbsps coriander leaves, mix well and transfer into a serving bowl. sprinkle a little ghee

6- Add 1 cup of finely chopped spinach to it and blend them. 
7- Add 1/2 pinch of Asafoetida, 1/4 teaspoon of carom seeds after crushing it to it. 
8- Add 1/4 teaspoon of red chilli powder, 2 finely chopped deseed green chillies to it.
9- Add 1/2 inch of grated ginger julienne, 1/2 teaspoon of coriander powder, more than 1/2 teaspoon of salt to it and mix them well.

14- Spread the batter on it using a spatula. You can prepare the pancake according to your desired size
15- Cover and  Cook Cheela on the medium flame for 2 to 3 minutes.
16- Spread some oil around its corners.
17- After 3 minutes, remove it from the pan because it has cooked.
18- It takes 5 to 6 minutes to prepare a Cheela.
19- The moong sprout cheela/pancake is ready to be served.

column25:
Method: 
First soak the moong daal and then boil it till its soft. Now take a pan, add ghee and then put all the masalas one by one and mix everything together. Once the stuffing is fried and combined together, mash everything with the help of a masher. Your stuffing is ready. Now take a small portion of the atta dough. 

Make it round and flat in shape from the edges keeping the middle portion thick. Put a generous amount of the stuffing in the middle section of the flat dough and then wrap it from the edges so that all the stuffing should be inside the dough of the paratha. Now make a nice ball shape and sprinkle some flour dust on it and then roll out the dough into a nice flat bread just like roti or Indian bread. Repeat the same. Take a tawa and put it on the flame. Let it hot for some time. Then add the flat bread onto the tawa. Once it is cooked from one side flip it to another side. Put some ghee on the cooked side and then repeat this again on the other side. Your pithiwale parathe is ready. Serve Hot along with curd, green chutney and red chillies. Enjoy!

Preparation Time: 10 minutes 
Cooking Time: 15 minutes 
Makes 6 tikkis 

Ingredients: 
1 cup sprouted moong (whole green gram) 
3 tbsp chopped coriander (dhania) 
3 tbsp chopped mint leaves (phudina) 
1 tbsp besan (bengal gram flour) 
salt to taste 
a pinch asafoetida (hing) 
2 tsp green chilli paste 
1 tbsp chopped coriander (dhania) for rolling 
1 tbsp chopped mint leaves (phudina) for rolling 
1 tsp oil for greasing and cooking
column25:
Method 
1. Blend the sprouted moong along with little water in a mixer to a smooth paste. 
2. Transfer it to a bowl, add the coriander, mint leaves, besan, salt, asafoetida and green chilli paste and mix well. 
3. Divide the mixture into 6 equal portions and roll out each portion into 50 mm. (2") round flat thin tikkis. 
4. Roll each tikki in mint leaves and coriander, till they are covered from all the sides. 
5. Heat a non-stick tava (griddle), and cook each tikki, using 1/8 tsp oil, till they turn golden brown in colour from both the sides. 
Serve immediately.

Prep time: 10-15 minutes 
Cooking time 15-20 minutes 
Serves: 3-4 people 

Ingredients: 
POHA | पोहा 3 CUPS 
OIL | तेल 2-3 TBSP 
CUMIN SEEDS | जीरा 1/2 TSP 
MUSTARD SEEDS | राई 1/2 TSP 
GREEN CHILLI | हरी मिर्च 2 NOS. 
CURRY LEAVES| कड़ी पत्ते 10-12 
PEANUTS | मूंगफली 2 TBSP 
POTATO | आलू 2 MEDIUM SIZED (DICED) 
ONION | प्याज़ 1 NO. (CHOPPED) 
SUGAR | शक्कर 1 TSP
SALT | नमक TO TASTE 
TURMERIC POWDER | हल्दी पाउडर 1/2 TSP 
FRESH CORIANDER | हरा धनिया A SMALL HANDFUL 
LEMON JUICE | निंबू का रस 1 TSP 
WATER | पानी A SPLASH 
FRESH CORIANDER | हरा धनिया A SMALL HANDFUL (CHOPPED)
column25:
Method: 
In a large bowl add the poha, make sure that the poha that you are using are of the thick variety & they should be old. 
Add water into the bowl & gently wash the poha by mixing them in the water, then immediately strain the poha using a sieve, let the poha rest in the sieve for 8-10 minutes. 
While the poha is resting you can start the further cooking process. 
Set a pan over high flame, once the pan gets hot, add the oil & heat it well. 
Further add cumin seeds, mustard seeds, green chill, curry leaves & peanuts, mix well & cook over low flame briefly & then add the potatoes. 
Cook the potatoes over high flame until they are half cooked, make sure you half cook the potatoes before adding the onions, if you add potatoes & onion together then the onions will get overcooked.
Once the potatoes are half done, add in the chopped onion & sugar, stir well & cook until the onion turns almost light golden brown over high flame. 
When the onion turns almost light golden brown the potatoes will also be cooked perfectly, lower the flame at this stage & add salt & turmeric powder, mix well & add the soaked poha along with fresh coriander & lemon juice, stir everything very gently. 
Further add a splash of water over the poha & cover the pan with a lid, switch off the flame & let the poha rest for 3-4 minutes, following this step will ensure that the poha turns out to be very moist & fluffy due to the steam. 
Remove the lid after 3-4 minutes & sprinkle some freshly chopped coriander. 
Your batata poha is ready, garnish with some grated coconut while serving.

column24:
Ingredients 
1 cup rice flour 
Salt to taste 
Thecha to serve (Optional)
column25:
Method 
1. Bring 1 cup water to a boil in a deep non-stick pan, add salt and mix. 
2. Add rice flour and mix, cover and steam on low heat for 2-3 minutes. Take the pan off the heat and transfer the dough onto a large plate. 
3. Knead the dough using a small stainless steel bowl till it cools slightly. Once the dough is warm, start kneading with your hands till a smooth and soft dough is formed. 
4. Divide the dough into equal portions and shape each portion into a ball. 
5. Dust the worktop with rice flour, place the dough ball on it, dust a little rice flour on top and roll it into a thin bhakri. 
6. Heat a non-stick tawa, place the bhakri on it and cook for 1-2 minutes, flip and gently press with a wooden press or till the bhakri puffs up. Take it off the heat. 
7. Arrange the bhakris on a serving plate and serve hot with thecha.

1 tsp Mustard Seeds 
3 Green Chillies 
6-7 Curry Leaves 
1/4th tsp Turmeric Powder 
1 1/2 tsp Red Chilli Powder 
1 tsp Goda Masala 
1/2 tsp Garam Masala 
1 1/2 tbsp Jaggery (Optional)
Coriander Leaves 
Salt to taste 
Water
column25:
Method: 
- In a pressure cooker add matki and water. Cook the matki on 1 whistle. 
- In a mixer grinder add grated coconut, ginger & tamarind. Grind everything to a fine paste. Keep this mixture aside. 
- In a pan, heat some oil. 
- Add asafoetida, mustard seeds, green chillies and curry leaves. 
- Add the cooked matki and mix well. 
- Add the coconut mixture and again mix well. 
- Then add turmeric powder, red chilli powder, goda masala & garam masala. Mix well. - Add jaggery, salt to taste and water. Mix well. 
- Cover it with a lid for 2 minutes. Once the usal starts boiling, switch off the flame. 
- Garnish it with coriander leaves and serve hot!

column25:
Instructions

In a pan, heat 2 tablespoons of oil and add half of the raw vermicelli. Lightly fry the vermicelli noodles until they turn golden brown, about 5 minutes. Constantly stir with a wooden spoon, so the vermicelli do not burn.
    Then add a large volume of water to boil the fried vermicelli. Once the water starts to boil, add the rest of raw vermicelli and cook for just 3 minutes. Drain vermicelli in a colander.
    Add butter, cardamom, sugar and diluted saffron to the pan. Mix and heat until sugar is dissolved for about 6 to 8 minutes.
    Add vermicelli back to the pan, mix and cook for an additional 2 minutes.
    Heat 3 tablespoons vegetable oil in a separate pan. Add the beaten eggs. Tilt the pan in order to spread the uncooked egg. When dry on top, flip the omelet over and cook for an additional minute.
    Serve vermicelli with omelette on top.

column25:
Instructions
    Heat 3 tablespoon olive oil in a large cast iron skillet. Add the onions, green peppers, garlic, spices, pinch salt and pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until the vegetables have softened, about 5 minutes.
    Add the tomatoes and tomato sauce. Cover and let simmer for about 15 minutes. Uncover and cook a bit longer to allow the mixture to reduce and thicken. Taste and adjust the seasoning to your liking.
    Using a wooden spoon, make 6 indentations, or "wells," in the tomato mixture (make sure the indentations are spaced out). Gently crack an egg into each indention.
    Reduce the heat, cover the skillet, and cook on low until the egg whites are set.
    Uncover and add the fresh parsley and mint. You can add more black pepper or crushed red pepper, if you like. Serve with warm pita, challah, or crusty bread of your choice.

column24:
Prep – 5 minutes 
Cook – 1 hour 
Quick Soaking 1 hour

Ingredients:
    ▢ 1 pound dry chickpeas, approximately 2 cups dry chickpeas
    ▢ ½ to 1 teaspoon baking soda, depending on the cooking mehtod
    ▢ water
    ▢ Kosher salt
    ▢ 1 to 2 bay leaves
    ▢ 2 garlic cloves, lightly smashed
column25:
Instructions:

    Prepare the chickpeas for cooking. Simply look through the beans and discard any rocks or anything that does not look like a chickpea. 

Stovetop Method

    Soak the chickpeas. You can either soak them overnight or try the quick soaking method. To soak overnight, put the chickpeas in a large bowl and add plenty of water to cover the chickpeas by a good 3 inches. Set aside for 24 hours. For the quick soak method, put the chickpeas in a pot and add 6 cups of water. Bring to a boil and cook for 2 minute. Turn the heat off, cover and let the chickpeas soak for 1 hour. Drain.
    In a large cooking pot, put the chickpeas and 1 teaspoon of baking soda. Cook over medium-high heat, tossing constantly for about 3 to 4 minutes. Add 7 cups of water to cover the beans by several inches. Season with a big pinch of kosher salt (about 1 teaspoon or more if you like). Add the bay leaf and garlic. Bring to a boil, then turn the heat down and simmer, skimming off any foam or skins that float to the top. Chickpeas will cook anywhere from 40 minutes to 1 ½ hour or until tender (cooking time will vary depending on the type and freshness of the chickpeas). 

Slow Cooker Method

    In a 2 ½-quart slow cooker, put the chickpeas, ½ teaspoon baking soda, 7 cups water, a big pinch of kosher salt, bay leaf, and garlic. Cover and cook on high heat for 4 hours, or low heat for 6 to 8 hours, or until tender. 

Pressure Cooker Method

    Add the chickpeas and 6 cups of water to the pressure cooker. Seal the lid shut. Select High Pressure and cook for 50 minutes. Allow the pressure cooker to naturally release for 10 minutes, then vent the remaining pressure and when the release valve drops, safely open the lid. (Be sure to review the pressure cooker manual before use and follow all safety precautions).

    Lightly brown the other side (the edges will start curling up).

column24:
Ingredients
For the rice: 

    1 kg Basmati rice

    75 gms local ghee

    2 tbsp salt

    2 ½ tbsp Machbous spices mix

    75 gms tomato paste

    15 gms chopped coriander

    2 to 3 whole dried lemons

    1 ½ kgs chopped tomatoes

    80 gms chopped onions

    1.5 l chicken stock

    1 tsp Bezar spice (Emirati spice mix)

    3 to 4 bay leaves

For the chicken: 

    3 kgs Fresh chicken (cut in quarters)

    20 gms saffron

    3 tsp salt

    1 tsp Bezar spice (Emirati spice mix)

    1 tsp tbsp Machbous spice mix (store bought)

    2 kg Emirati ghee

    1 tsp turmeric powder

    2 tbsp lemon juice

For garnishing:

    Fried cashew nuts

    Crispy fried onions

    Fried pine nuts

    Chopped coriander

    2 to 3 dates
column25:
Method

Cooking the chicken:

1. In a baking tray, place the chicken and add all the spices on the top. Mix well to coat the chicken thoroughly. (Here's a recipe for making Bezar - an Emirati spice mix).

2. Roast in a preheated oven for 20 minutes at 180 °C.

Making the rice:

1. Wash the rice and let it to soak for 30 minutes.

2. Heat a pot with local ghee. Add the chopped onions and dried lemons, and sauté until the onions are golden brown in colour.

3. Add the spices, tomato paste, chopped tomatoes, chopped coriander and sauté together.

4. Add water to the pot and bring it to a boil then add the rice and bring it to a boil again, and cook till the water has reduced and the rice is almost cooked.

5. Cover the pot with a lid and keep aside for 20 minutes to finish cooking in the residual heat.

6. Once cooked, place the cooked chicken on top of the rice and garnish with the onions, nuts, coriander and dates.

column24:
Prep Time: 10 minutes
Cook Time: 50 minutes 
Total Time: 1 hour
Servings: 8 servings

Ingredients
For the meat:
    ▢ 1.5 kilogram bone in lamb shoulder or leg, medium pieces (veal is also a good option)
    ▢ 2 tablespoons vegetable oil
    ▢ 3 medium onions diced
    ▢ 3 dried limes (optional)
    ▢ 3 cinnamon sticks
    ▢ 3 bay leaves
    ▢ 6 green cardamom pods
    ▢ 5 whole cloves
    ▢ 1.5 teaspoon salt
    ▢ ½ teaspoon ground cinnamon
    ▢ ½ teaspoon ground cardamom
    ▢ ½ teaspoon ground black pepper
    ▢ ½ cup tomato sauce
    ▢ 2 tablespoons tomato paste
    ▢ 4 cups water

For the rice:
    ▢ 3 cups basmati rice
    ▢ 1 teaspoon salt
    ▢ 4.5 cups broth

For the Garnish:
▢ ½ cup slivered almonds
▢ 2 tablespoons olive oil
▢ ½ cup raisins
column25:
Instructions
For the meat:

    Start by peeling, washing and dicing the onions.
    Next, in a non-stick pot (or in the instant pot), sauté the onions until soft and lightly brown, for about 7 minutes, on medium heat.
    Next, in the same pot with the onions inside, sear the lamb pieces for a few minutes on each side. Don't worry if the pot is crowded, aim to get some colour on the meat.
    Next, add the whole spices and the ground spices to the pot with the meat and onions and cook for a few minutes.
    Next, add the tomato paste and cook for a few minutes.
    Add the tomato sauce and the water to the pot, and now you have the option to cook the meat on the stove top or the pressure cooker.
    For the pressure cooker (or instant pot), pressure cook for 20 minutes. Manually release the pressure and move on to the next step.
    For the stove top, cook on medium high heat for approximately 60 minutes until the meat is very tender, making sure to replenish the water as required.
    Once the meat is soft, remove it from the broth and place it in a plate to the side. Strain the broth from the onions and whole spices.

For the rice:
    While the meat is cooking, wash the rice until liquid runs clear, then soak it for 30 minutes.
    Layer the meat at the bottom of the pot that you will cook the rice in (this can be the same pot you used for the meat if you cooked it on the stove top).
    Then, pour over the meat broth that you strained, making sure that you use exactly 4.5 cups (for 3 cups of rice). If you don't have enough broth, just top it up with water. If you have too much broth, save it for a future use.
    Place the pot onto high heat for 5 minutes until liquid is bubbling.
    Place a paper towel over the pot, then cover it with a tight-fitting lid and simmer on low heat for 25 minutes.
    After 25 minutes, turn the heat off and fluff it with a fork.
    Toast the almonds on medium heat in the olive oil, stirring frequently until lightly golden. Remove and add the raisins in the same skillet for 1-2 minutes until warmed through.
    Serve in a large platter by adding a layer of the rice and meat, then garnishing with almonds, raisins, and finely chopped parsley if desired. Enjoy!

column24:
Prep Time: 15 minutes
Cook Time: 2 hours

Ingredients
Kabsa spice mix:

    1/4 tsp ground cardamom (cardamom powder)
    1/4 tsp ground white pepper (white pepper powder)
    1/4 tsp saffron
    1/2 tsp ground cinnamon (cinnamon powder)
    1/2 tsp ground all spice
    1/2 tsp dried whole lime powder

Chicken kabsa:

    2 tbsp oil or butter
    3 onions, sliced
    1 tbsp minced ginger (ginger paste)
    1 tbsp minced garlic (garlic paste)
    1 green chili
    2 dried bay leaves
    6 cloves
    4 cardamom pods
    1 cinnamon stick
    2 tbsp tomato puree (tomato paste)
    1 pinch ground nutmeg (nutmeg powder)
    1/2 tsp ground black pepper (black pepper powder)
    1/4 tsp ground cumin (cumin powder)
    1/2 tsp ground coriander (coriander powder)
    3 medium carrots, thinly sliced
    200 g canned diced tomatoes (or 3 tomatoes chopped)
    2 chicken stock cubes
    1 1/2 kg whole chicken, cut into 6 pieces
    3 cups basmati rice, rinsed
    1/4 cup raisins
    Water
    Salt to taste
    Raisins, to garnish (optional)
    Slivered almonds, to garnish (optional)
column25:
Instructions:

    To make kabsa spice mix, combine together cardamom, white pepper, saffron, cinnamon, all spice and lime powder in a bowl. Set aside.
    Heat oil in a large heavy bottomed pan over medium-high heat. Add onions, ginger, garlic and green chilies. Sauté for 2-3 minutes or until the onions turn golden brown. Add bay leaves, cloves, cardamom pods and cinnamon stick. Fry for a minute.
    Stir in tomato purée. Add ground nutmeg, ground black pepper, ground cumin, ground coriander and kabsa spice. Season with salt. Fry the spices for a minute. Add carrots and diced tomatoes. Stir, and cook for 2 minutes.
    Add chicken cubes and chicken pieces. Brown chicken, turning occasionally, for about 30 minutes. Remove the chicken pieces from the pan. Set aside.
    Add rice and raisins. Pour in 4 cups water. Season with salt. Bring it to the boil. Reduce the heat, cover with lid, and simmer for 10-15 minutes.
    Preheat grill. Grill chicken for 10-15 minutes or until cooked through. Serve rice with grilled chicken.

    2. Add tomato paste and bullion cube to pan, cook a little then add rice and water. Carefully place fish mixture on top. Raise heat to high and allow to come to a full boil, cover and reduce to low. Allow to cook until rice and fish are thoroughly cooked. Prepare Chicken Broth:

Prepare Dejaj Salona:

column24:

How to make it?

column24:

Cook Time 25 minutes

column25:
Instructions

    Peel and chop the pumpkin. Boil in water till the pumpkin is soft. Strain and set aside.
    Grind the pumpkin, honey, cardamom and saffron into a smooth paste.
    Heat ghee in a saucepan. Roast the flour on low flame, stirring occassionally till the flour is well roasted and smells nutty.
